deck_excerpt: Cyberse (サイバース Saibāsu) is a Type of monster. This Type is used by Yusaku Fujiki, Varis, Bohman, BitBoot, Takeru Homura, Earth, Windy, Lightning, Haru
deck_description: Cyberse (サイバース Saibāsu) is a Type of monster. This Type is used by Yusaku Fujiki, Varis, Bohman, BitBoot, Takeru Homura, Earth, Windy, Lightning, Haru, Skye Zaizen, Ai, and Pandorin Yu-Gi-Oh! VRAINS. Appearance-wise, they resemble creatures and humanoids strongly connected to elements of digital technology and cyberspace. At times though, they tend to resemble either Insect, Machineor Psychic monsters (the humanoids bearing design elements from the TRONfranchise). The name is a portmanteau of "Cyber" (サイバー Saibā) and "Universe" (ユニバース Yunibāsu).  Their general theme revolves around swarming the field with weak monsters to easily Link Summon powerful Link Monsters, and they also have lots of monsters that gain effects when banished in a similar vein to Psychic monsters.

deck_excerpt: Pre Toon Chaos but who have thought Toon is a Halq engine by itself and the endboard with Herald of the Arc Light sets the follow up with Relinquished
deck_description: Toon is very similar to Malefic, because its just a new approach to already existing popular cards, but it allows us to run those popular cards support to fetch the Toons, making it more consistent and has more tools. The combo is we make 2 lv7 on field and overlay it to Ebon Illusion Magician to fetch our tuner Magicalibra for Halqifibrax combo. Toon Dark Magician and Toon Red-Eyes Black Dragon easily accompolish that, so we play to turbo both. Cards like The Black Stone of Legend (our main normal summon, ss Red-Eyes from deck), Magicians Souls (fetches Toon DM to gy or ss og DM as lv7 fodder), Toon Table of Contents (adds any Toon, mostly Toon DM as Toon Red-Eyes can summon it from hand), Where Arf Thou (works with both Black Stone and Magicians Souls), One for One, Dark Magic Veil (ss dark spellcaster from hand or gy, works with DM lineup), and lastly Tenyi Adhara (tuner lv1) or Vishuda (lv7 with bounce effect). The Halqifibrax combo with Borreload Savage Dragon and Herald of the Arc Light is very suitable to this deck as it only uses small extra deck space and can search Relinquished lineup as follow up play. Fusion lineup is for either Eyes Restrict or Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon (since we run og DM, I think Dragoon is the best addition here), being Instant Fusion and Magicalized Fusion (Millenium-Eyes Restrict or Dragoon). Not only that, Dark Magic Veil can revive both Eyes Restrict and Dragoon too. We also use spellcaster support like Selene for Accescode since the Toon spell easily dump 3 spells and we run bunch of spellcaster anyway. Can put in Chimeratech Megafleet too as we have Toon Cyber Dragon. Toon Briefcase is just another search target and we can make it online if we have Toon monster for spare. Kaiju works well too, either as Relinquished fodder or lv7 xyz material. Imduk is there to utilize og DM with Magicalized Fusion for Dragoon. We dont play the Toon Kingdom lineup as it banishes 3 cards from deck (we have combo pieces) and while its protection effect is good, sitting on Toon monsters aint good enough. Relinquished also clashes with Toon as Relinquished is super good going second while most of the Toons cant atk the turn they are summoned, so this deck is made to synergize both Relinquished and Toon. Pros: Themed, good board setup with follow up, consistency is borderline acceptable. Cons: Board is easily broken, lack of recursion, both Toon DM and Red-Eyes cant atk the turn it is summoned and only have moderate atk as beater.

deck_excerpt: More handtraps then you'd ever think you'd need!
deck_description: It's Shaddolls but it has more hand traps and disruption then you'd ever think you'd need. The deck can go first or second, but in my experience, it's probably best just to go first and try to prevent your opponent from building an unstoppable board.  There's definitely some room for experimentation here! For example, you may consider running the wind invoked monster in place of Apollousa or Dweller. Or maybe you want to do the whole buster lock thing with Union Carrier.  The deck can be super strong and in the right hands keep up with the best! It's a fun deck and people will be happy to take a break from all the Eldies and Rock People. Have fun with it and let me know if you have any cool ideas to help refine the list!

deck_excerpt: Brotherhood of the Fire Fist deck with Lightsworn engine
deck_description: Pure Fire Fist in my opinion was a bit too bricky so I tried to find a good engine for them. The best I could come up with was Lightsworns since they have couple of Beast-Warriors to go for Eagle and use as material for Swan. They can also mill cards to grave which helps with Eagle's, Panda's and Dragon's effects. The spells can also mill Wulf which makes summoning arguably the most improtant card of the deck, Eagle, easier. I first tried using Luminas instead of Aurkus, Lightsworn Monk but kept constantly wanting Lumina to be a Beast-Warrior type so I changed it. I think adding the Lightsworns made the deck brick less and make better combos but it is still quite bricky and starting the combos needs a bit too much resources compared to some meta decks for example. Hence the lack of hand traps and other generic protection and destruction cards. Replays: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lLuc22l4xps

deck_excerpt: Bait out hand traps with gallant and doki then go for halq combo and make an oppressive board.
deck_description: Your primary goal with this deck is to try and turbo out Halqifibrax after your opponent has used their hand trap and before you Normal Summon. Ideally you need to go first, this deck will struggle vs an established board. If you can make Gallant Granite before Halq, do it and the opponent will be forced to negate it. Gallant and Doki are cards the opponent are forced to negate otherwise they'll give you too much advantage. If you can resolve Halq then go for Martial Metal Marcher combos and it should be off to the races. You're playing 4 copies of Block Dragon, try and hold it as long as possible or use it as material for an Apollousa. Block Dragon is how you're pushing through hand traps, without Block Dragon you're likely to lose. Worst case scenario, you can attach it using Union Carrier but you more want to save Carrier to attach Buster Dragon to force the opponent to scoop. The ideal end board should comprise of: Apollousa of at least 3 negates, Union Carrier, I:P Masquerena, Herald of the Arc Light, Savage Dragon with 2 counters and Buster Dragon attached, Dweller with Tackle Crusader as material, and Block Dragon to be used with I:P to make unicorn which will then be co-linked with Carrier to go +4.     Game 2 Side in the hand traps and try to block the opponent's combo as best you can. You have 14 hand traps to work with, all of which can either block Halq Combos or stop Auroradon/Linkross combos, so use them wisely. Game 3 side in exchange to get rid of dark ruler or anything else that can threaten your board. Toughest matchup is the mirror since its very die roll dependent. Its not impossible to win going second vs the mirror but its quite an uphill battle if you dont open imperm or nibiru.

control deck

The general strategy of this deck is to combo up to trigate wizard with all 3 co-links on turn one, negating your opponent's critical play. On turn two, OTK with either Crusadia Avramax or Accesscode Talker. To achieve this, you'll want to start your combo off with lady debug and micro coder. Search out cynet codec, and combo up to trigate with the use of extenders. This deck is a variation on a deck list shown here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uqM1EUxhovo&t=780s

Eldlich Zombies deck. The goal is to be a Zombies deck, running Eldlich cards as a control engine. It means running 2 card combos instead of Jet Synchron, and makes the routing a little heavy on extra deck space, but the deck has follow-up and interactions for days. Let's begin. 3 Uni-Zombie and 2 Shiranui Solitaire make up an eighth of the deck, meaning odds are we'll see them in our top 8 cards. These numbers are run because with 6 it always feels like you see 2 too often. These form a 2 card combo with any of Zombie World, Glow-Up Bloom, or Necroworld Banshee. 2 Banshee and 2 Glow-Up Bloom give us access to Zombie world in the case of banshee, and the choice of Doomking Balerdroch or Eldlich the Golden Lord from Glow-Up Bloom. These numbers help ensure you see the combo reasonably often, and makes follow-up plays possible. 2 Doomking Balerdroch are the maindeck boss monsters, and make a Halquifibrax combo that ends on 3 interactions plus Zombie World. Vampire Fraulein is an OTK with Dragonecro, in addition to being a level 5 combo piece and defensive hand trap. Worth it as a 1 of in the Zombie build, because you can summon it with Eldlixers, and pure Zombies plays it anyways. Rivalry of Warlords locks people out of playing non-zombie monsters with Zombie World, and is basically a Zombie card. Super Poly is likewise a zombie card, and is a 1 of to search it with Predaplant Verte Anaconda to make Dragonecro super poly as a link 2, just a 3rd line of play that's good going second, basically. 3 Zombie World is essential, half of our deck only works if this card is on the field, so playing 3 with everyone running Cosmic Cyclone for Eldlich seems like a good idea. For the Eldlich half of the deck, we have pretty standard numbers with some minor trims for deckspace reasons. 3 Golden Lord is pretty standard. Zombies plays 2 of these anyways, and we need to have more Golden Lords than we do Eldlich cards in a game. They're gonna get banished so 3 is essential in my opinion. 3 Cursed Eldland is insane, if find you Golden Lord, it finds you other interaction, it sets up your GY, this card is also nuts with Performapal Popperup going first. It's also one of the Eldlich combo extenders needed for second string follow-ups / alternatives. 3 Scarlet Sanguine, but only 2 Black Awakening and 1 White Destiny. Different names are important, as is recuring zombie threats such as golden lord and Balerdroch. These 6 cards are all also extenders in second string plays. 2 each of Conquistador and Huaquero is pretty standard, these are the meat of the deck, and combo pieces. 1 Golden Land Forever gives us a searchable omni-negate, good in games when you just go off on turn one, and pretty okay in middling games as well. I'd run 2, but space is tight. 3 Performapal Popperup is our card draw of choice. I know it works well in Eldlich, and it definitely has synergies in Zombies. Drawing 3 cards deeper into the deck while pitching cards for fun and profit leads to some extreme highs, and it can mitigate middling hands as a mulligan in a pinch. Better than Souls' here because we want to pitch monsters about as often as spells/traps. Mecha Phantom Beast O-Lion is a brick, but it makes the Herald+Raptite combo possible. Ghost Ogre is not a complete brick, but it here to be an extra interruption off of Needlefibre. Easy money. We even make the Ghost Girl a ghost with Zombie World. Extra deck space is tight. 3 Needlefibre are essential. 2 are used in the deck's main combo, and 1 is used in follow-up plays. Linkuriboh makes Glow-Up Bloom into full combo with Zombie World, which just increases the odds of seeing 2 card Needlefibre combos more often. Linkross, Martial Metalmarcher, and Wonder Magician go into Borreload Savage on your opponent's turn + Herald of the Arc Light on yours, plus maybe a spell/trap pop with Wonder Magician out of our 2 card Needlefibres. The second engine is a 3 card combo, but a fairly redundant one to put together, which ends on Ghost Ogre + Huquero/Conquistador interruption + Dawn Dragster on their turn, which draws a card off Formula Synchron. You can even use Fraulein for added consistency. The last string of plays is Predaplant Verte Anaconda to Super Poly their monsters into Dragonecro. I'd love to run more of these, but space is sooo tight in the main and extra. Train cards eventually win games by OTKs. Red Splatter makes this much easier. Combo 1 can be done with a bunch of cards, but for simplicity, we'll focus on Uni-Zombie + Zombie World.
  1. Play Zombie World
  2. Play Uni-Zombie
  3. Send Glow-Up Bloom to GY
  4. Banish Bloom, ss Balerdroch
  5. Link Balerdroch and Uni-Zombie into Needlefibre, ss O-Lion.
  6. Link Needlefibre in Linkross, ss 2 tokens.
  7. Synchro O-Lion and a token into Martial Metalmarcher. O-lion chain 2, Marcher chain 1, ss token, ss Uni-Zombie.
  8. Synchro Marcher + level 3 token into Raptite with O-lion in the GY. Synchro Herald of the Arclight.
  9. During opponents standby phase ss Balerdroch.
Zombie World locks you out of Auroradon. Combo 2 involves previously mentioned Zombie cards plus a bunch of combinations of Eldlich cards. For simplicity, we'll use Uni-Zombie, Zombie World, and Red Splatter.
  1. Play Zombie World
  2. Normal Summon Uni-Zombie. Send Glow-Up Bloom to the GY.
  3. Banish Glow-Up Bloom, ss Golden Lord.
  4. Link Uni-Zombie and Golden Lord into Needlefibre, ss Ghost Ogre.
  5. Set Red Eldlixir.
  6. ss Golden Lord, send red splatter to the GY.
  7. Banish Red Eldlixir for your choice of Conquistador and Huaquero.
  8. Opponents turn you have Ghost Ogre, an Eldlich Trap, and you can banish Needlefibre to ss Formula Synchron, draw a card, and synchro it and the level 5 monster into Dawn Dragster for a negate.
The third-string play is just Super Poly out of Verte Anaconda, a power play for sure and great going second to break boards. Profile already changed. Basically I'm trying to make the grind game more consistent.

deck_excerpt: This Tindangle deck isn't exactly Meta, but can still pull off loads of wombo-combos if set-up correctly. If anything goes wrong like effects get nega
deck_description: To start a good 1st turn combo if you have a foolish burial, you have a good start, so foolish a Tindangle Intruder, then trigger Tindangle Jhrelth to discard any Tindangle's in your hand and deck(Discard a Tindangle Protector or DHoles.) to special SET it. Next you use DHoles ability to revive the other Tindangle(NOT Intruder or DHoles), then Intruder will chain the effect and will special summon itself in face down position. You should have 3 face down monsters. Then you activate Nagel's Protection to make your Tindangles's invincible to your opponents card effects.Finally End your Turn. When your opponents monster attacks the Tindangle, make sure they attack the Jhrelth or Intruderr to flip them face up and add 2 Tindangle monster's from your deck to your hand. FYI Your opponent can flip Protecter to trigger its search effect that will flip all the Tindangle's and search even more cards.(About 3 if used correctly.) Then you want to activate your searched Jhrelth to discard the TRAP Tindangle Delaunay to then activate Delaunay's effect to banish itself  to summon back the destroyed Tindangle's last turn. But if they negated it, don't worry, just stall out for one turn. Use Trinity since he is immune to battle. Then activate the Tindangle Delaunay that was previously negated(If it wasn't just LINK Summon Tindangle Acute Cerberus just make sure to put Tindangle Base Gardna in the GY.) to summon DHoles, Jhrelth, Protector and Intruder. Wait for your opponent to do their turn. When they're done, you want to flip Protector face up to reveal the rest of the Tindangle's to draw 3 cards. Next, activate Jhrelth's effect to search any Tindangle. After That, you can LINK Summon Acute Cerberus. If you use Trinity as one of the materials you can search a Gergonne's End and discard a Euler's Circuit to the GY, then activate Euler's Circuit to banish itself and discard 1 Tindangle in your hand to serach another Euler's Circuit and then activate the field spell to make it where your opponent cannot attack you if you control 3 or more Tindangle monsters which you probably already have with a lot of set-up.(Also you should activate a Nagel's Protection along with the wombo-combo you did to put a lot of Tindangle's in the GY especially Base Gardna.)When you activate Nagel and you attack with Acute Cerberus doing double damage and could OTK if u have 2 Tindangle's CO-LINKED to Acute Ceberus. Although it seems like a tough deck to set-up since this is a flip deck. You can actually pull off some NEAT Wombo-Combo's. deck_description:
Step by Step Tutorial for a Basic Hero Combo:   Hand: Vision HERO Faris, Solemn Judgment, Mask Change, Evil HERO Adusted Gold, Elemental HERO Shadow Mist  
  1. Special Summon Faris by discarding Shadow Mist (don't activate Shadow Mists effect just yet)
  2. Place Vision HERO Increase from your Deck in your Spell/Trap Zone.
  3. Summon Increase by putting Faris in the GY.
  4. Special Summon Vision HERO Vyon from your Deck and activate his effect to mill Destiny HERO - Malicious
  5. Special Summon a new Malicious with his effect from Deck by banishing him from the GY.
  6. Link Malicious and Increase to Xtra HERO - Cross Crusader and Special Summon Malicious from Grave by his effect.
  7. Use Cross Crusaders Effect to send Malicious to the GY and get Elemental HERO Liquid Soldier in your Hand
  8. Normal Summon Liquid Soldier and revive Shadow Mist to get another Mask Change into your Hand
  9. Use Mask Change on Shadow Mist to summon Dark Law
  10. Activate Evil HERO Adusted Golds effect to get Dark Calling.
  11. Activate Dark Calling by banishing Adusted Gold and Faris to summon Evil HERO Malicious Edge
  12. Activate Mask Change to Summon Masked HERO Acid
  13. Set down Solemn Judgment and attack or pass depending on the game state/turn.

deck_excerpt: Most consistent "meta" build for Winged Dragon of Ra
deck_description:
So you wanna devote yourself to the Sun itself? This is the most consistent build you will find. Once more i searched the web trying to find a good decklist for this deck, i didn't find the perfect one, so i had to make one myself. Servants of the Sun:
  • Before you summon your Egyptian God you need to summon his pawns, for that you have Sangan, the starter of the Deck, if you don't open your hand with him don't worry, Tour Guide Of The Underworld searches it for you.
  • When you dump Sangan for a Link Summon be it Almiraj or Masquerena you will search for Arboria, your extender. Then you will make the most boring combo nowadays and abuse Halqifibrax.
  • Arboria Special Summons itself from your hand, so you Link into Halqi, Summon O-Lion from your deck, Link Halqi into Linkross, Synchro Summon the Level 3 Metal Marcher and Special Summon Arboria from the GY.
  • With the Token summoned by O-Lion, you go into Union Carrier, target Arboria in your field and equip Guardian Slime to her, there's still one Level 1 Token left, so you Synchro Summon Hastorr for maximum ATK Points and Monster Steal or Arc Light for the negate, thus dumping Guardian Slime and enabling you to search any card that supports Ra.
  • You can also use Crystal Girl, to search for Guardian Slime. One for One facilitates that.
  • Temple of the Kings allows you to activate Metal Reflect Slime in the same turn it is set, so you can summon Ra more easily.
Bringing the Sun to the battlefield:
  • Now that the offerings are in your field, you can use them as tributes for the Sun God, there are a lot of scenarios that can happen, the most common one is that you search Ancient Chant with the Guardian Slime you just dumped, bring Ra to your hand and summon him.
  • If you go first you will want to summon Sphere Mode before bringing Ra to the field so you don't spend your LP.
  • If you already have Ancient Chant in your hand you can go for Millenium Revelation, so you can search for Monster Reborn if needed or even One With The Sun God so if anything happens to Ra, you gain your LP back.
Become one with the flames and bear the name of Phoenix:
  • You also cannot forget that you have Immortal Phoenix in your deck, and there are a two ways of sending it to the GY. One of them and the best one is Millenium Revelation, discard Phoenix and search Monster Reborn.
  • You can also discard it for the effect of One for One in order to summon Crystal Girl.
  • When you have it there your GY is set up as well. If Ra goes to the GY by any means, Immortal Phoenix rises from its ashes and allows you to destroy your opponent's field. One With The Sun God allows you to do that
  Some extra explanations:
  • Instant Fusion allows you to bring Theseus a tuner to the field, so you can make Halqifibrax most of the time.
  • Mound of the Bound Creator offers extra protection to your Winged Dragon of Ra.
  • Life Absorbing Machine can be replaced.
  • Don't forget Blaze Cannon you can search it with Guardian Slime and it can decide the duel.
  Any suggestions or questions leave it down below. Also you can check my profile in Dueling Book, it's _Theseus. Now burn your opponent with the Sun itself, and make sure they become a Sun God devotee as well!
youtube link - https://youtu.be/tYMXgD0fvpk

deck_excerpt: Powerful beasts that will destroy your opponents!
deck_description: Thought Id come back and revisit this deck. Haven't really played Yu-Gi-Oh in a while, but this little patch should clear up a good part of the deck clutter that I experienced with it.  A really few really nice combos I discovered while play-testing.  You can summon 'Silent Wobby' to your opponents side of the field, and not only do you gain 2000 life-points, wobby also acts as fodder to start that kaiju brawl.  if you start with 'Owner's Seal in your hand, you can instead of Special Summoning two kaijus, summon 1 to your opponent's side of the field then retake control of it leaving your opponent theoretically defenseless.  In the current META due to 20 minute long combos that involve lots of tributing and discarding and effect activating getting 'Kyoutou Waterfront' out on the field is essential!  'Neo-Spacian Grand Mole' can make a pretty nifty loop combo, by tributing your opponents boss monster to summon a kaiju before sp. summoining your own and normal summoning 'Grand Mole', you can attack your opponent's kaiju with 'Grand Mole' and send it back to your hand leaving them without a boss monster, you can continue this loop almost infinitely.  KUMONGOUS. IS. IMPORTANT. negating your opponent's ability to activate effects and attack in this current META is the best thing you can do, it can and will cancel their combo's leaving them wide open. if you find yourself against an overly effect reliant deck such as sky-strikers, time lords or subterrors Kumongous can throw off their entrie strategy, and paired with Kyoutou Waterfront, is really self sustainable.  Be mindful when summoning Gameciel to your opponents side of the field. Yes, he is the weakest Kaiju monster stat wise but thats a balancing chip with him. If there are readily accesible kaiju counters while once you've summoned Gameicel its better to take him out first before going for any potentially game ending effects (like Dogoran's).

deck_excerpt: Turn 1 Complete lockdown: Opponent cannot activate spells, traps, or monster effects.
deck_description: Most underrated thing I've ever seen. Will explain how it works if asked but after reading each card and playing around with it its self evident.  Board Possibilities:  1) Simorgh Link, Apex Avian, Barrier Statute, Harpie's feather storm (extra simorgh monster to protect link if possible)  2) Simorgh Link, Dark Simorgh, Anti-Spell Fragrance, Harpie's feather storm (extra simorgh monster to protect link if possible)  Any mix of the above can be made if you have the extenders. Use the Simorgh spells to extra-normal summon Avian without tributing if you have it in your hand. You can also end on the other two big simorgh birds but they aren't as good. If you manage to get traptrick or harpie's feather storm in conjuction with either/both of dark simorgh+spell fragrance or avian+barrier statute, or both, your opponent will quit.  Only weakness if evenly matched. Save Apex Avian or Simorgh of Darkness's effect(s) for this. Link Simorgh makes them all immune to infinite impermanence, so for the most part traps that can be played directly from the hand aren't a threat despite normally being capable or circumventing the simorgh lock.

deck_excerpt: Step 1. Mekk-Knight Step 2. Win. Step 2.5. Avida Step 3. Now win
deck_description: One day, I received one of those random 25 card packs, which contained Mekk-Knight Green Horizon. A year or so later, I decided to build an entire deck off of the Mekk-Knight archetype. A couple minutes before I made this deck, I searched up the same combination of archetypes that make up this deck. There were no results, so I thought it was time to upload my deck IRL.   One of the main strategies of this deck is with World Legacy Scars. The chain of effects in order to activate World Legacy Scar's secondary effect is super simple. After that, the game should not last much longer.    This deck is made up of 4 different archetypes. These are all within the same lore story. While some of the cards I do not own physically, they are still not needed to play this deck. Those cards are "Ib, the World Justiciar" and "Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax." This deck is still a fairly smooth and easy deck to play.

Machina Trains. Now is a bad time for this deck. With Needlefibre combos dominating the format, it's way too risky to run a deck with little room for handtraps that wants to go second. On the other hand, I think the deck's fundamentals are actually really solid. Citadel synergizes with Train cards, the deck takes total advantage of broken Earth Machine support, you have great utility link and Xyz plays including True King of All Calamities of your own.  2x Machina Citadel are the main reason to play the Machina engine. Having one of these in the GY essentially gives your Super Dora a floating effect that wipes your opponent's board at spell speed 2 at a time of your choosing, and you want the second copy so you can loop 2 of them out of your gy. This guy is a good backup boss monster, and the center of Urgent Schedule otks.  2x Machina Metalcruncher give you some normal summons. These help make Calamities, which is easier than you'd think with Urgent Switchyard, Flying Pegasus, and Machina Redeployment alongside Machina Megaform and Machina Irradiator. They also search a train to your hand, which helps make rank 10s. These are just better than Night Express, but you need 1 Night Express to tutor with Switchyard, so I'm only running 2. Both of these could be 3, but space is tight.  1 each of Fortress, Irradiator, and Megaform. Fortress is actually kind of broken, the thing inherent summons itself multiple times a turn if you pitch it with Scrap Recycler. Because we have so many ways to search it, one is all you need, since you don't want multiples in your hand. It's also a good beatstick, which can float into Megaform if it's in your GY, and is hard to remove with monsters without taking a penalty. Irradiator and Megaform are a free Citadel, or really any Machina card you want (Citadel). This combo also helps to make your Xyz plays, and is easy with Redeployment.  For Trains we have 1 Night Express, and 2 Flying Pegasus, to grab with Switchyard. Flying Pegasus can be a good normal summon in its own right, and helps make those Xyz plays seem easy. There are also 3 each of Bullet Train and Freight Train, not much to say about these, they're the bread and butter of the train deck. You want 3 of each to find them with Metalcruncher, but I could see cutting a Freight Train for a Citadel.  3 Scrap Recycler are run, alongside engine requirements Scrap Golem, O-Lion, and Gizmek Orochi. Please don't ban O-Lion because Needlefibre and Auroradon are too good. Just ban Auroradon and Needlefibre, scraps did nothing wrong. You could run a huge Needlefibre combo out of here with Jet Synchron, but in testing I had trouble making a good Needlefibre combo that didn't use up space needed for Trains. It seems better to have more utility rather than focus on a single game plan everyone is preparing for anyways. The Scrap engine is still incredibly good, even going first it's a 1.5 card Apollousa with 4 negates, and Scrap Recycler sends all kinds of targets in this deck. These are also insane alongside Urgent Schedule and Machina Citadel going second. Orochi also helps make Dingirsu, and fun fact, with Megaform your can even put 3 materials on him some of the time.  I'm running 8 interactive cards, plus effectively 3 mystic mine, but none of them are handtraps. The goal is to go second and OTK, so we have cards that will help to break board in mind.  3 Jizikiru the Star Destroyer Kaiju are run. You could run Gamecial for Water Barrier Statue, or wind Kaijus even for Wind Barrier Statue, but you get the most synergy running Kaijus that are (sort of) trains. I've also got 3 Lightning Storm to help break boards and deal with Backrow, and 2 Dark Ruler No More so I don't autolose all the time going second. Not Otking is actually ok in this deck IMO, its grind game is still pretty good despite being a big dumb otk deck.  We've effectively got 3 Switchyard and 3 Mystic Mine thanks to 1 of each and 1 Terraforming and 1 Set Rotation. 3 of each while only using 4 deck spaces is the reason for this split - it uses as little deckspace as possible while still letting me run the numbers I want anyways. Mystic Mine can lock games down and facilitate Liebe or Borrelsword OTKs. Switchyard is an insane combo piece that virtually ensures you make a Rank 10.  There's not much to say about Urgent Schedule and Machina Redeployment. Urgent Schedule is an insane card in Machina AND trains, especially going second, and is just broken with Citadel and Recycler. Redeployment fixes your hand while pitching something to the GY, and finds combo pieces or way to Citadel in the process. In my opinion you must run 3 of each of these cards in the deck.

deck_excerpt: Speculating on the future ban list and alternate ways to play Eldlich. I liked the Popperup engine enough I dedicated a deck to it.
deck_description: Pretty simple deck, pure control Eldlich. We have 6 hand traps, 24 cards that combo with our card draw techs, and 9 of said techs, which are cards which can gain simply absurd advantage by pitching cards which we want in the GY to draw cards.  The card draw is the most important part. Magicians' Souls is the key engine piece of the deck, its ability to send cards from the hand or the GY makes it even better with Cursed Eldland than the other options. You're seeing things right, I'm normal summoning the sumbitch. Why not, the deck has no other normal summons anyways. Popperup is just an absurd card, a potential +6 if you "combo". Hand Destruction is a high risk - high reward option, since it greatly improves our own consistency since our deck is built around it, while it might actually disrupt an opponent relying on small combos and hand traps. Definitely pull these out in the mirror, though game 1 our deck is far better suited to take advantage of it than the average Eldlich build. With 9 of these the odds of seeing 1 in your opening hand is reasonably high.  24 cards are part of recursive grind engines. The only reason for 1 red Eldlixir is speculating on it being limited in the near future. Run 3 for sure while they're legal. All the Eldlich cards are here in full force, alongside Lost Wind, Titanocider, and the card advantage engine which is Metalfoes Fusion. You can use it as fodder for Golden Lord or the draw engine, all while drawing extra cards. 24 cards means nearly 2 of 3 cards will be cards the deck wants in the gy, alongside the 1 of 5 which can pitch it there (Golden Lord not included). You want all the Eldlich cards possible, since you'll often be throwing away copy 1.  6 hand traps means we will see them in just under 2/3 of all games, giving us a chance when going second game 1. The game plan going first is good enough we should only need them going second, but the deck could be punished for that. Imperm is particularly synergistic with Souls, and good right now, while Crow is too good to pass up even with 3 Huaquero.  Edit* Changed the numbers. Reduced recursion to fit in hand trap 7, running 3 red splatter while this is legal. Also running Pot of Extravagence. While it does lock you out of other draw for the turn, you aren't using your extra deck, and the card can be held on to in order to significantly improve your grind game, or be filtered through with your other draw engines.

deck_excerpt: Um deck que um grande potencial de otk
deck_description: 1. WwwWrite your deck strategy here...

Needlefibre turbo deck, with 6 1 card Needlefibres, a ton of combos to go into Needlefibre, and some hand loop stuff built into the combo.  I wanted to take advantage of the space in the deck to run 9 hand traps. 9 helps really ensure that we'll see a hand trap most of the time, and there just weren't other cards I considered essential enough. Nibiru is really good right now with all the combo running around, and Imperm and Crow are also really good against Eldlich and Adamancipator going first or second, so this split seems good. I'm not maining Dark Ruler, because IMO it's not good enough against Eldlich Synchron or against any deck with space for Jet Synchron combos/literally any 1 card Needlefibre. They're in the side deck for when a hand trap isn't as good or better.  We have 3 Deep Sea Diva and 3 Neptabyss with 3 Dragoons, 3 Minstrel, Lappis, and Moulinglacia. This means Diva ends on Moulinglacia + VFD having drawn 2 cards and hand looped our opponent for 3, with Neptabyss also making VFD + Draw 2. I cut the Formula Synchron combo to make space for some backup/followup plays in Bujinki Ahashima, Apollousa, and Bahamut Shark into Toad (running 3 cards just to draw a single card seemed excessive). 3 Heavy Infantry makes sense, since we go into Coral Drgon and Crocodragon as part of our main combo, and the potential to seriously break boards while comboing off is super clutch.  1 001 and 2 O-Lion are pretty key. 2 O-Lion is about always having an O-Lion to combo off with even if you brick, since the whole deck is pretty dedicated to comboing off one route.  3 Deep Sea Aria help find us any low-level sea Serpent, usually Diva, to start combos. The deck doesn't excel at putting monsters in the GY, but this card gives you 3 more situational copies of Diva, which is clutch. Pot of Avarice is at 3 which is insane, and I genuinely think more decks can play it. It contributes greatly to the grind game while also giving card advantage. While it might seem like a bit of a "win more" card, the truth is any deck that can easily put 5-10 monsters in the GY off of 1-2 cards should probably be running this. The card also isn't once per turn, which decks like this can take sometimes take advantage of (though not as well as Salamangreats, just sayin'). One for One is an extra Neptabyss, which is full combo, as is Abyssteus + Dragoons, which is what I like to call "overcombo".
This is my T.G. deck list.

deck_excerpt: ♪ Let's play hide-and-seek with the friendly Märfaes! ♪ (...and their new friends, I:P and Zeroboros...)
deck_description:
♪ Let's play hide-and-seek with the friendly Märfaes! ♪ Merfaes (or Märfaes, depending on your translation), are a new archetype in Rise of the Duelist. Right now they serve well as a beast advantage engine, but still need a few more cards to have a chance of being meta-viable. That isn't going to stop us. I'll level with you in advance; this is not a meta deck. It can't beat full-power Adamancipator or Eldlich. However, I've done my best to test and refine it and compare it to other Märfae deck variants, so this might just be the most meta-ready Märfae deck build you'll find on here, at least at the present moment. So let's get into the choices! - Playing Around With Märfaes: A Basic Primer - The essential idea of this deck is being able to make plays on both your own and your opponent's turn to keep a hold of the game. You'll be using effects like Obedience Schooled and Ties of the Brethren early game to establish a board, then using the recursion of your Märfae children to keep the advantage and disruption up later. You can go first or second; you'd rather go first, but you can adjust based on whether your opponent's playing OTKs or not. The core gameplay options of this deck revolve around a triple threat of Extra Deck summoning mechanisms: using Naturia Beast as your premier Synchro, Märfaes of the Forest as your main Xyz play, and I:P Masquerena as the core Link of the deck. These let you stun spells, disrupt monsters while obtaining advantage, and go into powerful game-ending plays respectively. Each of the main Märfae monsters summons themselves from your hand during your End Phase, and can bounce themselves back to the hand when attacked or when your opponent summons, in order to activate a unique effect; Puppie summons a lv2 Beast from deck, Cathy gets any decked Beast to hand (notably, it can get Rescue Cat(!)), Fennie summons a Beast from your hand, and Ponie recycles a Beast from the Graveyard. We play an assortment of all of these - I originally ran only 1 each of Fennie and Ponie as their effects are mediocre, but quickly found that having multiple Märfae names accessible is useful as their effects are all hard once per turn. Your main disruption options during the opponent's turn are as follows:
  • Märfaes of the Forest Fiendish Chains an opponent whenever a Märfae returns to your hand, letting you freeze your opponent at critical moments as long as the foe's effect isn't an on-summon one.
  • Naturia Beast locks any deck that relies on Spells out of the game altogether, and lets you get monsters in your grave for later.
  • Kalantosa, Mystical Beast of the Forest will often be your Puppie/Fennie target of choice, popping any card the moment it hits the field.
  • Hop-Ear Squadron is a powerful Cathy target, as you can instantly Synchro Summon into a Herald or Hastorr the moment you add it.
  • I:P Masquerena is the ultimate culmination of your "play on the foe's turn" stratagem; it lets you utilise those Märfae self-bounce resource getters and their summon-at-end-phase to toolbox into Zeroboros, Borrelsword, or whatever other Link helps you solve the present problems.
  • ...and you've got plenty more convenient backrow support, such as old staples Called by the Grave and Ash Blossom, Märfae Tag for summoning, Super Rush Recklessly to yeet opposing threats right back to the deck, and even odd picks like Peropero Cerperus!
- Disowned by Märfae Mommie herself! - I'll address the elephant in the room while I can. This deck does not run Märfae Mommie, the second Xyz. It also does not run Märfae Time, the Trap. Why? First of all, I'm sorry, but Mommie is... not good. You have to expend 5 material to make her the best she can be, and that best is... a weaker Yubel with no effect protection. If I were playing Heroic Champion I could have solved world hunger by making a five material Xyz, so needless to say Mommie is not worth the investment. This also means that Märfae Time isn't worth it - at best you're getting 1-2 bounces by expending materials from your Märfaes of the Forest, which isn't much advantage for a slow trap. Märfaes simply have better ways to interact on their opponent's turn, as the above proves! Cutting both of these has given us much more room to focus on cards that do matter, as this deck is pretty short on both main and extra deck room. Pragmatism never hurt anybody! - Interactions and choices to keep in mind - First of all: Search stoppers like Ash Blossom are a pretty big threat to this deck. Most of your ways to go off on your own turn such as Ties/Rescue/Obedience are blocked out by it, and though it's not uncommon that you'll draw into two or more of those, it's still something to keep in mind. You've got three Called to help cover yourself on that regard, but if that ever feels like it's not enough for a particular matchup, feel free to splurge on those Three Tactical Talents in the side deck! Related to that; you don't have too many cards that lock you into specific conditions, but Obedience and Ties lock you into only Beasts and no more Special Summoning respectively. Obedience, therefore, is best when you don't want to go for I:P, and instead want to make an opening board of something like Forest + Puppie + Natbeast with a bunch of backrow and card advantage ready. Ties's limitation is less of a problem; you're not doing it to gain material, you're using it to get two more Märfaes from deck to field so you can proceed to pop off with Masqs and Kalantosas and Hopears and the like on your foe's turn! Use them wisely and you can't go wrong! On another note, what you should search with Märfaes of the Forest depends on the situation. Hide-And-Seek is a powerful one; giving a single effect protection per turn is surprisingly useful and lets you do amusing actions like keep the material you got from Rescue Cat, while it also lets you constantly recycling all the monsters you're going to be getting time and time again to get free hand advantage. I can't count the number of times in practice I shuffled back the exact three cards of Mine Mole, Valerifawn, and Naturia Beast, or thereabouts, to proc it... Märfae Tag is also a powerful option that lets you do stuff like surprise proc'ing an I:P-made Zeroboros to clear your opponent's field, but if you don't need any of them, Puppie (or whatever best Märfae you don't have on hand at the time) is always a safe bet. Finally, just remember that the Extra Deck and Side Deck for this deck are by no means locked in stone. There's a lot of different picks you can take, from different rank 2 Xyz, different Link toolboxing, et cetera. The side deck right now just reflects a few tools that might be useful - Barkion helps a lot in trap-centric matchups but is hard to make, Cerburrel works well with cards like Valerifawn and Twin Twisters (if you feel lucky, you can even run a Danger! variant of the deck with Bigfoot and Jackalope) and lets you make Unicore for a very unique stun option, and so forth. Definitely experiment to make the deck suit your own tastes! - Final Thoughts - Ultimately, the Märfae archetype is a very unique and thematic deck lineup that has a surprising amount of depth and flexibility to their play and has potential to become all the more powerful if more support is released from them in the future. From churning out advantage to going for unexpected kills with link 4s, there's a lot they can show off, and I hope this has convinced you to take a stroll in the forest yourself and try them out!

Deck Concept This deck is based around the field spell "Generaider Boss Stage" to create resources and provide disruptions such as Spell Speed 2 banish removal, effect negation, and summon negation during your opponent's turn. In this build, I decided to run 10 field searchers and 3 Boss Stage, which are about 88% to open with them in the starting hand. Basically the field is 1 card Spell Speed 2 banish removal, effect negation, and summon negation during your opponent's turn, but it loses to any kind of Spell Speed 2 spell/trap removal. So I decided to run the Jet Synchron Auroradon package to provide some protection for the field and provide some more disruption. P.S. English isn't my first language. Sorry for bad grammar. deck_description: While I like the grind game of the Turbo Control build, I also like comboing off, so I'm back on Synchros for a second. I still plan to play the control variant, which has a lot of advantages, such as space to run 9 card draw, the advantage of running 3 each of Golden Land Traps, and generally puts more interactions on the board with its spell and trap line-up than the Synchro version, which can often be dead in the water if your Needlefibre gets hand trapped. On the other hand, some percentage of the time you can win just by comboing off of 1 card, and the deck is uniquely suited to take advantage of the Jet Synchron engine, and in my opinion, the Synchro deck is better in most matchups for that reason alone.

deck_excerpt: A Toon deck that utilizes a control strategy involving There Can Be Only One, Summon Limit, and (oddly enough) Mystic Mine.
deck_description: The main strategy involves using Summon Limit, There Can Be Only One, and Mystic Mine to control against the opposing field. Mystic Mine may seem counterintuitive at first but aids tremendously in stalling the opponent during situations where Toon Kingdom has been removed off the field and in circumstances where activating this card may genuinely help replenish the hand and circumvent the duel. Toon World is used during situations where the opponent has already swarmed several monsters and is used in conjunction with Mystic Mine to achieve plays (particularly with Toon Black Luster Soldier whose banishing properties help cripple the opponent's field slowly.) Pot of Extravagance and Reckless Greed aids in providing the deck the necessary draw power.  On the other hand, Waking The Dragon helps in surprising the opponent and stunning them (such as with Bagooska) or simply making it more difficult for the opponent to deal with the field (such as with Raidraptor-Ultimate Falcon). All the other cards are pretty standard. The real player, however, in the deck, isn't really Mystic Mine or even Toon Kingdom though, as There Can Be Only One pretty much fuels the deck's control power strangely enough (being one of the few decks that can make genuine use of it actually helps it a lot.) If Mystic Mine ever gets banned lol there's still a lot of interesting options to choose from.

deck_excerpt: 1 card infinite negates in Harpie? Yes, Romulus equals to infinite negates, making Channeler, Perfumer, and Rescue Rabbit a 1 card Mist Valley lock. H
deck_description: Romulus turbo deck, it means any 2 dragons/winged beasts are enough to fuel the combo. So we play 3 Channeler, 3 Perfumer, and 3 Rescue Rabbit as our main starter because it makes our Feather Storm online to prevent Nibiru and other monster handtrap while still can summon Romulus. Use Romulus add Divine Lance, use Divine Lance, equip and ss Phalanx, make Linkross using Romulus ss 2 tokens, make Halqifibrax using Linkross + Phalanx and ss O-Lion, make Martial Metal Marcher, use Martial ss O-Lion/Phalanx (Phalanx better, so enemy's D.D. Crow wont give us -2 card advantage) chain O-Lion ss token, make Union Carrier using Mecha Phantom Beast token + Martial, make og Clausolas using O-Lion/Phalanx + Linkross token, make Simorgh link 3 using Clausolas + Halq. This deck will be even better once the new Dragunity support come, because you can easily make Dragunity Areadbhair + Herald Arc Light + Black Garden (prevent opponent from atking Arc Light), all just from a single Romulus too (by switching to Auroradon instead of using Simorgh/Clausolas). We will still have follow up because Garden Rose Maiden can revive Areadbhair and you can even summon Dragunity Arma Gram/Dragunity Glow (searchable by Romulus) if you have it in hand. I dont use Harpie synchro as it is a combo deck, it means we wont be running that much option to trigger its effect as interruption. Pros: Ultra consistent, minimal resource, have Nibiru (or other handtrap) prevention, follow up play is okay-ish, big space for staples. Cons: Infinite negates is only once/twice per chain, it means your opponent can break the cycle by interrupting it mid-chain.

deck_excerpt: Millenium Eye Effect with Toon Support.
deck_description: The puropse of creating this deck was to get some usage out of the new Toon support cards. It also has the capability of looking into an opponent's deck with the chance of removing a card from the other players' hand giving it a Millenium Eye "Mind Scan" effect. I will be modifying it later, but as a warning, this is a 1 first turn deck meaning that this version has to go first.  Toon Gemini Elf can exist before Toon World or Kingdom is played. Like all toons monsters, it has the ability to attack your opponents directly.  You also want to try and banish any key cards a player has with the trap cards, Trickstar Reincarnation and Chain Dissappearance. Reincarnation will disrupt plays by banishing any monster, spell, or traps they could play in their hand. Chain Dissappearance will only banish all copies of the monster that has 1000 atk or lower. The Forceful Checkpoint allows to you send a monster from the hand to the grave after negating their attack.  Crackdown, Heartfelt Appeal and Comic Hand allows you to take your opponent's monsters and use them as you see fit given you are able to hit the right targets.  Then there's the usual protection of Solemn Counter trap cards. However it's at the cost of your own LP.  I do have other cards in mind to add it on for the future. Just got to make it more wackier than usual!

deck_excerpt: The deck of Playmaker's bastard child. Easily executed Link-based deck that COULD ruin your opponent's day, although not as much as banish and burn de
deck_description: 2 Cyberse monsters (Tokens included) 》 Splash Mage + 1 (Splash Mage effect) 》 Transcode Talker + 1 (Transcode Talker effect) 》 Accesscode Talker (or any Topologic monster, depending on the situation)  The primary goal is to bring out Accesscode Talker with 5300 ATK and at least 2 "Spell Speed 4" destruction effect activations (from the Link monsters used in the combo).  Various negates, especially Mystic Mine, were included in the deck because Accesscode Talker is defenseless during the opponent's turn. Mystic Mine will not become a hindrance even if your opponent only has one monster on the field since the deck relies on the alternation of Special Summons and Link Summons, which essentially only requires one monster on the field at any given time to continue the combo.  If Accesscode Talker was removed from the field during the previous turn, another one could be brought out again easily if you could summon 2 monsters on the field. This is very easy to do since all of the Effect Monsters in the Main Deck revolve around Special Summons and Tokens; the opponent would have to burn at least two negates in order to break your combo in most cases, even more if you have a good hand.  Mathmech Addition and Mathmech Subtraction are also great options, especially in baiting your opponent's once per turn negates (e.g. Cyber Dragon Infinity). However, I did not include them in this iteration because there were other options that could synergize well with Lady Debug and Cyberse Gadget, or at least that's what I thought.

deck_description: Early stab at Rikka hybrid deck. Turn 1 deck with strong turn 2 options. Extending into Snowdrop early, to enable early big bodies for your board. Mardel fishes for things you need on hand. Boss Stage. Primula. [Multiple Primulas can summon at once, seeing the effect can only trigger once]. Hiding things in the GY for later plays. Rose Girl for constantly recurring itself with Petal when you need recovery. Pot of Avarice to help recycle Snowdrop and Mardel for later use. Loptr is a Turn 1 insurance card. He makes sure you have something defensive to play. Brings out Mardel, who then lets you hand pick a card from the deck whether its a plant or Generaider card. Buffs any tokens that were brought out by Boss Stage.  Trying to tweak this into something that can better and consistently deal with/handle Altergeist.  EDOPro sucks... Don't use it. EDOPro sometimes registers Primula's effect to special summon herself as Snowdrops effect to tribute a plant by then locking out Snowdrop from using her own effect. So, use Dueling Book or hand test yourself.  Definitely, not the best deck. FOR NOW! With the play-testing online and IRL I have been having fun with this deck and I will continue to evolve this deck, hopefully, into something more competitive. I find the spell card Rikka Flurries is way more powerful than it's current consideration and should be a card to keep your eye on.

deck_excerpt: Step 1: Try getting Hidden City Step 2: Get Ash Blossomed  Step 3: Summon Guru and Final Battle/Trap Trick Step 4: Got OTKed Step 5: Remove all ot
deck_description: There are other Subterror monster other than Guru, Umastryx, Nemesis Archer and Fiendess. So I thought I will try tweaking the list a bit to fit Ultramafus while still making it consistent. This list was meant to downgrade Guru control from tier 2.5 to tier 3 in hopes of getting fun and not being called a meta fag by summoning Ultramafus turn 3 and aprove dominance by making Ultramafus 3.5-5k atk and OTK your opponent turn 3 or 5 ...  This deck is a go first deck and your God hand and go first tactic is basically Guru control and then turn 3 try swinging for big damage or control even moar.  These are the important cards you want to always see are Hidden City, Fiendess, Guru, Called/Ash/Imperm, and Final Battle/Trap Trick. These are the cards you don't want to see when going first is Nemesis Archer.  If you go first but see no Guru or Hidden City but have Fiendess, Ultramafus or Umastryx, and Final Battle or Trap Trick do the following play: Norma Summon Fiendess, Fiendess eff, Ultramafus or Umastryx, set Final Battle. If you have Called and Imperm set it, it is better than doing nothing.  You could also replace Necrovalley for Mystic Mine but to me it is riskier to play Mystic Mine because you have a limited options than to play against an opponent who plays Gravekeeper's.

deck_description: This is my take on HERO decks for post Toon Chaos. This deck has a few combos that add up to a big one. I will put the 3 main combos here: 1-Cards needed = 1 HERO monster and 1 Vision HERO Faris in hand.  Combo: Discard the HERO to SS Faris, Faris eff will put Increase into the ST. then Increase will send Faris to GY to SS itself from the ST and Vion from the deck, then Vion will send a HERO from deck to GY, then banish Farris w Vion eff to add Polymerization. 2-Cards needed = 2 HERO monsters on field and Malicious on GY. Combo. Link summon into Xtra HERO Cross Crusader, Cross eff will revive the Malicious, then Cross will tribute the Malicious to search a HERO, then Malicious eff will SS banish itself from GY and SS a Malicious from deck. Then u can either link summon into Wonder Driver or Dread Deimator, or fusion summon. 3-Cards needed = 2 HERO monsters w different atributes + poly. This is a simple 2 fusion summon combo. u fuse into Sunrise then use its eff to add Miracle fusion to your hand, then play miracle fusion.  To get a big combo just do combos 1, 2, and 3 together. There are more combos that end up with better boards but figure that out for yourself.  P.S:The Field spells and Favorite hero cards are optional and can be replaced by handtraps.

deck_excerpt: With this deck, your opponent's board is just another resource pool! | Made for the May/June 2020 TCG banlists.
deck_description:
This deck aims to go second—using Super Poly and Kaijus to clear the opponent's board of its peskiest problems, then taking the choicest monsters with Relinquished and its Eyes Restrict fusions. Millennium-Eyes Restrict then allows you to lock down your opponent and take the game. Some points of interest...
  • Advanced Ritual Art uses Thousand-Eyes Idol as its target, which then sets it up in the GY for the summoning of Thousand-Eyes Restrict.
  • King of the Swamp's search effect also sets up your GY nicely, since it can be used there as substitute for Relinquished.
  • Radian is the "safest" Kaiju in that it interacts well with Allure of Darkness. Jizukiru and Thunder King, however, will power up your Relinquished/Restricts above the 3000 ATK threshold.
  • Lava Golem, meanwhile, eats two monsters at the cost of your normal summon. This isn't always a safe choice, because both Manju and the Predaplant engine rely on your normal summon.
  • Consider running a second Darlingtonia Cobra, because Garnets suck.
  • Illusionist Faceless Magician gives longevity to an Eyes Restrict monster summoned by Instant Fusion (or the effect of Instant Fusion, copied by Anaconda).
  • Perhaps it goes without stating, but the GY effect of Relinquished Fusion should be reserved for Millennium-Eyes Restrict whenever possible. It's the only monster of this archetype which has no native monster steal effect; only through Relinquished Fusion and Millennium-Eyes Illusionist can you use it proactively.
  • The side deck contains only suggestions—I wouldn't recommend that exact side deck, but I would recommend any of those cards as options.

Yes, this deck is actually a thing, and yes it can actually work. Alien has a lot of floating and stun elements that can be used very effectively. When facing a spell/trap board, go for Gol'Gar to get the bouncing effect and build up counters. If facing a more monster heavy board, Hastorr is the better bet.

deck_excerpt: Annoy your Opponent and let them despair.
deck_description: Hey Guys :) So this is my Evil Eye Deck. I play that Deck myself in real life (and I love it) since it came out, so I have some Experience with it. The Main Strategy is always the same, but the Tech-options can vary a lot. I always try new Techs/Strategys, but I found this list very good so far. At my local Store I made second Place with it ( It´s a while ago, so I had some other  Cards in my Side Deck, but the Side Deck Choice is always different depending on the format, so...). With this Deck you want to go first, to set up everything you need. Goal is to summon Zerrziel (Link 3 Monster) equipped with Selene and Summon Limit, or There can be only one. Those Traps shut down so many Decks and it makes it much more easier for you.  There can be only one also restrict yourself, but to be Honest you just need one Monster (Serziel or Zerrziel) and having only one Dark Monster on the Field forces the opponent to use his Monsters when attempting to use Super Polymerization. Those Traps also increase the pressure on the opponent, because they have to deal with two spell/traps that threatening them. To make sure your Selene or the Traps don´t get destroyed or banned set the Evil Eye Countertrap. Only use that for the mentioned spell/trap removal. Protecting your Selene is very important. When you go into the second game you could side in another Evil Eye Countertrap or something similar. One major Plus point of this Deck is, that nearly no one knows this Deck and underestimates it. Most times those opponents loose the Game^^ I play this Deck quite a while now and I have to say that the worst Thing that can happen to this Deck is getting Kaiju-ed. In every other case the opponent first has to deal with the Selene and then with the Monster so he/she has to put some (Card-) material to it, which reduces his/her Cards. When you get Kaiju-ed you loose everything without the possibility to react to it. So in my Opinion it is absolutely mandatory to have Mask of Restrict in the side Deck especially for game two. Getting out Zerrziel (Link 3) first turn is very easy with Tour Guide. You special summon Catoblepas, the summon Gorgon (Link 2), the special summon Catoblepas from the Grave and then go into Zerrziel. You then also have one Evil Eye Card in your Graveyard that you can banish for Evil Eye Repose (if you have it in Hand) without disadvantage. With Ghost Sister you have to be careful, because when you didn´t get any life points through this, you loose half your life points, which is a bad Thing in a Deck relying on Lifepoint-paying. It is a very good Handtrap in this Deck because sometimes you really need that Life Point-recovery. When I use it, then as follows: 1. Only when it is worth it. What I mean with this is: Some Decks can clear your Board and easily kill you in that same Turn. So if you see that is such a Deck or a Deck that special summons a lot (especially Monsters with high ATK) you should use it. Because sometimes an Opponent stops further summons to prevent giving you such a high amount of Life Points. 2. Only when he activates a Card or effect that would special summon a Monster, because the you are safe that you get Life points with it (except he can special summon a Monster with 0 ATK and ends it there. This is very rare but I had that case once, so just keep it in Mind^^). The cards in the Side Deck are only one possibility.  My Main Deck except a hand full of cards mostly stays the same, but the Side Deck is always Changing. That said you can exchange everything to your own Playstyle. The only card that I would highly recommend you to play in the Side Deck is Mask of Restrict. When you get Kaiju-ed and the opponent doesn´t have a Brick or has a slow Deck you will probably loose the game.  So, now I wrote a lot and I will end this now. I could say something to every card choice and the chosen number of them and talk about some plays that you can do with different Hands, but that would be too much for here. I should recommend doing a Video about it^^  I´m always open to new Ideas, so if you have some Tips or interesting Ideas please leave a comment. I would love to here some other opinions. Thanks for being interested in this Deck and have fun playing and building it.

deck_excerpt: Nekroz, Pure, with Extravagence and Extra-Foolish Burial.
deck_description: Unicore going to 3 got me looking at Nekroz. The Deskbot 003 combo seemed really good on paper, but it doesn't play under Nibiru, which is really common in this meta, and it also incorporates a huge number of bricks for a combo card you can only run 3 copies of, since there's no rota for 003. Unicore next to Kristya is also a little redundant, and I feel it's not a great use of its power. It's definitely a good combo, which I might be inclined towards, but I feel like to truly take advantage of the Nekroz deck you should play it sort of like Invoked Shaddoll last format, and turbo out Nekroz of Unicore.  In the main deck we get 9 ROTAs, all of which find us either a Ritual spell or monster. 3x Manju of the Ten Thousand hands uses up our normal summon for this, but the deck is not normal summon reliant, since you are a ritual deck. Extra-Foolish Burial is either a Rota by sending Herald of the Arc Light or targeted removal by sending Elder Entity N'tss. Both of these cards are useful Kaleidoscope targets, so the cost for this is a measly 400o LP. Preparation of Rites recycles a Ritual spell while adding a ritual monster that's level 7 or lower, but because of Clausolas and Brionac you can grab either a Nekroz spell or Monster. Having 12 ways to find Unicore and 11 ways to search a ritual spells, plus the actual copies of each in your deck makes turboing out Unicore very plausible.  We're only running 1 Shurit. He makes higher level Nekroz monsters more plausible and is still an important 1 of, but the deck has literally a dozen ways to search him thanks to all the ROTAs.  For Nekroz Ritual Monsters, 3 Unicore is obligatory. The secondary effect is very useful, and unlike some of his peers he can be full material for himself, so multiple copies are fine and you want to see this card. The whole point of the deck is turboing this onto the field and seeing if your opponent can play through him. It's notable that Eldlich outs him very easily, with 6 copies of Golden Lord, even with other Nekroz cards backing Unicore up. This played into my card choices.  I'm also running 3 Brionac. This is an essential combo piece with Preparation of Rites, also it finds Clausolas which finds rituals spells, and its 3 MORE copies of Unicore. The goal is as much consistency as possible, so 3 seemed ideal. It also really helps going second to break boards, which makes this deck good going second as well as first. Yay!  2 Nekroz of Clausolas helps make Preparation of Rites search either spells or monsters, contributing to that whole "12 Rota" feel. Effect negation on the board is occasionally good, like against Zombies, still kind of a deck, or uhh... Maybe Toons? Not a lot of maindeck archetypes right now besides Eldlich, which also activates effects out of the hand and GY anyways.  2 Nekroz of Trish are basically hand traps that are searchable by all of our 12 Rotas, which do the Sauravis thing. Having played Vanity stun, the power of that is immediately obvious. Also, while the deck can find it hard to summon sometimes thanks to Extravagence, it has a great effect going second to 3 for 2 your opponent. This card is the real reason you need Shurit.  2 Nekroz of Valkyrus round off the hand traps. This one is the easiest of all of the high-level Nekroz monsters to summon, and can gain you card advantage going first, especially in combination with Manju. Its real purpose is to protect Unicore from destruction by battle, very relevant against Eldlich, or against any deck with high attack monsters you can summon in the main deck.  2 Cycle, 2 Kaleidoscope, and 1 Mirror round off the Ritual spells. All of these are good, but with 11 searchers for them and 5 copies you should be good on seeing these in your hand.  I'm running 3 Pot of Extravagance, which can hurt with Kaliedoscope sometimes, but generally is worth if for sheer card advantage. Its also good Ash bait in a deck that needs searchers, and may be better than Called by the Grave for getting your plays going against Ash, which is still seeing some play as a 2 of.  That left room for 10 hand traps, and I wanted to take full advantage of it. To me, being able to run 10 interactive cards was the main perk of playing this version of the deck. I focused on cards that would help against Eldlich in the main deck, since the Eldlich matchup is seriously rough, but in the side deck I have options for, Adamancipator, as well as various ways to board against combo and control, including spicier versions of Eldlich and Altergeist, which are both actually pretty good right now (I know Geist is a rogue deck, but it was still topping with 1 Multifaker and now it has 3), plus going second cards.  The only things in the extra deck besides Kaleidoscope targets, including some which double for Extra-Foolish Burial, is Eria Gentle into Accesscode. This lets us imitage Shaddolls even further, by increasing the decks potential to OTK (when it doesn't see Extravagence).  ***EDIT***  Added original flavour ROTA over an interaction slot. Through Clausolas it is the 12th spell rota, and the 13th Shurit Rota. Basically a better flex slot when I decided to add Shurit #2.  ***EDIT***  Added I Shaddoll Dragon main and 3 Shaddoll Apkallone to the extra deck. This lets us make Brionac to break boards more easily, while also popping an additional spell/trap. It's worth losing 1 Cyclone for this mini engine, since Dragon is also useful for popping spells/traps with Nekroz Rituals, and 1 copy can be recycled to pop more cards with Apkallone.

The return of Altergeist With the return of 3 faker, your chance of seeing faker on your first turn, going first, increases from 63.93% to 74.18%.  For reference, the average Mekk Knight Invoked Deck / Invoked Deck has either a 63.93% or 69.40% chance of seeing Aleister turn 1 (69.40% assuming they play Set Rotation in addition to 3 Meltdown, 3 Aleister, and 1 Terraforming). What that means is... Altergeist has been granted a significant boost to its consistency, amongst other things. In addition to the added consistency, you're no longer as prone to cards like D.D. Crow and Called by the Grave as you were with 1 Multifaker. You now have 3 copies of the heart of your Deck, and with new F & L Lists seeing use in online competitive events (like the PPG Circuit's custom ban list) there has not been a better time to pick up Altergeist. _________ Key Altergeist Cards: • Altergeist Multifaker: The engine that makes Altergeist work, Multifaker is critical to the snowballing of the Deck as a whole with its ability to get you to cards like Silq, for disruption, and Meluseek, for more advantage. • Altergeist Meluseek: A key piece in getting to your Fakers, and other Altergeist monsters (like Marionetter) down the line, Meluseek is also a versatile tool with its battle oriented removal effect. • Altergeist Marionetter: Inevitably you'll find yourself with some awkward faker-less hands, and when those hands creep up... the next best thing is Mari. With the ability to set Protocol or Manifestation, she can keep you alive during your next turn and even provide some much-needed interaction via Protocol. Aside from her Normal Summon effect, she also has another powerful effect. Mari's ability to send an Altergeist card to the GY to revive an Altergeist from the grave is incredibly powerful in the mid-late game, netting you additional Altergeist bodies. • Altergeist Silquitous: While it's not great to open, this card is undeniably important to the Deck's core strategy. Being a Quick Effect bounce is already really, really good. When you add the fact that this card can function as pre-errata Brionac for the Deck... it becomes even more insane. This card can not only bounce your opponent's cards to the hand, it returns your Altergeist Traps and monsters back to the hand for a 2-in-1 disruption, as you're also gaining future setup (i.e. setting up Faker again, getting another Marionetter set, getting multiple uses out of Kunqueary). Adding to its impressive repertoire of ability is yet another effect. If this card is sent to the GY, whether it be as Link Material or byway of interaction with your opponent, Silq can grab an Altergeist Trap from the grave. • Altergeist Kunqueary: While nowhere near as consistently impactful as the rest of its brethren, Kunq can be pivotal in winning some matchups. Its ability to stop attacks, that is not once per turn, coupled with its on-summon negation can prove to be too much for some Decks. • Personal Spoofing: Though it's not "technically an Altergeist card", it wouldn't be right to exclude spoofing from this list. Not only is it an additional 3 copies of Faker, and not only is it able to trigger faker on its own when activated... it can get you a whole host of other Altergeist monsters. Access to Kunq during your opponent's turn or Meluseek/Mari during yours are just some of the benefits this card can provide. • Altergeist Protocol: Likely your first set off Mari, Protocol is the 2nd inherent piece of disruption within the archetype - after Silq. On top of being a monster negate, that pops, it also has a nifty effect that prevents the activation of Altergeist effects. That's pretty absurd given how powerful some of the effects of the Altergeist lineup are, and this card is pretty handy given how many boss-caliber monsters exist in today's format (of which some are incredibly hard to out via monster effects). • Altergeist Manifestation: Though it may not be as impressive as some of the other Altergeist cards, Mani definitely has a place within the group. With cards like Silq and Protocol, you're able to abuse Manifestation's unique design to get free reborns on either turn in addition to getting your Mani back to Deck or hand. These reborns can prove to be crucial as you may not have a Multifaker on field, or a Silq left in Deck to bounce with. _________ Options to consider for Extra/Main/Side Aside from ratio adjustments, there are a few cards that should be considered when building Altergeist. • Extra Deck:

-> Linkross: It's able to trigger off your Hexstia, which will probably be even more relevant once turn 1 Hexstia becomes reality with the release of Altergeist Pookuery, and it's able to set up some Link 2 plays (assuming Linkuriboh is in your GY).

-> Borreload Dragon: It's still amazing all these years down the line. It's hard to out, it has the ability to remove some of the game's most annoying monsters, and it's pretty big. There's not much more you can ask for from Borreload, the issue is that it's not as fast or as impactful as some of the Extra Deck's other options (see Borrelsword & Accesscode).

-> Altergeist Primebanshee: Another Altergeist name that you may end up wanting if you manage to banish your 3 Hexstia. However this card's actual impact is debatable as Altergeist is not reliant on its Extra Deck... and this card's only real place is as another name.

• Main Deck:

-> Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay: Needlefiber does exist in the TCG alongside Linkross, Verte Anaconda, and Union Carrier. Given the power and prevalence of Link 2+ monsters in the TCG format, it is definitely worth it to consider this card.

-> Mystic Mine / Secret Village of the Spellcasters / Terraforming / Set Rotation / Metaverse: I'm putting a whole host of cards together because they all go together (though you do not have to play all together). If you opt to play a more Mystic Mine centered variant, as it has proven to be successful (see Gabriel Netz's 1st place LCS list), it's also pretty reasonable to invest Deck space into cards like Demise of the Land as well.

-> Heavy Storm Duster / Typhoon: Given the prevalence of Eldlich, and the rise of Altergeist, Storm Duster & Typhoon might be worth playing in the main Deck instead of Side. They're Normal Traps, so they can trigger your Multifaker and be set off Trap Trick, while removing threats in your opponent's backrow.

-> Crackdown: It's similar to Compulsory Evacuation Device, but you get to keep the opponent's monster.

-> Trap Trick: If you opt to play a higher Normal Trap Count this card is fantastic (it can get you Infinite Impermanence, maybe a Different Dimension Ground or even a Compulse).

• Side Deck:

-> Kaijus / Lava Golem: Same reason for why Sphere Mode is in the Side. Altergeist isn't entirely reliant on its Normal Summon and it can't clear a break-my-board type of field if it DRNMs, and these cards are amazing at doing exactly that.

-> Lightning Storm: It's great in the mirror, versus Salamangreat, and a whole host of other strategies. It clears backrow or Attack Position monsters, and doesn't care if you have a bunch of set traps.

-> D.D. Crow / Different Dimension Ground: For the more GY based strategies, these cards are great options.

-> Artifact Lancea: It hits Eldlich, it hits TCG Adamancipators, and it can hit rogue options like Thunder. Overall it's still a great option for Decks that banish to progress their gameplan.

deck_excerpt: The new earth Possessed beast with Magicians Souls + Gravekeeper Shaman locks your opponent GY and pops face-up card at the same time with Teamwork of
deck_description: Only a few cards revealed and Charmer already can compete by making viable board. Not only that, they can also pops card along the way. I chose earth, because its the best one so far cus it summons back its material means you can Halq if you used tuner as that beast fodder. The Halq combo we use is without Linkross (banned in OCG) and Borreload Savage (useless if summoned from Ascator package, I'll explain why Ascator package later) while maintaining at least 2 different attribute on field so our Teamwork of the Possessed extra effect is online.  Ascator package is used as it is a free Awakened-Possessed fodder and can go to lv8 synchro means you will have 2 disruptions online despite the synchro only restriction. Magicians Souls package works wonder too as it is an Awakened-Possessed fodder and can dump Gravekeeper's Shaman (1500 def spellcaster with gy lock, super good in meta matchup). Eda the Sun Magician (spellcaster, earth, 1500 def, all stats fits just perfectly) works okay-ish as it brings free monster from deck (Green Turtle Summoner, flip and pops monster, water for Eria link targeting opponent Halq for instant Accesscode). For earth extender, we use tuners like Adhara and Deskbot 001 (combo pieces). Instant Fusion is versatile on bringing which fodder we lack. Paleozoic Dinomischus is just great normal trap in general (removes Golden Lord permanently if given the chance), it makes Teamwork of the Possessed extra effect online cus it summons a water monster (giving that we dont summon the 1500 def water spellcaster), also it is a water for Eria. Trap Trick to fetch all the normal trap we play. The handtrap lineup is preferably tuner, and is an earth and/or spellcaster (ghost belle and veiler).  Extra deck we're using Draco Berseker instead of Borrel Savage cus its viable without link in gy. Linkuriboh + Secure Gardna is there to provide attribute variant for Teamwork of the Possessed (also it provides link 1 for Borrel Savage if you wanna use it). Selene + Accesscode good in late game as we run bunch of spellcasters (but only a handful of spell tho).  Side deck, Kaiju is the first thing to use cus it provides attribute you desire with using Slumber while breaking board (this deck has slow removal, trap, so we need faster removal going second). Scarlight is another great lv8 option via Ascator going second. Lightning Storm and Evenly Matched as faster removal too.  Cards to think of: Block Dragon is good but it requires you to run rocks for full advantage, at that point why not play adaman instead haha. Fossil Fusion lineup maybe good, but Weathering Soldier wont trigger if it's used as Awakened-Possessed fodder. The field spell is very gimmicky, because while its nice to have monster negation, it is mandatory and needs 1500 stats spellcaster it means most of the time it wont negate handtraps if we're on further Halq combo, the adding earth monster is bad too as the spellcasters are better than those 1500/200 earths.     Pros: Fun to play (except the Halq part lol). Playstyle has multiple variant, call it backrow or combo. First turn board is okay-ish.  Cons: Struggle going second (almost guaranteed lose going second cus some of our play is flip monster or trap).

DISCLAIMER: I would recomend playing 3 of each S39, instead of the Knightmares and the Heartlandraco, but the deck editor wouldn't let me. It's a control deck, you play it like guru, lol. Here is a beginners guide tho, for everyone who has no idea what either toons or control decks are about. *Always use bookmark to search kingdom, otherwhise search bookmark with table of contents, because bookmark gives protection for the kingdom and the kingdom is kinda important for the deck to work. *Don't search Table of Contents, with Table of Contents! There is no reason to deck thin in a toon deck. *Only attack with BLS if you swing for game, removal is worth more in most cases. *When you go first, there is no reason to select BLS as a summoning option for Page-Flip, select DM, Red-eyes and Masked Sorcerer. *When you can special a toon, you usually do it in defense, because they can't attack anyways in most cases and it protects from Utopia Double. *Use DM to search Terror, Briefcase or to special BLS (or Red-eyes when BLS is in hand).  *Bookmark can search Comic hand, but NOT Briefcase, keep that in mind because you will often have Bookmark+Table of Contents in your hand. *Comic hand helps to swing for game. *If you didn't quite make game with attacking, just use Crackdown or Comic hand to grab opponents monsters for a cowboy, or special Cannon soldier from deck with DM. *Attack with masked sorcerer first to see your options after the draw. *Don't use floodgates if not necessary! You don't want to be locked in on Summon limit or Tcboo against sky striker. *Against Meta decks you wait and use Crackdown on essential combo pieces, like jet synchron, aleister, golden lord or an adamcipator tuner. Against rough decks you can use crackdown on the normal summon. In a lot of cases it ends their turn.
