deck_excerpt: Invoked Shaddoll list for the June 2020 format.
deck_description: Back on Invoked Shaddoll, since my foray into Nekroz basically made me wish I was playing Shaddolls instead. The goal was to flex somewhere between the combo version and the straight Winda Turbo version, and running a lot of very specific interaction pieces to try and combat the format.  I wanted room for at least 9 interaction in the deck, to increase the odds of seeing a hand-trap. However, I also felt that Called By The Grave was essential for Eldlich the Golden Lord, which natively outs Winda. It seems like the matchup against Eldlich is super rough, so I wanted to run cards that were good against Eldlich or Adamancipator. With Eldlich heavy on the combo build and most decks incorporating a Needlefibre Package, Nibiru seemed like an obvious pick, particularly since it is a light monster. I went with D.D. Crow over Effect Veiler, mostly because it helps make Winda in a pinch, but also to snipe Golden Lords out of the GY while still stopping or stalling Adamancipator combos.  The Invoked engine is obligatory. These cards are very powerful, and have huge synergy in the fusion deck. 3 of all of them, and Terraforming to search Meltdown. After that its pretty ordinary numbers of Shaddoll cards for a deck without Desires. Juggler and Trick Clown are the last engine, they just help make the 1 card combos off of Shaddoll Fusion much better and give us light fodder to use to make Constructs or Mechaba.  I almost never go into Apkallone, but monster negation comes in clutch, and it's searching/sending ability is super useful as a floating effect. 2 Construct and 3 Winda are my usual numbers. I want to have multiple Winda for when 1 gets broken, and I like running 3 so that when people are sniping my extra deck with Lysogasm they have to go for all the Winda to deny me it. Mechaba is the main Invoked card, it gives us a good negate, even if its rarely an omni-negate. Purgatrio breaks boards, and Raidjin turns things face down. Almiraj and Gardna give us ways to get Aleister in the GY, while giving us access to 1 card Mechabas or Purgatrios that add Aleister to the hand. Cross Sheep makes the link 4 plays possible, with Borrelsword to OTK and Apollousa for some added negation, which also makes it possible to combo off to end on a board with Winda, Apollousa, and Mechaba.  3 Effect Veiler and 3 Impermanence are for combo decks, particularly Amamancipator. Sometimes you need all 9 hand traps. Cyclone and Lightning Storm are for Backrow decks, with Cyclone also coming in over Nibiru against Eldlich game 2. Dark Ruler No More is just a habit, it will allow the deck to break a lot of otherwise completely unbreakable boards even if it falls short against the main meta decks.

This deck is a HERO deck that, aside from fusion summoning out big monsters, can quite easily and consistently turbo out a Plasma to rip a monster off the field and act as a one-sided skill drain. You would usually normal summon Stratos to search out a Plasma and then make the Vision hero combo starting from Faris. It is not the best at playing the long game so you would have to combo out everything in turn 1 and possibly OTK in turn 2 or 3. The deck isn't that good competitively or anything, Just a really fun deck to run.     My Rating:  Attack: 5/5  Defense: 3/5  Consistency: 5/5  Stamina: 2/5  Strong Against: Dragun Spam, Cyber Dragon  Weak Against: Dragma, Sky Striker  Vision Hero Faris + Stratos Combo  Cards in hand: Faris, any other HERO for Faris to dump  Activate Faris, discard the other HERO and SS itself  Activate Faris, search for Increase and put it in the S/T zone  Activate Increase, tribute Faris to SS it  Activate Increase, SS Vyon from the deck  Activate Vyon, send Malicious to the GY  Activate Malicious, SS another one from the deck  Activate Vyon's other effect, search a Poly  Link off Malicious and Increase for a Cross Crusader  Activate Cross Crusader, SS Malicious from the GY  Tribute Malicious with Cross Crusader's effect and grab a Stratos to the hand  NS Stratos to search for Liquid Soldier  Poly the Stratos and Liquid Soldier for a Sunrise  Use Liquid Soldier for a draw 2 discard 1  Activate the Sunrise, search Miracle Fusion  Banish the Stratos and the  Liquid Soldier to make Absolute Zero  End your turn. If you have Plasma in your hand you can play it, but if you want to use its effect effectively you need to go second or wait a turn to nick a monster. If you want to you can tribute Absolute zero for Plasma but it will nuke all the monsters your opponent controls so you most likely wouldn't be able to use Plasma.  Overall this deck is a very aggressive deck that has the potential to completely wipe out boards and deal with troublesome threats with Plasma (He doesn't target!!!). Stay safe and have fun!

deck_excerpt: Fun; Cheap; Meta Rokket Dragon Link
deck_description: The deck is based on the SD Rokket Revolt, you just need to buy some other cards (OCG card for lower prices) There's 3 combos; it'll be better if you have White Dragon or Black Dragon in your opening hand -------- 1st: Absorouter Dragon/Noctovision Dragon + Quick Launch + White Dragon - Activate Quick Launch --> summon Rokket Tracer --> sepcial summon Absorouter/Noctovision Dragon - Link summon those two to Dragunity Knight - Romulus (Romulus eff chain 1) --> Absorouter eff chain 2 (you can add 1 random rokket) (Noctovison eff chain 2 for chain block) - Activate Dragon Ravine (discard 1 random card to send a dragon from your deck to GY) --> send Galactic Spiral Dragon - Normal summon a rokket you just added to your hand; special summon White Dragon by bannishing 1 DARK monster (Absorouter/Noctovison) - IMPORTANT PART: Link summon 1 of those dragon to Guardragon Elpy to the zone Romulus points to --> the other dragon to Striker Dragon (add Boot Sector Launch) (and White Dragon effect that lets you add Black Dragon) --> active Elpy effect: special summon 1 dragon from your deck to the zone TWO LINK MONSTER POINT TO (Romulus and Striker Dragon) --> special summon Black Metal Dragon. - Activate Striker Dragon effect: destroy it to add Rokket Tracer back to your hand from GY --> link Black Metal to Guardragon Pisty --> Metal effect: add Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon to your hand -->  special summon Red-Eyes by banishing Elpy --> Red-Eyes effect: special summon any dragon from your GY (except White Dragon). - Link Red-eyes and that dragon to Dillingerous Dragon --> Pisty effect: special summon back Red-eyes --> link Dillingerous and Pisty to Galaxy Satellite Dragon. - Use Red-eyes effect --> special summon Rokket Tracer --> special summon Black Dragon by banishing White Dragon --> use Tracer effect destroy Dragon Ravine to special summon any LV 4 rokket monsters - Use Rokket Tracer and Black Dragon for Draco Bererker; other rokket and Glalaxy for Quadborrel Dragon --> Quadborrel effective: discard Boot Sector Launch (what remain in your hand) destroy itself to special summon back Rokker Tracer and any LV 4 rokket monster --> use them for Borreload Salvage Dragon --> Salvage effect: equip Galaxy Satelilte to it. End Board: Draco Berserker; Borreload Salvage 2 counter and 4000 atk; Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon (for next turn dragons resurrect it needed); Dragunity Knight - Romulus. At the first step you can link to Crystron Halqifibrax 2nd: 1 rokket tunner + 2 lv 4 rokket (+ White Dragon) 3rd: White Dragon + Quick Launch They're pretty much the same end board as long as you have White Dragon in your opening hand.

deck_excerpt: Rokket Dragon FTK. 8000 Damage by your opponent's Standby Phase.
deck_description: FTK changes everything. Real unsure of this version, but I want those high chances to see my starters, so I'm trying this out. I tried to just slice out as many of the bricks as possible to run 3 Called + 9 Hand Traps so that we have a shot going second game 1. But I think the right way to play the FTK is to go all in on it and just try and kill people. Even slight changes in your chances of seeing a specific starter can make a big difference over a large number of games.  Since the originator of the FTK seems to have done calcs and determined the original 60 card deck had great odds of FTKing, even through hand traps. As a result, I changed my mentality on seeing 1 card starters, and decided to trim down on engines I thought were unnecessary while still running as many cards as I wanted. This also let me pump up the hand traps, making space for Gamma, meaning more high impact ways to secure a win going second. All the cards are also full combo with Chaos Space and One For One, and D.D. Crow is a viable normal summon to make Romulus with (Phantazmay is only here to be used as an extender, but hey, draw some cards off our opponent's plays).  I'm already back to 60. I kept upping the hand trap count to improve my odds of seeing 2 hand traps, even in a 60 card deck. To compensate I put back in extenders, White Rose Dragon, which makes seeing a dragon less bricky while still being an extender, and Monster Reborn, which is full combo with any normal summon of a Dragon. I'm also on 3 Exploderokket, so that even if we see 1 copy we don't brick out - we have to see 2 copies of explode or a total of 4 bricks to brick out. It will happen, but not very often.  Option 1 is FTK after making a Negate. Option 2 is the buster lock. Option 3 is Nibiru token + Borrelsword OTK, but this is largely irrelevant, since the deck FTKs much more consistently than it sees Nibiru. It is worth keeping in the back of your mind.  The normal Route for the combo is using Borrelsword or Borreload to fire off on Exploderokket to deal 2000 dmage after equipping your Borrel Dragon with Piscu. Then on your opponent's turn, you use the Tracer you get off of Explode to fire on Piscu, clearing a board full of plants created by Black Garden to deal 4000 damage. Then your Borrel Dragon fires off on the Explode Tracer summoned for the last 2000.  So hear me out, but I think this deck might actually be tier 0. I replaced Called By the Grace with World Chalice Guardragon. There are 2 reasons for this. The deck needs a lot of hand traps, because in the mirror you are screwed if you can't both prevent them from making Herald AND stop them from using Union Carrier. This takes at least 2 hand traps, and while all of our hand traps are relatively high impact, and capable of performing that role in multiples while being combo pieces, you might notice the highest impact of them in fact special summon themselves, and that Phantazmay doesn't do much in the mirror going second but dig for Nibiru. I think the built-in synergy of being a combo card that Brainstorms and protects your combos is reasonable, but these probably should be sided out in the mirror, or replaced with Imperm if this deck does become Tier 0. World Chalice Guardragon doesn't combo with Chaos Space, but it does perform full combo with any Dragon Extender, and just as importantly, it protects Union Carrier, which is really the whole plan of the deck when you think about it. It seems like the most vital place to attack the deck in the mirror, and it CAN protect from Imperm and Gamma, which Called cannot. It can also be an extender if you've pitched Driver (or made Needlefibre on your turn), not super relevant but it can come up.  3 Tracers comes up in a deck with no other level 4 Rokkets. Rokket Synchron still hasn't come up, so I'm running the third Tracer.

deck_excerpt: Quad-Splash Pure Zombie deck. Mayakashi,shiranui,eldlich, Zombie world control.
deck_description:
This is a versatile, unpredictable, Zombie-fest. Only instead of relying on chance, I've catered it to be easily manipulated into one of 4 strategies. I've purposely stayed as on zombie theme as possible. At a glance some of the card choices, and some cards that I dont use (draganecro, rivalry, super poly to name a few) may seem odd. But, it's all for an easily manipulated flow.     I'll name a few combos, but if you enjoy pure zombie bashing like I do you will get the hang of it hopefully. At first I would brood over turns, having the starters for 3 separate valuable combos in hand with extenders already on field and balerdroch waiting to negate ash. But, after a while you learn what's useful when. I've worked on this for roughly 2 months now. Made of what I physically own, though I have ALOT of zombies. It could use another golden lord, and it wouldn't hurt to ditch haquero and book of life for 3x called by sided. All....ALL thoughts,recommendations, and criticism is welcomed. Help me make this deck be fun, versitale, and meta viable. Please keep in mind it is a pure zombie deck. I think bomber dragon is my only non zombie and I put him in here to break well established boards. I was noticing the deck lacked a dark hole or raigeki wipe. But, I wanted to keep the trend of not relying on chance alot.   Now onto the strats. Monster manipulation through the multiple "send from deck to gy" cards and thinning if you chose to activate each eldlixir and golden land card the moment you can, then banish asap to cycle em through. Extra deck choices: mayakashi and shiranui full synchro 1 ofs except for yoko, its strangely easy for this deck to pop out synchros, zombie-skull for either extra punch, to force an offensive response if your opponent is turtleing or to rank up with another tuner. Links: sucker for draw power and to start the link ladder, savior "sends" dakki if you wanna do the ole mayakashi roulette or mezuki for SS from GY or gozuki for SS from hand or glow up bloom for SS from deck or if you dont have zombie world out yet (it's out by turn 2 for me consistently) then send banshee. I've also been crafty before, had supremacy and Bayonater on field beside dakki, opponent thinks I'm going for mayakashi, link bayonater and supremacy bring out bomber dragon activate spectralsword in gy with spiritmaster, summon samuraisaga and destroy opponents face up (alternatively I could have used spectralsword with bayonater and double juked into mayakashi roulette avoiding bombers zones) but then tune dakki w samuraisaga boom you just went full into a whole other 2 boss monsters that weren't mayakashi. I'm definitely going to make this too long but, I'm committed and excited to share this with the community. I've searched so hard seeing decks that where good but not GREAT and upon the realization that a more than casual pure zombie deck was possible because of the hidden summoner and secret slayer support I buckled down, my phone and laptop didnt give me a solid look, something about laying the cards out in front of me helps me visualize ratios and patterns. Then I take it to the screen and trouble shoot. Anyways.. Spell choices: I'll address the elephant, mayakashi winter is bricky, but really read it and look back through what I've compiled, 2 Yoko's, 2 spirit master, mid game that's an easy 2 destroys or I mean you get it there are just so many routes you just judge the board and focus on keeping hand advantage. It's easy to use your entire hand first turn and establish a pretty strong board, it's even easier for your opponent to slap a nibaru down and grab a quick win for his deck. Also, winter sends dakki from field for a plus 1, if you can SS a lvl 3,5,7,or 9 synchro then you got a hitter. I have 2 allures for draw power because its euphoric to then use samsara to pull em from banish to deck AND DRAW AGAIN. That's crazy... use 2 effects only sending to gy allure so only loosing 1 card, in order to return 2 banished tuners to deck (easily searched) and draw 3 cards. Mayakashi return is situational as well, use it to send one of the monsters or pull em to hand or search for winter if you already went through the roulette. 1 foolish burial and 1 monster reborn, because that's how I got the brick ratio down....honestly.....running 3 zombie world I've sided a terraforming and have 2 banshees. You will learn (if you dont currently know) what decks you want to have zombie world out first turn for and what decks to side out both banshees and a copy of it to improve another strat for. Also, if you "send from deck to grave" eldlich you can use his effect easy, then with him on the field all of those confining spells that can only pull him out become doorways to options. Eldlixirs SS from hand deck and gy, (depending which you use) and have 0 restriction as long as you got eldlich on field. Onto traps: samsara has saved this deck from loss more than I ever imagined it could when I threw it in on a whim. This card is soooooo underrated, it can banish 1 of yours from field, and there are plenty of reasons why that's good and you are safe for that turn. Even if your opponent msts it or something, it also returns your tuners and synchros to the deck and nets (if you choose synchros you dont shuffle and therefore do not draw).  The golden land monsters are basically my zombie version of Called by and a clean "destroy 1 face up" as you can see there are multiple ports for card destruction. I've actually used Conquistadors summon to destroy a gozuki I had summoned for a "sends" and got to SS and banish from gy. The eldlixir of scarlet sanguine, I hate this but.....they're gonna be bait. Idk why but, people see the eldlixir trap (sanguine) and just have to negate or destroy it while set. Its gonna happen over and over just start telling yourself its bait now, it's the best one of all of them bc it SS from deck n gy but, I've almost never gotten to resolve it.
  1. Hmmm, side deck stuff: some double and triple prints to bend the deck in-between matches so if you face-off against a previous onlooker you can throw them off, ghost sister and swallow slash where my answer to avoiding nibaru, and it's all beneficial. Fraulein is a special card, he can steal magician girls or dark magicians to keep em away from their supports, or empower an already ridiculous shogunsaga for a HUGE beater, or, to keep that extender or balerdroch or whatever on the field for a turn longer. Typically I'll side in ghost sister if I'm going to also run fraulein to recover some of the LP. The opponent will either go off anyway hoping they have enough turns to dwindle you back down, half combo just enough to keep em in the game which typically is still a nice chunk and I've found is the least successful response unless your running low atk, and the dreaded third response, my favorite one, they stick to normal summon and end turn. Now you have nothing for lifepoints, and your card worked. You wanted to halt special summons and that you did, what the opponent dosent know is that you wanted this, you had drawn ghost sister first turn and awaited the right time to strike..turn 7..combo into bomber, attack and use fraulein, pay all but 100 LPs, opponent trys to negate HA! Flip solomn judgement and cut 100 to 50, attack with all your might, differential LP damage on top of the opponents monsters atk reflected, and if they had created one of those boards they think is unbreakable, then summon fraulein 1 spot over and wipe the field still judgmenting a negate.
In summary, i prefer choice to chance, and zombies over all in this game I've been playing my whole life.      I look forward to the responses that will aid to improve the deck. But, I urge you to get a small feel for it first, bc it's so fun to just decide what kinda deck you are gonna play, stop mid-combo and link into something that starts a combo for another strat....i understand I'm being ambitious with a "Quad Splash" but, there is something here. This deck took on, adamancipater and skystriker with victories. Orcust, as long as you hold out until they setup and then find a way to wipe it (many destroys and banishes or bomber) then throw down lethal. Shaddolls hate zombieworld/balerdroch combo, if you can pop out 1 or 2 more negates (hand traps or solomn, etc.) Then setup the mayakashi roulette its typically over the next few turns, if They overpower or effect kill your skeletal mayakashi you get to unwind into yoko and destroy a card saving your remaining negates and purposely letting that turn pass to refresh balerdrochs negate.   Monster: Shiranui Swordmaster x1 Tsukahagi, the Poisonous Mayakashi x1 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring x3 Jack-o-Bolan x1 Shiranui Spectralsword x2 Doomking Balerdroch x2 Shiranui Squire x2 Dakki, the Graceful Mayakashi x1 Bayonater, the Baneful Barrel x1 Uni-Zombie x3 Gozuki x1 Necroworld Banshee x2 Shiranui Spectralsword Shade x1 Mezuki x2 Glow-Up Bloom x2 Shiranui Solitaire x3 Eldlich the Golden Lord x1 Shiranui Spiritmaster x2 Spell: Allure of Darkness x2 Mayakashi Return x1 Zombie World x3 Cursed Eldland x1 Mayakashi Winter x1 Eldlixir of Black Awakening x2 Foolish Burial x1 Monster Reborn x1 Eldlixir of White Destiny x1 Trap: Conquistador of the Golden Land x2 Eldlixir of Scarlet Sanguine x2 Shiranui Style Samsara x1 Huaquero of the Golden Land x1 Extra: Yoko, the Graceful Mayakashi x2 Tengu, the Winged Mayakashi x1 Topologic Bomber Dragon x1 Oboro-Guruma, the Wheeled Mayakashi x1 Vampire Sucker x1 Gashadokuro, the Skeletal Mayakashi x1 Shiranui Squiresaga x1 Shiranui Samuraisaga x1 Shiranui Sunsaga x1 Archfiend Zombie-Skull x1 Tsuchigumo, the Poisonous Mayakashi x1 Shiranui Shogunsaga x1 Shiranui Skillsaga Supremacy x1 Avendread Savior x1 Side: Book of Life x1 Shiranui Style Swallow's Slash x1 Vampire Fraulein x1 Conquistador of the Golden Land x1 Eldlixir of Scarlet Sanguine x1 Cursed Eldland x1 Plaguespreader Zombie x1 Solemn Judgment x2 Ghost Sister & Spooky Dogwood x1 Terraforming x1 Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion x2 Glow-Up Bloom x1 Huaquero of the Golden Land x1

deck_excerpt: Thunder Dragons with Toon Chaos support and a mini lightsworn engine
deck_description:
Lightsworn Chaos Thunder

What is this deck trying to do? The goal of this deck is to end on a Thunder Dragon Titan + Any LINK-4. If going first, you can set up an Apollousa for 3 or a Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. If you're going second, you want to make Borrelsword or Accesscode Talker and go for game. How does this deck work? Every card in this deck falls into one of three categories: Starter, Thunder Dragon, and Extender. Any starter + any Thunder Dragon + Any extender can end on a Titan and a LINK-4. Bread and Butter Combo: Given that you have an starter, a Thunder Dragon, and an extender in hand, the combo is as follows:
  1. Activate your starter and send Thunder Dragonroar
  2. If the Roar is in grave, use your extender to banish it. Once banished, special summon a Thunder Dragondark
  3. Link your starter and the Dark into a Cross-Sheep
  4. Search Thunder Dragon Fusion with the Dark (If you already have it in hand, you can search for a Thunder Dragonhawk to extend even further, or a Thunder Dragon to pop cards with Titan)
  5. Use the Thunder Dragon card in your hand's effect (or any other way to get it out of your hand), then use Thunder Dragon Fusion to make Titan.
  6. Use Cross-Sheep's effect to resurrect your starter.
  7. You now have enough monsters on the field to go into Apollousa for 3, Crusadia Avramax, Borrelsword, or Accesscode.
A three card combo? That's too much Since the entire deck is comprised of cards that fall into these three categories, it's relatively easy to get the pieces you need. Also, some cards have the ability to function as multiple types of cards (ie. Thunder Dragonhawk is both a Thunder Dragon and an extender) Why are you running Lightsworns? Dangers are better You can run Dangers, but you might not have enough space to run them all in a 40 card deck. In testing, I found that the deck's biggest issue was getting enough cards in the grave on the early turns, and the Lightsworn engine helps with that greatly. You also need cards in the grave for your extenders, and this is the best engine to do so. Raiden is also a light, which means you can banish it or pitch it to Chaos Space.

  • I debated whether to do R3 axis or Isolde deck, ended up mixing both with slight preference for Isolde, I am happy with the result.

  • Tear scale is 1 card anything you want, whether its Isolde, Cherubini, Curious, Guardragon combo

  • Stained Greaves is fantastic to because he enables Utopia Kaiser shananigans, which translates to Kali yuga as I have showed

  • Wing Raiders / Raiders wing (Whatever its called) is more of Raidraptor support. He doesn't help the deck

  • New Rank-up is just a "phantom" compared to our beloved Rank-up magic launch (Good in RR tho). You can summon Air Raider which ll then target and pop their monster... + cloak cant search it.

deck_name: Nostalgy Time - An Extensive Guide on How to Play Toons
deck_excerpt: Hello dear duelists! My name is Maximillion ... Should you want to master the Toon Archetype, and enhance your Yu-Gi-Oh knowledge, please feel free to
deck_description:
Nostalgy Time - An extensive guide on how to play Toons - June 2020 Introduction: The Toon Archetype got a huge boost recently, with the release of the Toon Chaos Booster Box. New additions to the Toon Series would certainly have made Pegasus proud, and might also have reconciliated the fans with Konami. Long neglected by the firm, the archetype was withering away, filled with cards that were far too old, and therefore full of constraints that no longer make sense in today’s metagame. Fortunately, Konami brought out the heavy artillery to the delight of the early fans, offering us some crazy search engines and one boss monster to fuel the deck! Warning: Don’t get me wrong, the deck may be very fun to play at locals, it is far from being able to compete against any real Tier 1 meta deck. Some would say it could fall in the Rogue category, at most. That being said, let’s dig in! In-Depth Analysis: Strengths:
  • Amazing consistency thanks to the addition of Toon Bookmark and Toon Page-Flip. Toon Table of Contents remains one of the best searchers of the entire game, basically enabling you to pick any Toon card from your deck, while not even being limited to one activation per turn.
  • Ability to easily summon ignoring the summoning conditions, which is abused by the deck’s strategy.
  • The powerful field spell Toon Kingdom acts like a protection for all your creatures.
  • Dealing Direct Damage: your Toons can pass through any threatening body, as they can attack your opponent directly (as long as Toon World / Kingdom is on the field).
Weaknesses:
  • Lack of Explosiveness: there is no such thing as huge combos involving tons of summons with the Toon archetype. You won’t be able to set up any kind of lockdown or establish a powerful end board with multiple negations. That is the main reason why I find the “Going 2nd" approach for the deck way more effective.
  • Toon Kingdom being one the greatest strengths of the deck, it also appears to be a double-edged sword! Indeed, the deck relies heavily on this sole card: all the strategy depends on your capacity to put it on the field. Should this card be countered (destroyed / banished / negated), you will have a hard time trying to recover.
  • Draw Power: there is no real Toon draw engine worth playing in the deck. That is why Pot of Extravagance comes in handy.
  • Bricks: to a lesser extent, some Toons can end up being dead draws in hand as most of of them have a high level. One notable example is Red-Eyes Toon Dragon that we often do not want to draw (not always the case though).
Strategy: Going 1st: Do not overcommit on the board, try to protect your Kingdom, and set up Toon Terror (search it). Ideally, you would end up with one big toon on board (Red-Eyes, Toon Black Luster Soldier (BLS) or Toon Dark Magician (DM)), Toon Kingdom, Toon Terror, and one Bookmark in grave. If you get lucky, you will also end up with a hand trap for some more negates. This end board might not look that impressive, but with one negation and one Kingdom protection (Bookmark), you can still manage to survive your opponent’s next offensive. Keep in mind this deck is built to go 2nd. If you go first, you just want to slow down your opponent in order to get a chance to break his board and overwhelm him on your 2nd turn. Going 2nd: This is where the fun begins! Try to interrupt their combos with hand traps. Linkross, Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon & Crystron Halqifibrax are obviously good targets to consider by the time I am writing this. Get rid of your opponent’s board with Evenly Match (EM) if you open it. Based on the state of the board, it is up to you to decide whether you need to bait your opponent with EM or another card instead. Choose wisely which card you want to resolve the most. Remember that you do not really care if your rival has big bodies on board as your toons can attack directly and are indestructible thanks to the field spell. On the other hand, you would rather want to get rid of backrows or sneaky Effect monsters that could potentially endanger your Kingdom. Then, you must set up your Castle at all costs because without this cartoon-like fortress, your monsters are weak and powerless. Main Strategy / “Combo”: Extend on board. The Black Stone of Legend + DM and any other Toon card in hand --> Normal Summon Black Stone, Special Summon (SS) Red-Eyes --> SS DM with Red-Eyes Effect --> SS BLS with DM effect sending the Toon card to the grave. You can overlay DM + Red-Eyes for a Rank 7 play. For instance, Xyz Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon in order to revive Red-Eyes with its effect, or Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack to destroy a card on the field. Use BLS to push for damage or banish another card. Strategy 2 / Emergency plan: Effective against backrows deck. If you did not draw EM, and have to face a board full of set cards / or annoying creatures, you will want to play as much BLS as possible, one after the other. Let’s say you summoned the first one through Page-Flip, use its effect (banish), then SS another one from hand, tributing the BLS on the field, banish another card, and repeat this operation one last time. You end up with only one BLS on field, but you banished 3 cards. The BLS banishing effect is a soft “once per turn”, take advantage of it! The entire deck is very searchable and reminds me a bit of the Nekroz search engine. Thanks to Bookmark and Toon Table, you will be able to consistently select which tactic to use in order to adapt to your opponent, as you will have access to any specific Toon card. Hence, depending on the situation you are dealing with, there is plenty of options available, which I describe below: Toon Toolbox:
  • Facing a powerful Link Monster? Use Toon Cyber Dragon to Megafleet your opponent’s extra monster zone.
  • Search for Toon Harpie Lady if you want to quickly get rid of a Spell or Trap card.
  • Any useful card in your opponent’s grave? Search for Mimicat and steal it.
  • Any annoying monster on your opponent’s field? Go for Comic Hand instead … and steal it!
  • Want to set up an omni negate? Search for Toon Terror.
  • Need to summon a big boy? Activate Toon Page-Flip --> always choose BLS + Red-Eyes + DM. Then, depending on which one is randomly picked, adapt your following play / strategy.
  • Need an Extender ? Search for Toon Cyber Dragon or Toon Harpie Lady.
Rational behind Ratios: 3x BLS: Best Toon so far, nothing to add, great stats, great effect, relatively easy to summon. 2x Red-Eyes: you do not want to open it, it is a brick. You only want to SS it through Black Stone. 3x Black Stones: combo starter. You want to open it. This is your only normal summon. It gets you Red-Eyes which gets you another Toon from hand in return. 3x DM: you want to open it in order to SS it through Red-Eyes effect. If you need some space for a specific tech, you may remove one. I am still debating on the right ratio. 1x Comic Hand / Harpie Lady / Mimicat / Cyber Dragon / Toon Terror --> you do not want to open them, you want to search one if needed for a very specific purpose. 3x Evenly Matched: very strong going 2nd card + you usually do not set up big board going first, so you can still get good value from it in case your defense gets wiped out. 3x Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring / Infinite Impermanence: really depends on the meta, any hand trap will do. Main objective is to disrupt your opponent's play to contain their board. Tips:
  • Always use Extravagance first 😉
  • If you do not have another Bookmark in hand, always Toon Table into Bookmark into another Toon card in order to set up your Kingdom’s protection in grave ! Very important!
  • DM and Red-Eyes cannot attack directly the turn they are summoned. BLS CAN.
  • Toon Table cannot search Mimicat & Comic Hand, Bookmark CAN.
  • If Page-Flip or Bookmark gets negated, please re-read this again and again: "If you negate the activation of a card that can only be activated once per turn then you may activate another copy of said card again in that same turn."
  • What do you want to see in your opening hand going 2nd? Bookmark / Page-Flip / Kingdom & Field searchers (Terraforming / Set Rotation) / Table / Black Stone & DM / Evenly Matched / Hand Traps
  • Do not forget to use Black Stone Effect in Grave !
  • You can swap the Evenly Matched playset for 3 Nibiru, The Primal Being if you face too many spam / combo decks --> You can steal the token with comic hand and swing with it for ... maybe game ?!
Other Toon cards to consider:
  • Toon Gemini Elf is tempting because of the discard effect, but too slow as they cannot attack the turn they are summoned.
  • Similarly, Toon Masked Sorcerer drawing effect looks nice at first sight, but it also requires one turn to be activated + 900 ATK is really bad.
  • Toon Ancient Gear Golem if you wish to increase chances to be able to summon BLS.
  • Potentially Toon Mermaid x3 if you add Bahamut Shark and Toadally Awesome to your Extra deck, but then, you would change the whole deck structure. You would need to switch to an Xyz Rank 4 focused deck and adapt your extra deck accordingly. It is not optimal at all in my opinion. And Mermaid alone is full garbage, the card being too old.
  • Toon Briefcase if you want to improve your Going First plays.
  • Toon Mask is too slow, not worth the effect.
Extra Deck: Multiple copies because we play Extravagance --> C-O-N-S-I-S-T-E-N-C-Y !!!!
  • 2 Starving Venom Fusion Dragon and 2 Mudragon of the Swamp for the Super Poly Engine. You might also consider Predaplant Dragostapelia instead if you face lots of fusion-based decks such as Heroes.
  • 2 Red Eyes Flare and 2 Dracossack for the Xyz 7 plays. No Number 11: Big Eye because Comic Hand does the job already.
  • 3 Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon because I really do not want all copies to get banished faced down by Extravagance!! Megafleet is really strong going 2nd against most decks, and your opponent will never play around on game one if he does not know your deck.
  • 1 Relinquished Anima because sometimes, you have an extra copy of Black Stone in hand, and also because Pegasus / Relinquished you know? More serioulsy, people are not used to it yet and somet players forget to play around. You could replace it for any powerfull link 3 monster such as Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos, or another Link 1 Salamangreat Almiraj for extra-protection.
  • Combo Accesscode Talker + Eria the Water Charmer, Gentle = revive back opponent's Halqifibrax with Eria, link into Accesscode. As simple as that.
Hope you learnt one or two things with this guide ! Should you have any question, or remark to improve the list, please feel free to ask in the comment section below! Thanks for your attention! Yuuuuuuugi Boy!

deck_excerpt: The new rank 5 Vespenate ties Ancient Gear and Machina together. A single Redeployment ends on Apollousa, Avramax, Block Dragon, and Howitzer. We will
deck_description: The new rank 5 Vespenate the Spinbreaker enables the synergy between Ancient Gear and Machina. The end board with Apollousa, Avramax, Howitzer, and Block Dragon is easily achieved with a single Redeployment or any of Gearframe + Irradiator/Possesstorage, making the consistency is somewhat acceptable. Bricking wont be a big issue as you will play regular Citadel control or handtraps. We will have 4 Ancient Gears (Frame, Box, Ballista, and Howitzer) too along the way if you didnt banish them for Block Dragon, it means we can follow up for Chaos Ancient Gear Giant via Verte/Overload Fusion. We dont use Halq in the combo, it's just there for follow up play/free plus. The combo is super long, I will upload the replay tutorial (it uses Codebreaker package it means you gotta free the link 3 zones for them). https://bit.ly/3er2PVX The Machina lineup consists of Irradiator, Gearframe, Possesstorage (great in grind game), and Redeployment as 3 ofs for our combo starter. 1 Citadel and 3 Overdrive is there as Citadel control and recycles your banished machines, esp since we use Overload Fusion and Block Dragon. The Ancient Gear package is small as theyre just combo pieces being Ancient Gear Fusion, Box, Frame, and Overload Fusion (Chaos Giant follow up via Verte). Rock lineup enables further spamming mid-combo despite being bricks (lol). Block Dragon (easily searched and summoned along the way, watch the replay), Adaman Researcher and Seeker, Weeping Idol, and 3 Gigantes. The rest is just handtrap as well as Crossout target (not TCG legal yet) and generic backrow removal. Pros: Themed, end board is hard to penetrate without strong cards like DRNM, Sphere Mode, etc. Combo can adapt going first or otk. Cons: Bricking hard. Cards to think of: Machina Fortress is good in grind game but with negs. Ancient Gear Wyvern works via Ballista/Howitzer for free plus if we draw Frame/Box but it is another brick.

deck_excerpt: Zombie deck using Lightsworn as an engine. Exploit Uni-Zombie + graveyard effects
deck_description: Use cards like Shiranui Solitaire and Charge of the Light Brigade to bring out Uni-Zombie. Use it's abilties to send Mezuki, Necroworld Banshee to the graveyard and spam their effects to get the Synchron monsters you want. Use Lightsworns to fill out your graveyard and Burial From a different Dimension to return banished cards to use all over again. Eldich is useful to negate and summon another monster that fills your field with powerful cards and Doomking Balerdroch can be helpful in certain situations. Your Uni-Zombie should effectively bring out the right cards you need in order to wipe the opponent's effects and lifepoints before you can deck out. If some cards feel weird, that's because they are. Minerva isn't a perfect fit but can be helpful and sometimes Zombie Master is redundant. Have fun toying with it.

So I have played Six Sams for a while, and every time I make a deck my sole purpose: Fulfil the conditions needed for "The Six Shinobi". I rarely actually manage to do this though :P  Anyways, this deck's main purpose is to swarm the field with different Attributes of Monsters, then activate Six Shinobi to stall for another turn and attack for game. Great Shogun isn't really useful unless your opponent has Dimension Barrier or something, but that's just my opinion. So yeah.  Also, pls dont spam me with comments saying I copied someone else. This deck's style is kind of similar to someone else's, but I did not copy them. Thanks

deck_excerpt: The Gladiator Beasts (GBs) are an archetype of monsters with various attributes that seek to dominate the board using it's unique style of 'tag out' s
deck_description: The Gladiator Beasts (GBs) are an archetype of monsters with various attributes that seek to dominate the board using it's unique style of 'tag out' special summoning and contact fusion ability. After battling, GBs are able to shuffle themselves into the deck and bring out a different GB (unlocking it's dormant effect at the same time). With this ability, GBs are able to quickly swarm the field, setting them up for Fusion Summoning. GB Fusion monsters don't have to use Polymerization, but instead are summoned by shuffling the fusion material into the deck. What's better is that after battling, the fusion monsters can also be shuffled into the deck to bring out 2 GBs ! One of the most important Main Deck Monsters in the deck is Gladiator Beast Augustus, with it's cool ability to bring out another GB from your hand (plus it's effect) It is a Level 7 with 2600/1000 stats. The key Extra Deck Monster is Gladiator Beast Tamer Edition, who can bring out a new GB fusion monster each turn! It's stats are 2400/3000 Spell cards such as Gladiator Rejection allow you to special summon an edition monster in defence while preventing your monsters from being targeted by your opponents, and the Field Spell Colosseum - Cage of the Gladiator Beasts gives your monsters an extra 100 ATK/DEF each time a monster is special summoned from either players deck, giving you a great advantage!

deck_excerpt: Xyz Summons using Special Summons and uses "Flip" effects to search more Geargias to Xyz Summon. Instant Fusion gets out an Elder Entity to bring out
deck_description: With the use of Castel, the "Flip" Effects that the Geargias use can be triggered off easily. The Book of Taiyou is another great addition, and I would run 3. Book of Moon is better off on side deck. The Elder Entity helps get your Geargias out of your hand with the use of Instant Fusion. Xyz Summons are done Quickly and Easily with cards like Geargiaccelerator, Gadgets and Geargianos that I run here. I side deck the Rank 3 and I play the Wind Ups too! They can flip easily. As for the Dreadnoughts, I usually Xyz into them with the Geargias and the Geargianos. I usually use Ancient Gear Box with Geargiauger to search the Geargias faster, but the Disadvantage for this is that I can't get my Geargiaccelerator with this, so I usually recurr to reusing Geargiarmor's "Flip" effect to search it, or the Gear Gigant X. Usually the Geargias that go to the Grave I bring them back with either Monster Reborn, Geargiano, and Geargiano MK-II. Mk-III I just keep one of that guy there to get out any Geargias out fast. Basically Xyz Summons really quickly, and uses many Special Summons, so it does have the risk to be Nibirued. Many of the Xyz Summons can be negated, and it still needs a lot to go but this seems to be a pretty solid Deck on its own.

deck_excerpt: Noble Knight Monsters by the Destiny Hero Engine for Draw Power.
deck_description: The deck has a construction based on the Noble Knights, using the Destiny Hero motor as a support to obtain greater draw power, taking advantage of the fact that both archetypes are based on warrior monsters which provides versatility to using them also several of the Noble Arms. The first effect of "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights" serves as a seeker for both the Noble Knight and Destiny Hero monsters, In the case of the Noble Knights to have a second turn response putting in our hand the "Noble Knight Medraut" to continue with the basic combo of the Noble Knights ("Noble Knight Medraut" + "Noble Arms"), the use with Destiny Hero gives us a target for an eventual "Destiny Draw" that we have stuck in hand in the first turn. The deck takes advantage of the normal summons provided by the "Noble Knight Custennin", as it can be specially summoned to the field having the only requirement to have a "Noble Arms" face up, so use the "Destiny Hero - Decider" to equip a noble weapon , and to be able to link summon "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights". "Morgan, the Enchantress of Avalon", provides a decent cover in response to the effects that our rival can use, and if combined with the "Noble Knight Dystran", resulting in the negation of an effect and the destruction of a card face up in control of our opponent. So we will use the destiny hero engine to have "Morgan, the Enchantress of Avalon" in our hands as soon as possible. Finally, the effects of "Merlin" can provide us with protection as well as an eventual OTK, making use of the synchronized summon or exceed of our monsters.
I usually get OTKs or FTKs with this, and when I don't, my opponent surrenders and leaves me to win the match. I usually summon Spirit Dragon or Twin, but, even then, it is still a good deck.

deck_excerpt: Anti-Meta MR 5 True Draco deck with the ability to switch to a Monarch deck during matches if needed.
deck_description:
Hello everyone, this is my first submission. The deck I'm gonna present to you today is the one I currently use, it is a True Draco deck that I built when I came back to YGO in Master Rule 3, I updated it since then so it would always stay relevant and work around nerfs the archetype received. To this day, its purpose is still the same, being an excellent Anti-Meta deck that is able to have a great control of the field as well as limiting the opponent's options.

Composition :

Monsters :

  • Metaltron x1 : A very good boss monster, provided you summon it correctly it gets a full effect immunity (even to yours), it can also be discarded and called by through TK Return. We do not make use of his second effect in this deck, you are free to swap it for another monster if you wish to.
  • Dinomight x1 : Probably the best TD monster (save for the ultra-op Master Peace), which explains why he is limited. You want to get him out on the field ASAP (provided it is safe) to help setting up your continous traps.
  • Dreiath x1 : A very good monster that effectively shields your other True Draco monsters from getting rekt by most common Meta effects, it's always good to have on the field, its second effect is also very good as you. I advise running at least 1, but you can add a 2nd or even 3rd copy in your deck if you want to counter the Meta more efficiently.
  • Ignis Heat x3 : The Spell counterpart to Dinomight, it is much less strong but it is still a decent monster to have, you can remove one copy.
  • Majesty Maiden x2 : Another good monster to have, it's weaker than the other in the TD archetype but it can help you search for another TD that you need.
  • Night Dragolich x3 : A surprisingly underused card, especially with TD, it is a Wyrm monster that switches all non-Wyrm Special Summoned Monsters to Defense position as well as reducing their current Defense Value by their original Value (which often means it will be set to 0). Given the fact that all TD monsters in this deck are Wyrm, there is absolutely no reason not to use such a simple but extremely efficient monster. Seriously, keep it at 3 and enjoy.
You may be tempted to add Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder (or even Uria, Lord of Searing Flames) in a deck with so many Continous Spells (and Traps) and wonder why I don't use them. The short answer is that those are bait cards for TD decks. The long answer is that even if there probably will be a duel in which you can summon Hamon and laugh in a 4000 ATK monster that deals 1000 effect damage each time it destroys another monster and that offers attack protection to other monsters when staying in DEF mode, it would also require you to also run at least 1 or 2 copies of Cerulean Skyfire to efficiently protect and make the most out of Hamon, which would take up precious Deck Space for cards that you cannot search and that have very poor synergy (not "innexistant" because of the continous TD spells) with TD cards. I'm sorry for the long parenthesis to talk about this but it is a common mistake begginer TD players make when they want to create a deck. So, please, for the love of the Egyptian Gods, don't do that, it's genuinely trolling and will cost you much more duels than it will win you.

Spells :

  • Dragonic Diagram x1 : I would bet it is the strongest Field Spell in YGO, it is way too perfect and we are lucky (or not, depends on your side) it is not fully banned, each TD Monsters can't be destroyed in battle once EACH TURN. You can also discard any card on the field or in your hand to search for any TD card in your deck once per turn. And as a side benefit, TD monsters gain 300 ATK and DEF.
  • TD Heritage x3 : Depending on the number of TD cards you discarded during this turn, you can draw the same ammount once per turn. Needless to say it can turn up into a +2 / +3 or more on each use.
  • TD Disciples x3 : Your main (and only) recycling tool, able to save your sorry ass if Dinomight, TK Return or Dragonic Diagram are destroyed and sent to your GY, that card is much better than you might think, it can be a life saver, it also allows you to get a +1 once per activation, which is always nice in the long run.
  • Terraforming x1 : Well, do I even need to tell you why ?
  • Domain of the True Monarch x1 : This card is actually insanely good with TD, you do not run an Extra Deck here and decks relying on Tribute Summoning are very rare, locking your opponent out of their own Extra Deck. Its second effect is also very good to make up for TD's generally low ATK values. You can run more than one copy of it, don't forget you can search it with Terraforming too.
  • Card of Demise x1 : A very good instant +2 card. The prices you pay for it are no big deal, setting up a good field is better than inflicting damage and discarding unused monsters is okay since you can bring them back with TK Return or recycle them with DC Disciples.
  • Pot of Duality x3 : This card is decent, you trade it for one of the next 3 cards in your deck, it is a +0 but you get to chose what you need the most out of the options you get, and you do not Special Summon anyways.
  • The Monarch's Stormforth x1 : Give the Kaiju / Super Poly treatment to any big wall or annoying monster like Dragun or Zeus standing in your way. Sadly, that cheesy strat is dying as a lot of new boss monsters have effects preventing them to be tributed (f for Obelisk btw) or effects that allows them to negate any dangerous card once per turn, so you have to be creative to get those effects wasted first. Keep that card at one to avoid bricking !

Traps :

  • TK Return x2 : No but seriously, that card, it's just straight OP, get it on the field ASAP and make sure you can recycle it in case something bad happens to it, every turn without Return on your field is a turn you didn't play right. With its recent return to 3 copies, you can throw in a 3rd. TK Return counts as a TD Trap !
  • TD Apocalypse x3 : This card is also really OP but it smh isn't Limited or even Semi Limited, you can fuck up your opponent really badly with its effect, but we'll talk about it later.
  • The Monarchs Erupt x3 : It negates the effects of all monsters that were not Tribute Summoned, that's it, I don't need further explanation. Allthough you gotta make sure to always have a Tribute Summoned monster on your field, which shouldn't be too hard.
  • Waterfall of Dragon Souls x2 : A good search card, especially if you abuse its second effect (we'll come to it later). You can add a 3rd copy if you want.
  • Rivalry of Warlords OR Gozen Match x1 : Those cards can be usefull against decks featuring only one Monster Type or Archetype, you can add more of these but I do not think it is worth it as it can brick you if you get them when you do not need it. (I'm currently putting those in the Side Deck)
  • Storming MF x2 : That MF is fire, literally. Yeet all ATK position monsters your opponent controls into his hand (or extra-deck). If you get it off, you will most likely see your opponent instantly surrender (and sometimes call bullshit or flame you).
  • Infinite Impermanence x2 : You know the card, you know why it's good.
  • Escalation of the Monarchs x1 : Because Tribute Summoning during your opponent's Battle Phase is always fun and giggles, you can already summon during his Main Phase with the TD traps.

Playstyle :

True Dracos have held a good spot as an anti-meta deck since their release, being really dominant in 2017 and early 2018 (and still being strong in 2020). Despite numerous limitations and bans, the Archetype is very good and almost always combined with other Archetypes to solidify its or the other Archetype's strengths while covering for weaknesses. This deck is making use of Monarch cards to make it hard for the opponent to Special Summon (as well as locking down the Extra Deck). As I said earlier, I have been using this deck for a long time and I think my win-ratio throughout the years is roughly or above 75%, IRL and Online on YGO.PRO (and now EDO.PRO). However, living in a small town far away from the bigger cities, I have not taken part in any major tournament, which would be this deck's true test. I have a harder time going against other TD or Monarch decks, the end result depending more on the RNG and luck than anything else and against Dark Magicians and Vanilla Blue-Eyes decks (by Vanilla I mean decks that want to summon the regular BE White Dragon without using Chaos Max / Neo Ultimate or any other non-normal monsters) as they are unaffected by some of my lockdown cards. I recently came accross some trouble against some Phantasms decks when having a mediocre starting hand as they are Power Decks that do not rely much on the Extra Deck and you need to make perfect use of your resources to dispatch them. Not gonna lie, I'm expecting you to know how TD work and what their unique gimmick here if you came here and read this far but I'm going to sumarize it incase it is not your case. TD Monsters are to be Tribute Summoned and they can use Continous Spells or Traps to be Summoned. TD Spells have two effects in common : They allow you to Tribute Summon a TD Monster once during your Main Phase (in addition to your Normal Summon) and, if they are sent from your field to the Graveyard (through being use as Tribute or Destroyed / Discarded), they allow you to destroy any Spell or Trap card on the field. TD Traps also have two shared effects : They allow you to Tribute Summon a TD Monster once during your OPPONENT'S Main Phase and, if they are sent from your field to the Graveyard (through being use as Tribute or Destroyed / Discarded), they allow you to destroy any Monster card on the field. That means that you have to be mindfull of your cards and how you manage them. You nevertheless have the ability to cycle a lot through your deck and to draw or search a lot of cards through clever usage of your effects. If you go first, you want to assert dominance over your opponent and to make sure you won't have your field shatered in an instant and to get OTK-ed, which is the point of the current Meta, relying on the "Monarch" aspect of the deck and Dreiath for cover. If you go second, you want to break your opponent's field wide open with your spells and traps and to make sure he does not have any chances of making a come back (with Dragolich to lock him out of special summoning from the GY for example). Do not hesitate to tribute your TD spells or traps if you need to get rid of the opponent's backrow or monsters, even if that means tributing TK Return, the gods will forgive you in that leads you to a victory, especially now that it is not Limited anymore. Also, do not be the noob that activates the Spell and Traps GY effects when your opponent have nothing you can target, you will have to destroy one of your own card and you will look (and feel) dumb. Anyways, this deck has a lot of Combo Potential, here is a few examples to get you started, I'll let you discover the rest by yourself !

Combos and Tricks

10 IQ combos :

  • Card of Demise + TK Return
    • Just send TD monsters to the GY during your endphase, and instantly after doing that, summon one with TK Return.
    • You can also "cheese" the damage immunity this card grants to your opponent if you use it during your Main Phase 2.
  • Dragonic Diagram + Any TD Spell or Trap (+TD Heritage)
    • You not only get to search a card you need, you also yeet a card your opponent controls in the process.
    • After that, you can use TD Heritage to draw a card (or more if you sent more TD cards from the field to your GY this turn)
  • TD Apocalypse (+ Dreiath III) + TK Return
    • When your opponent attacks, use TD Apo to target a monster you control and send it to the GY to halve the opponnent's monsters ATK points, then use TD Return to bring that same monster if Defense position.
    • This combo gains 90 bonus IQ if the monster you sent to the GY is Dreiath as you will be able to use its effect to summon any TD monster and then you can call back one of the highest DEF points TD monster.

100 IQ combos :

  • TD Apocalypse + TD Apocalypse (or TK Return if you can't do otherwise)
    • When your opponent attacks, use TD Apo and target another TD Apo (or Return if you REALLY MUST), not only will your opponent's monsters lose half their ATK points, you will also be able to destroy one.
  • TD Apocalypse + TD Apocalypse
    • Just use TD Apocalypse effects twice, halving even further your opponent's monsters ATK. Be mindfull however, the trick here is that you cannot use that combo in the same Chain, so you will have to find a way to create two different Chain blocks !
  • Waterfall of Dragon Souls (+ Dreiath III) + TK Return (+ TD Heritage) (+TD Disciples)
    • Use WDS second effect to send a monster you control to the GY to draw two cards (or more if you sent more monsters to the GY with that effect)
    • Add 100 IQ if that monster was Dreiath (you know the reason if you read the TD Apo + TD Return Combo)
    • Add 300 additional IQ if you then use TD Heritage to draw even more cards (tho it has to be during your turn)
    • Make it over 9000 IQ if you can then get TD Disciples off and to draw one last card.
  • Metaltron XII + Dreiath III (+TK Return) (+Any TD Spell)
    • Use Dreiath to Tribute summon Metaltron, then use its effect to special summon another Metaltron (if you have multiple copies of it) or any other TD Monster.
    • Add 100 IQ if you then bring it back with TK Return
    • Add Cyber Dragon Nova IQ if you then use a TD Spell to Tribute Summon another Dreiath
    • Add Cyber Dragon Infinity IQ if you once again use a TD Spell to Tribute that other normal summoned Dreiath to Tribute Summon another monster (and Special Summon again with Dreiath)

500 IQ Combo :

  • Escalation of the Monarch + Metaltron XII + Dreiath III (+TK Return) (+Any TD Trap)
    • That is actually the same combo than the one I just mentionned, but you will start it during your opponent's Main Phase or Battle Phase instead of during your turn, causing Chaos within is mind as you play YOUR TURN during theirs.
    • If you do that during the opponent's Battle Phase, you won't be able to use the (+Any TD Trap) part and you will have to wait for your opponent to get to his Main Phase 2, you can circumvent that issue with Escalation of the Monarch.
    • Seriously, it already happened to me several times that confused opponents mistakenly ended their Battle Phase or lost to the Timer because they weren't sure who had to play and what Phase we were in anymore.

Lockdown Combo :

Night Dragolich + Any Tribute Summoned TD Monster (preferably Dreiath or Metaltron or both) + Monarch's Erupt + Domain of the True Monarchs + TD Apo + A card ready to be used for TD Apo + Infinite Impermanence ready. Your opponent can only break it piece by piece, and you should be able to deal with it.  

In conclusion :

I thank you A LOT for checking this deck and reading this far, do not hesitate to try the deck out or to ask me if you have any questions left. If you have constructive feedback to give about anything, do not hesitate either. I will surely keep updating this deck as BanLists come and the Meta evolves, I am often experimenting with new stuff revolving around TD (I'm currently trying an Invoked + True Draco deck, it's good stuff but it is sometimes weird). Once again, thank you for reading and see you in a duel ! Drultime EDIT 1 : March 12th 2021 : Rephrasing Cyber Dragon Infinity IQ combo to remove confusion, Typos cleaned, update recommendations for TK Return following it's Return (pun/20) to 3.

deck_excerpt: May somewhat compete with meta decks. Has countermeasures to most meta decks (comes with video).
deck_description: Video for some of the combos: From what I've experienced, it's impossible to be consistent with Dark Magician Deck regardless of how many draw engines you add to it. The reason for this is because of the number of cards that can be potential bricks if other cards are still inside the deck, not the actual draw power of the deck itself per se. Therefore, I did not add spellbook engine because it requires a normal summon, which conflicts with Rod (and having 3 in your deck), and since you can retrieve rod with Soul Servant, it shouldn't be too difficult with an average hand. Your normal summon is VERY important, using it for draws is the same thing as giving up this turn. You can quickly accumulate draw power using Dark Magician Fusions and Magicians' Souls, with a bit of luck you can EASY pull out 10+ cards from the deck. Draw power is not Dark Magician's real issue, reliance on a good starting hand is. It sounds counter intuitive but it's not as much as you think. Basically, for Dark Magicians, making sure that your starting hand can start in a way by having more card interactions is more important than drawing more cards. For example, using metafoes fusion results a deck shuffle, so you're getting a random deck. But using cchicken race or upstart goblin over metalfoes fusion,you can pair with magic circle or soul servant and choose what card you draw. As long as you can secure getting rod and souls, you can likely get something that matches situation, preferably a way to either get out Magicians' Souls or the Dark Magicians, which allows you to dump more Soul Servant compatible cards to the graveyard. Not having a once per turn restriction also helps tremendously compared to metafoes fusion. Your main goal is to dump Mana/Dark Magician/Dark Magician Girl/Mahad to the graveyard, then gaining draws from it. Rod and Magician's Souls are the main starting point of Dark Magician Deck, therefore it is necessary to max all of them. Dark Magic Circle is one of the most important card in the deck, and since it can potentially draw a card if it is a Dark Magician spellcard(which is guaranteed used with soul servant), it is recommend to put all three. Soul Servant is the main method of search your deck, it can search anything DM related in Deck/GY, its only downside is that it can be a brick starting with it turn one, but you can alleviate this by using in combination with Chicken Race or Magician's Souls. On the other hand, Eternal Soul and Navigation are easily Searchable, so having all 3 is not necessary, especially when they can be bricks when you don't have Dark Magician in GY or in hand. Navigation in particular since you generally only really need to dump 2 monsters at once with Navigation in an entire match for fusion. 1 Mana, you only need one Mana, since you can dump her using magicians' souls (which should be your first priority most of the time when using Magicians' Souls) and you really want her to stay there or on the field, not in your hand or the deck. Mana is very good for deterring your opponent from targeting your monsters, since she is quite pesky in the sense that she can summon Dark Magician Girl from the deck when she is destroyed, in turn giving your +1 draw power from Soul Servant while leaving a monster on field. If Your Magicians' Souls get Effect Veilered, to the very least you can go for Red-Eyes Dragoon using Verte Anaconda using Magicians' Souls and Mana as materials.   1 Mahad can counter many dark monsters, including Dragoon and Chaos Max Dragon. 2 Eternal Soul is nice to have on hand if you have another card that can get Dark Magician to the GY or hand, but having 3 is more than necessary, especially when it is easily searchable and even retrieve from GY with Soul Servant. Retrieving it using Soul Servant+The Dark Magicians also allows to summon Dark Magician on the same turn, which is very useful. 1 Secrets of Dark Magic is very important for summoning Dragon Knight and The Dark Magicians, but one is enough since it's searchable and generally you'll only use it twice at most, and you can use soul servant to retrieve it from GY as well. If you have Dark Magician Girl if your hand, you can also use her instead of Dark Magician for fusion to get her in the GY, which is very important for Soul Servant. 1 Illusion Magic is used for retrieving Dark Magician to your hand for Fusion/Navigation/Eternal Soul, as well as protecting your monsters from other more harmful effects than being sent to GY. 1 Eye of Timaeus, this card is not searchable but at same time can be bricky when running multiple. Since this Deck already uses Secrets of Dark Magic, you don't really need more than 1. One Apprentice Illusion Magician, since there's only one Navigation in the Deck, the need to use her to get Dark Magician in hand doesn't come up that often. She can also be special summoned using Navigation, which can you an opportunity to fusion Dragun of Red-Eyes or Dragon Knight when it's your turn. That sums up the Dark Magician cards. I used Chicken Race over Upstart Goblin and Metafoes Fusion, mainly because: 1. You do not have a once per turn restriction; 2. You can use Chicken Race to draw a card, then use Magician's Souls to get rid of it to draw another, giving you two cards in the process. 1 Terraforming, since you're already running Chicken Race and Secret Village. 1 Super Polymerization, since it's searchable with Verte Anaconda you don't need that many. Moreover, you can also use this to remove most enemies since Verte can make another monster dark as well. 1 Red-Eyes Fusion and 1 Red-Eyes Black Dragon, because Dragun of Red-Eyes is OP. Dark Magician Deck is very weak to enemy hand traps, so at least 2 called by the grave is pretty necessary, I feel. The Card Three Tactical Talents will also help tremendously when you're faced with such a situation. 1 Secret Village of the Spellcasters, though it may be side decked since it's a rather situational and can affect you as well (it will hurt you more than help you against decks like Poltergeist). handtraps are handtraps. You can change with w/e you like, though some Effect Veiler is recommended because it's a magician monster, which allows you to summon Selene which can summon Spellcasters from graveyard, and can link summon into Accesscode Talk for a whooping 5300atk. You can also use it as The Dark Magicians fusion material, or Illusion magic. As for Extras: Dragon Knight: This + Eternal Soul is very powerful against many decks (though it's not infallible such as against Orcust), definitely bring one, though you only need 1 since it counts as Dark Magician and as such can be summoned with Eternal Soul even if it is sent to the GY. Dragun of Red-Eyes and Verte Anaconda: I don't think I need to say anything how powerful this combo is. Even some Orcust run it nowadays. Starving Venom Fusion Dragon: Very easy to summon using super poly, especially with superpoly and vertes (which can turn one of the monsters into dark). At minimum it works on any monster that can be targeted and effected, since you can turn it into dark and use verte for the other material. The Dark magicians: Extremely easy to summon, offers great draw power and can potentially get Dark Magician Girl on field for more Soul Servant draw power. It can also draw a card and set it and use on the same turn, in including Eternal Soul, which goes VERY WELL with cards like soul servant. Use its draw ability wisely every turn, save it until using soul servant and/or dark magic circle Needlefiber/Selene/Accesscode Talker: Use a card+handtrap to summon it lategame, and you can use it to summon Selene, which can summon Dragun from GY if you need it. Alternatively, you can also use her to summon another Spellcaster then use them to link Summon Accesscode Talker (5300atk+destroying multiple cards without triggering them) to finish the opponent. Knightmare Phoenix: Link-2 Summon, if the opponent runs Imperial Order this is your way out. Imduk: Dark Magician can Link summon Imduk, so if you have two Dark Magicians on field or 1 in hand, you can make a Dragon Knight or Dragun. Having two Dark Magician on field is not a difficult task most of the time. Linkuriboh: Since Linkcross is getting banned in July, it's less useful, but you can still convert Magician Souls into this to minimize damage. It's also necessary for easy summoning of Ningirsu: Normal summon a handtrap → Summon Needlefiber → Search Effect Veiler from Deck → Make Veiler into Linkuriboh → Ningirsu Galaxy Tomahawk: This is a a bit long, but basically it's extremely useful for setting up a powerful board with Dark Magician, since it creates tokens to summon link monsters like Ip Astram. I've learned it from a Dark Magician veteran, a powerful combo with only 2 cards: Rod + Magicians' Souls Rod → Soul Servant → Magicians' Souls to summon Dark Magician → Soul Servant to fetch Mahad → XYZ summon Tomahawk → make Verte Anaconda + Union Train + Ip → Red-Eyes Fusion summon Dragun of Red-Eyes → Use Union Train and Equip Dark Magician Girl on Ip.  If you have extra bricks in hand, you can also consider using Verte's first effect then have Dragun deny it to get 1000atk AND remove it to save you from Sky Striker Roze/superpoly. Next turn Make Astram, Dark Magician Girl gets sent to GY, now you have Dragun + Astram, AND 3 Soul Servant related card in GY, meaning you can draw 3 cards with it. As for the side decks, I don't have great ones in mind atm. Phantazmay is not only good synergy with Dark Magician Deck due to it being a dragon, it also pairs with  Nibiru, allowing to get the draws AND clear the board together. With Forbidden Drop I feel like Kaiju monsters aren't as necessary now, and since it can discard cards on field, you can use it to discard Chicken Race with no real cost (and probably benefits you). Consider wiping opponent backrow if they're heavy on spell/traps with Dark Magic Attack. Union Train can be used when making Ip + Verte combo,  since you'd have 6 monsters/tokens on board, leaving two left. You can use this method to bring out Dark Magicians or Palladium oracles then either equip it on the link monsters so when they are sent to graveyard as material, it gets dumped to the graveyard as well. Alternatively, you can also use Magicians' Souls to send it to graveyard while gaining a draw from it. Skill Drain is useful but like Village can also hurt you, especially against Poltergeist. If the opponent is a big fan of disabling magic cards, stuff all Typhoon the from side deck so you can stand a chance by destroying their cards like Secret Village of Spellcasters or Imperial Order.

deck_excerpt: Formud Skipper enables both Mathmech and Sky Striker plays then OTK with Final Sigma or Accesscode+Multiplication. All you need is 1 other Mathmech mo
deck_description: While both Mathmech and Sky Striker excel in going second, each of them has their weakness. Mathmech lacks of removal card and Sky Striker lacks in OTK power, mash them up together and they complete each other. Formud Skipper ties them together making it the best starter for OTK with 1 other Mathmech monster in hand just like regular Mathmech play, but the difference here we can summon Sky Striker with Formud along the way. Not only that, just like Salamangreat, now Sky Striker is able to OTK with Accesscode/Updater Jammer with the same starter above! The combo needs Formud + Mathmech monster, so we play 3 Cynet Mining and One for One. Other way is 3 cards, Parallel Exceed + Mathmech + Sky Striker (Raye/Roze/Hornet). The Formud OTK combo is we use Formud copy Zeke, ss Kaina, use Formud chain Kaina (chainblock Ash, vice versa depends on you), add Parallel Exceed, ss Hayate use Exceed, ss another Exceed from deck, make Primathmech Alembertian add 1 other different Mathmech monster, use Alembertian tribute Hayate ss Mathmech (other than Sigma cus it can ss itself), ss Sigma. From here you can either make Final Sigma or Accesscode route. If youre making Final Sigma, ss it on extra zone, use Multiplication doubles its attack and swing for game. The Accesscode route, you make Splash Mage with Alembertian + non-Multiplication, use Splash Mage ss lv4 Mathmech from GY, make Accesscode with Splash Mage and 2 mats (including Multiplication), use Multiplication and chain Accesscode. Now we have 8.6K Accesscode with bunch of different attribute link monsters in GY (3 at minimum, Kaina, Hayate, and Splash Mage). Mathmech lineup: 3 Sigma, 3 Nabla, 1 Multiplication (searchable by Nabla and Alembertian, not a tuner means ded if we play multiple), 1 Equation (extender). Sky Striker lineup: 2 Raye (2 cus it's not our main normal summon and we dont run Area Zero), 1 Roze (extender), 2 Afterburners, 2 Widow Anchor, 1 Hornet Drones. We dont run Area Zero/Multirole as we only play minimal Sky Striker cards, it means we grind only with Raye, Hayate+Kagari, or Shizuku. The rest of the main deck is just typical go second cards. It's hard on TCG cus no Crossout to prevent Nibiru. Extra deck is self-explanatory. Trisbaena is there cus we can trigger it by using Splash Mage to reborn Formud then Linkuriboh on Trisbaena zone, super useful against Eldlich/Dragma or after we use Red Reboot but cant OTK. Pros: Consistent OTK and we play Sky Striker if we failed to OTK anyway, and lots of staple space. Cons: Going first is bad, we play bootlegged Sky Striker, and going second against meta is really dependent on the staples you draw.

deck_excerpt: Eldlich has room for hand traps. This is good, because I want to eat combo.
deck_description: Latest version. Running the Uka package, because ironically in a Needlefibre world it is simultaneously generic and high impact. This leaves room for 12 total hand traps, and has a lot of bricks. On the other hand, the deck's grind game is pretty good for a synchro variant, it can slow a game right down, and capitalize by winning in an instant.  The extra deck is the Calamities + Pot of Greed combo, or the 2 negate combo as a back-up/follow up.  I like One For One. Very often you see it with Golden Lord (when you do see it) and so long as you have a hand trap its a 7th way into the combo. The deck doesn't really care that it doesn't use the normal summon, but it still seems worth it.  Nibiru is the other high impact hand trap that might still stop a turn, and basically lets me win the game, sometimes. Also, it combines with other hand traps very nicely against Adamancipator. Imperm is obligatory in Eldlich, it's a good generic trap that negates and activates from the hand, I think this deck will always run Imperm first.  I want to be back on 3 of each Golden Land trap. It gives the deck a better grind game, and increases the odds of seeing them just enough.

deck_excerpt: Just an idea I had. As many 1 card starters as possible, with good back-up plans.
deck_description: Hi, welcome to the deck! The main goal is to make True King of All Calamaties off of easy 1 card combos. The rest of the deck are basically bricks that facilitate these combos.  Jet Synchron is full combo, pitching a card. Tuning finds you jet synchron, might mill Token Collector, Citadel, or Jinzo. One For One is the full combo without using your normal summon, allowing you to use any extender to Scrap combo off first, before Auroradon. It can pitch Jinzo, Citadel, or Token Collector for profit. Scrap Recycler are more routes into Needlefibre through Jet, and are also great follow-up plays, for routes to OTK and/or break boards. Its a nonbo with the field spell, since it will miss timing. Deskbot 003 is the best of these starters, since you don't have to pitch a card and can stock the GY up with an extra Jet for later use, such as to pitch a Jinzo you drew late into the turn. Urgent Schedule is a "starter" going second. You can OTK, pop backrow, wipe monsters, and even set up Halqifibrax through this card. Thanks to the field spell you can even use this card going first (though generally you won't be able to link with it afterward). Machina Citadel are to special summon off of Urgent Schedule, and you can loop them by stacking a back-up in your GY. Jinzo is a one of - it has 2400 ATK points, so it's easy to res with the field spell, and shuts down Imperm and Evenly. That's it. Foolish Burial is an extra copy that works as an extender in bad hands. Black Garden is nuts in this deck, being able to turn on Urgent Schedule for free turn 1 enables truly broken stuff, if we so choose we can clog up people's zones and slow the game down, so it's nice on its own with some of our solid hand traps. 2 each of 001, O-Lion, and Scrap Golem makes sense to me - you could cut down to 1 Golem and be happy, but it's nice to know your combo will work even if you see 1 brick, and there are unusual circumstances where using one of these as a normal summon still combos off. Pot of Avarice is a spot of card advantage, coupled with the ability to recycle combo pieces. It's really that simple, if the deck gets interrupted I want to have a second chance with the game. Gizmek Uka makes a lot of sense in the deck. It's a free special summon that locks people out of their extra deck for playing Needlefibre in a meta where every deck is Needlefibre. Eria the Water Charmer Gentle makes this a very high impact hand trap. All of our hand traps help make our board, while being as impactful against the current meta as possible and playing through Called.  Gizmek Orochi is back. This lets you make Apollousa with 4 negates without using up your synchro cards, for those games where you get Black Garden + Urgent Schedule or One for One + Scrap Recycler. It is also a free(ish) extender and a Gizmek Uka target that you can use to make Uka into an insane extender once you get your Black Garden.  Herald and Borreload Savage are things you can make with Gizmek Uka and Scrap Recycler or 003. This also gives you an alternative line of play with Urgent Schedule going first, and gives us a second combo after the first for 3 read em 3 lines of play. (4 if you count Eria). This means only running Accesscode for our Scrap Wyvern, but honestly, this is fine. I'll miss Borrelsword, but Accesscode does a good impression and also plays out of the Eria line.  I hate going down Auroradon, but I can recycle one copy with Avarice, and I can make Herald in other ways, so I'm running Herald as well.  I cut the copies of tuning in order to run Phantazmay. This increases our chances of seeing high impact spell cards, and doubles as a target to special summon with Black Garden.

But anyways, to start things back off I want to introduce you guys to my newest Altergetist build with Altergeist Multifaker at 3. The deck is back at full power and I think its insane especially with Meluseek being a water attribute because you can use him and another other monster to make Eria, The Water Charmer and using her effect to steal your opponent's Crystron Halqifibrax which can lead to other combos like Ningrisu or Accesscode Talker. Going second it allows you to break your opponent's board and then setup yours so that they surrender during the following turn since they won't have anymore resources.
