deck_name: Revival of the Nekroz – A Beginner’s Guide
deck_excerpt: Dear fellow duelists, please feel free to delve into the mysteries of the Nekroz through this comprehensive guide...
deck_description:
Revival of the Nekroz – A Beginner’s Guide Remember when Nekroz of Brionac price tag was spiking at circa $150-$200 back in 2015? At that time, advanced format was dominated by the Nekroz Archetype, before Konami decided to enter the stage with a flood of bans, in a successful attempt to rebalance the metagame. As time went by and game evolved, new sets were released with ever greater cards each time, ultimately leading Konami to reconsider its banlist, and set free the Nekroz top cards one after the other: Shurit … Brionac … until very recently, when Nekroz of Unicore finally got back to three! Now that the deck can (almost) be played at full power, I thought it would be interesting to share some knowledge on the Nekroz mechanics & strategies, that may seem a bit obscure at first glance. Hence this extensive guide covering various aspects of the deck, as well as some insight on my personal build. Hope you like it. Foreword: Nowadays, there is a widespread decklist of the Nekroz that is often featured on Youtube. I invite you to check the following link first, in order to see by yourself: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u-tBsd1JpOg. Admittedly, this variant is much more explosive thanks to its insane 1-card combo generating an impressive card advantage. However, despite the “hype”, and after having extensively tested both versions, I still think the Impcantation build is better. Let me briefly outline the main reasons behind this statement:
  • Deskbot 003, the combo starter, is not searchable: if you do not draw it, you drastically decrease your chances of winning the duel because your entire build is oriented (artificially skewed) towards this particular combo, and therefore less efficient in every other scenario.
  • Tons of hard bricks: two Deskbot 001, one Mecha Phantom Beast Coltwing, and one Archlord Kristya (to a lesser extent), and you still need to play with a 40-card deck if you want to open Deskbot 003 more often. There is a 42.71% probability to open at least one brick in your starting hand (4 bricks / proba going first / 5 cards in hand), and still a 33.76% proba if you do not count Kristya. That means at least one out of 3 starting hands, which is not negligible.
  • Destroyed by hand trap: if the combo is shut down only once, it is “end of turn”. Deskbot 003 into Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring = “GG” and I am not being sarcastic. Some will say: “yes but it is the same for any combo if stopped properly, right?”. Not quite actually, many combos rely on various extenders and can still survive a hand trap, while other can at least adapt themselves and achieve decent end boards while being disrupted. There is no such possibility in this case.
  • Nibiru incoming: Even though the combo includes a Herald of the Arc Light early on (negate ability), it is still too late to avoid Nibiru, the Primal Being, which will not hesitate to crush your board whenever it can.
  • The deck needs to run 3x Called by the Grave to protect against Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. Should you want to have a “high” chance to go through your entire combo, you would need Deskbot 003 + CBG in hand (both not searchable). This leads to a probability of only 23.72% of drawing them (going first / 5 cards in hand), meaning 1 chance out of 4. Adding the proba of being Nibiru’ed, it does not fly… And you also have to take into account this combo can almost only be performed going first (would be countered otherwise) which once again reduces your chances of achieving it.
  • Conclusion: this really is a trade-off scenario: are you willing to sacrifice stability for a powerful combo which will most likely win you the game if properly conducted? I would say this is a high risk/high reward dilemma, but I myself would rather bet on consistency on the long run. Overall, too many flaws in my opinion that drastically decrease the real chances of going through your combo.
If you disagree, I would very much like to hear your thoughts in the comments section below! That being said, let me guide you through the mysteries of the Nekroz…   Strengths: Unmatchable Search Engine: It is so powerful… it might even destabilize beginners who won’t know where to start! Nekroz of Brionac, on its own, enables you to access ANY Nekroz card, either directly, or through another layer of search thanks to Nekroz of Clausolas. Let’s not forget Nekroz of Unicore’s second ability, which can also retrieve from grave by discarding itself. Consistent as Hell: Add the “Impcantation” package and ridiculous spells such as Preparation of Rites to the Nekroz core engine, and you get a deck thanks to which pretty much any hand can get you what you want. I really mean it, the deck is so stable (no bricks at all), you will often feel overwhelmed by the plethora of options available to you. Absolute Power Plays: Nekroz of Unicore & Nekroz of Trishula effects are game changers: Trishula will grant you a huge card advantage while Unicore’s Extra-Deck Lock will shut down most of the strategies of your opponent if not dealt with. Highly Versatile: You can choose whether you prefer to go 1st or 2nd… and that is pure luxury! I certainly built this deck with a “going 2nd” approach in mind (even though Vanity's Ruler is a turn 1 option), but you can aslo decide to start the duel if you feel the need to, depending on the deck you are facing. This build can clearly adapt and compete in both scenarios. Very Resilient: So many searchers in the deck = not too difficult to sail through a sea of negates & interruptions while developing your strategy “seamlessly”. Many ways to bait your opponent & resolve crucial cards. Double Trouble! Nekroz have a huge impact on board, that’s for sure. What if I told you they can be even better when kept in hand? All Nekroz come up with two effects: one that activates on the field, and the second one from hand. Nekroz of Trishula negates effects that target your other Nekroz monsters, while Nekroz of Valkyrus acts like a Battle Fader, ending the battle phase right after being discarded, an ability that will help you a lot to stall the game and buy some time. Weaknesses: Ritual Summoning Condition: Obviously, Ritual Summon is not the easiest way to summon a monster in Yu-Gi-Oh. And the restrictive conditions regarding the level of the tributes will force you to think twice before making a move. Fortunately, Impcantations are a blessing for this deck (and any other ritual-based deck) and make it much easier to summon your favorites creatures! Search-Lock Effects: I said in the previous section that this deck worked a bit like an open bar, where you can pick any card you want with ease. However, every Nekroz player loathes cards that prevent you from searching directly from deck. Droll & Lock Bird or Mistake, to name a few, will haunt your worst nightmares…! In the current metagame (July 2020 – MR5) dominated by Adamancipator and Eldlich, these cards are not prevalent (even in sides), so don’t worry too much. Over-Passivity: On your opponent’s turn, you can defend yourself, but you cannot actively interrupt his/her plays with the Nekroz engine at all. You will rely on your “going 2nd” cards and hand traps to do so. You have no negates available, no removal that can be activated during his/her turn. No Signature Trap? If you read Nekroz cards carefully, you probably noticed some of them mentioned traps in their description (such as Clausolas), but no Nekroz trap has ever been released so far. Maybe Konami thought it was not necessary considering the huge impact of the archetype on the game when it first came out. Nowadays though, almost every archetype as its negating trap, and I would be glad if Nekroz had one. Famous examples are: Toon Terror, Salamangreat Roar, Orcust Crescendo etc…   Strategy: Main Objective: Nekroz of Unicore + Vanity’s Ruler on board --> Prevent your opponent from special summoning + Negate all effects of monsters summoned from the Extra Deck // Trishula + Valkyrus in hand --> Protection from targeting effects (Trishula Negate ability) & Protection from battle (Valkyrus ends battle phase). Most often, you will want to ritual summon Nekroz of Unicore with Nekroz Kaleidoscope, sending a Herald of the Arc Light to the grave in order to add any ritual card directly from your deck to your hand. I would consider this play as the main generic move you will surely repeat over and over, against a great variety of deck, when playing Nekroz. If your opponent does not use the Extra Deck (Monarch Archetype for instance), change of plan: obviously, you should go 2nd against such decks, BUT, if your opponent lets you start, THEN: try to XYZ Nekroz of Unicore + Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands for a rank 4 play --> I suggest Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir. And make sure you end the turn with Valk in hand. Bagooska will prevent any monster effect from activating on the field, and Valk will keep your health points safe. Do not try to build any sort of “Nekroz-related” board (Brionac or Clausolas or Valkyrus or anything else on turn one), it is useless. Your powerful Nekroz are meant to be unleashed on turn 2. Protect yourself, try to stay alive one more turn, and only start building up your offensive the turn after. Main Combo when Going 1st: You can achieve same end board with multiple combinations. The sequencing is primordial. Nekroz of Unicore + Impcantation Chalislime + Nekroz of Brionac in hand
  • Reveal Unicore, use Chalislime effect into Talismandra effect into Cyber Angel Benten in hand
  • Brionac discard into Clausolas discard into Kaleidoscope in hand
  • Ritual Summon Unicore with Kaleidoscope dumping Herald to Grave
  • Add Cycle from deck with Herald’s effect
  • Use Cycle to revive Brionac from grave dumping Benten to grave
  • Use Benten effect to add Vanity’s Ruler from deck to hand
  • Normal Summon Vanity by tributing Talismandra and Brionac
--> Preparation of Rites OR any impcantation can also provide you with a piece of the combo. Pretty much all your cards are combo pieces at this point 😉 When Going 2nd: Take down your opponent defenses one by one and build up your own board:
  • Evenly Matched & Super Poly to wipe their board
  • Summon your Boss Monster Trishula to banish exactly 3 key cards from hand, field and grave
  • Summon Valkyrus to draw by tributing your impcantations, and refill your hand
  • Summon Unicore to negate effects from annoying monsters
  • Summon Brionac to shuffle back up to two monsters summoned from the Extra Deck
  • Swing for game, you can even super poly your own Nekroz during battle phase for extra damage --> Example: Super Poly Brionac & Unicore for Mudragon = +1900 ATK for lethal!
  Rationale Behind Ratios: Nekroz Core Engine: 3x Nekroz of Brionac: Nothing to discuss here, 3 is mandatory. 3x Nekroz of Unicore: Idem, at 3 since the last banlist, adding a lot consistency to your opening hands. 2x Nekroz of Clausolas: Can be searched via Brionac, no need to play at 3. You can even consider playing only 1. 2x Nekroz of Valkyrus: 3x would be a little too much (arguable), you do not want to open it, but you definitely want to end your turn with it. 1x is not enough. You need at least one to end the battle phase, and another one to recycle your dead draws & Impcantations on board. It is also a strong body. 1x Nekroz of Trishula: I main only one, but I also have another copy on my side deck. Usually, you first summon it through Mirror, and then with Cycle (from grave). However, I sometimes need two in order to deal with huge threats or powerful continuous spell/traps. 1x Nekroz of Decisive Armor: Personal tech choice (most of the time swapped in game 2 for Trish if not needed). Can be very helpful to break the 3000th ATK wall. None of your Nekroz can beat a Blue-eyes White Dragon which is annoying. And I guarantee you, you should not neglect that. You will sooner or later find yourself in a spot where you would just need a slightly higher ATK monster to make the difference and win the duel. Furthermore, its ability to destroy AND banish any set card, as well as its Honest-like ability in hand make this card a very versatile option to consider. This card is usually underrated in my view. 1x Shurit, Strategist of the Nekroz: I tried him at x3, it was too bricky. I tried him at 2x, could came in handy, but most of the time, I felt like the second copy was too much. 1x is fine according to me: Shurit can be searched with Brionac (so technically, you have 4x). You want to use it once from hand, and you can even use it twice thanks to Mirror, so it seems enough. 2x Nekroz Kaleidoscope: When Unicore was limited, I would only play one. Now that it is at 3x, 2x Kaleidoscope feels right as it is the principal option you will use to summon Unicore. 2x Nekroz Cycle: Best Nekroz ritual spell, helps you a lot in late game. 1x Nekroz Mirror: The most situational ritual spell, you will almost every time use it to summon Trishula by banishing Brionac and Clausolas OR Shurit from grave. Remark: All these ritual spells are searchable via Clausolas, so you do not need a playset. It would be way too much. Impcantation Package: 2x Impcantation Chalislime: Best Impcantation, you want to open it, but you do not play enough other Impcantations to run 3x copies. 2x is enough. The third one would most likely end up dead in hand. 2x Impcantation Talismandra: Talismandra into search for Brionac or Unicore is the most common play. You never want to open this card so 3x is too much. It needs to be special summoned with one of  its mates. 1x Impcantation Candoll/ 1x Impcantation Penciplume / 1x Impcantation Bookstone: Best scenario is to open one of them and special summon Talismandra. You could replace one Bookstone (the less useful) for one other Pencilplume, to improve your late game. I prefer to run one of each in order to diversify my draws and options. 1x Impcantation Inception: I see too many people running more than 1. This is wrong. This card is searchable and can even be easily retrieved from grave. What’s more, there is already 5 other ritual spells in the deck which is almost too much. With 6 ritual spells, you have a 57.71% chance to open at least one (going first / 5 cards in hand). Let’s say you want to add 2 more, proba would therefore rise to 69.40%, more than 2/3, whereas you do not want to see them in your hand!! 6 ritual cards already account for 15% of your deck, this is huge!! Be very careful about bad ratios, they can totally ruin your chances of winning. Rest of the deck: 3x Preparation of Rites: Best spell in the deck, 3x is mandatory. How come this card is still at 3x? Thanks Konami! 3x Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands: grants you one ritual search, enables XYZ rank 4 plays with Unicore, is your only normal summon except from Vanity’s ruler. 3x is a must. 3x Evenly Matched: particularly effective in Nekroz since you never have to set any trap. 3x Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring: generic hand trap. Replace it depending on the state of the meta. 1x Cyber Angel Benten / 1x Vanity’s Ruler: for the combo play. No need for more copies, both are searchable. Why Ruler instead of Kristya? Kristya's special summoning condition is too hard to meet, you will never use it... and downside is it also prevent YOU from special summoning. Impcantations make it so easy to normal summon Ruler that I do not see any reason not to play it.   Useful Tips:
  • Nekroz of Trishula’s effect states “banish EXACTLY 3 cards”, there is a restriction that Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier does not have. Keep in mind if your opponent has no card in hand, the effect won’t activate at all!
  • When sequencing your plays, do not forget (if possible) to play Preparation of Rites after having already summoned a Nekroz, in order to retrieve the ritual spell used from grave.
  • Nekroz of Brionac can bounce back monsters that were special summoned from THE EXTRA DECK. Do not extrapolate this statement. If an XYZ, Synchro, Fusion etc… monster has been summoned via Monster Reborn for instance, Brionac’s ability won’t trigger.
  • Nekroz of Valkyrus’s recycling ability can be used by tributing monsters from your HAND, not only your FIELD.
  • Do not forget, you are locked into summoning from the Extra Deck if you have an impcantation on board.
  • Remember you need to reveal a specific card from your hand before playing any Impcantation. Always think about it before making any other play and realizing right after you cannot fulfill the requirement anymore!
  • Brionac into Clausolas into Nekroz Mirror = you can invoke Trishula by banishing from grave the two above-mentioned creatures.
  • Bear in mind your ritual spells have effects in grave that require you NOT HAVING any monster on the field to trigger.
  • If you opt for the Manju play, you will not be able to summon Vanity. Be warned!
  • If you do not ritual summon after using Chalislime's effect, you will lose 2000 HP, ouch!!
  • Nekroz of Valkyrus can only be discarded by banishing a Nekorz card from grave!
  Extra Deck: 3x Herald of the Arc Light: to get a free ritual card out of Kaleido/Unicore. 2x Elder Entity N’tss: to destroy a card out of Kaleido/Unicore. Super Poly Targets: Classics include Starving Venom Fusion Dragon, Predaplant Dragostapelia and Mudragon of the Swamp. The latest can also be used on your own monsters, as I explained previously. 1x Number 41 Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir: to slow down your opponent, survive until turn 2. 1x Evilswarm Exciton Knight: emergency option ... to nuke the board! 1x Daigusto Emeral: for the very late game, to reload your deck (very rarely used). 1x Abyss Dweller: if you face a deck abusing effects from grave. 1x Shooting Quasar Dragon: any level 12 will do fine (Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon, yes, you can finally use this ultimate beast!): level 12 = 2x Brionac OR Valk + Unicore OR Trish + Clausolas with Kaleidoscope. 1x Star Eater: any level 11 will do fine: level 11 = Valk + Clausolas with Kaleidoscope. 1x Shooting Star Dragon: any level 10 will do fine: level 10 = Unicore + Brionac with Kaleidoscope. Side Deck: 3x Super Polymerization: you have some free space in your Extra Deck, so why not using it? Another strong way to avoid negates and get rid of your opponent’s monsters. 3x Lightning Storm: very helpful against backrows, as the Nekroz engine does not contain that many removals. And very op, come on! 3x Dark Ruler No More: break monster-based lockdowns, avoid negation. Useful against combo decks abusing Halqifibrax and building powerful end boards. 3x Nibiru, the Primal Being: tons of combo decks out there that cannot play against Nibiru. Best way to wreck their board. 1x Nekroz of Trishula: whenever you think one is not enough. For late game, against control decks. --> The rest is up to you, depends on the meta as usual. 2x Twin Twisters, 2x Cosmic Cyclone, 2x D.D. Crow etc…   Other options to consider: Deskbot 003: already mentioned in the foreword section of this guide. I am not a fan, but very explosive & impressive combo involving Crystron Halqifibrax and Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon (no joke!?). If you feel luck is on your side, go for it! The Zaborg Dilemma: I tested a lot Zaborg The Mega Monarch, and I must say I have mixed feelings regarding its viability for (semi-)competitive play. Its effect is very strong, no doubt, but the conditions required to benefit from it seem quite huge to me. It also comes with its share of drawbacks: It is not searchable, it uses your normal summon, and therefore collides with Manju and Vanity. It helps deplete your opponent’s extra deck, but you can already rely on Unicore to do the job (a bit redundant). You need to tribute a LIGHT monster in order to choose which cards you send to GY from the opponent’s Extra Deck --> it means you would have to reconsider and adjust your impcantation ratios in a way that would not be optimal otherwise. Can sometimes end up dead in hand, especially if you draw it after turn 1. For fun/casual play however, I would highly recommend giving it a try, as you can potentially have access to some sick combos if you combine Zaborg with Miracle Synchro Fusion and specific Extra Deck monsters. Let me know in the comments if you would like more information. Splashing Dragma: the new Dragma Archetype which will make its debut in the “Rise of the Duellist” set (only available in OCG at the moment), will most likely redefine the way we play Nekroz. I do not want to elaborate on this topic. One thing at a time, mastering the actual version of the deck is already quite complicated. Nekroz of Gungnir: I first included it in my side deck but decided to replace it with Nekroz of Decisive Armor which comes up more often. Good removal overall that can find its place in the side deck. Celestial Observatory: very good in this build, enables to replenish your Impcantation engine by shuffling back Talismandra in your deck. Benten and Brionac are also great targets. Reinforcement of the Army: can search for Unicore and Shurit, but there’s so many searchers already, do you really need one more? Maybe... Any other suggestions let me know! If you are one of those who’ve read this far… well, thank you! I hope this guide has facilitated understanding of many key aspects of the Nekroz, and clarified most of the dark spots surrounding these mysterious knights possessed by the spirit of the dragon! Here are some other deck profiles you might like: Phantasms’ Awakening – How to tame the Sacred Beasts! https://ygoprodeck.com/phantasms-awakening-how-to-tame-the-sacred-beasts/ Nostalgy Time – An Extensive Guide on How to Play Toons https://ygoprodeck.com/nostalgy-time-an-extensive-guide-on-how-to-play-toons/ Lightning

deck_excerpt: Lyrilusc abusing Union Carrier to make OTKs more consistent.
deck_description: (Disclaimer: TCG legal with "Battles of Legend: Armageddon" on July 24) Concept In the past, Lyrilusc decks have been forced to run bricky, unsearchable equip spells, to raise Assembled Nightingales OTK capabilities. These struggles lie in the past though, as the generic Union Carrier is able to provide an easy 1000 ATK boost. That is not all however, as the only non-Level 1 monster in the deck, Valkyrie Chariot is conveniently a Wind monster and raises the ATK of an equipped monster further by 500 per attack. This means, that 6 materials on field are an OTK. Components Lyrilusc Core: Standard 3 of each, since they are still the best LV1 engine and provide beneficial effects as Xyz Materials. Appliancer Engine: 3 Socketroll, Copybukkle and World and 1 Kappa in ED. The one Kappa enables you use Worlds recovery to get back a Socketroll, so World plus any of the other two equals 4 usable materials. Normal Summons: 2 Kepler into Gate into Lamia, who can also be used from Grave and send from hand, so it's not too bricky. Only 2 Kinka-Byo because it need setup and Normal Summoning Socketroll nets more pluses. Generic LV1 Extenders: 3 Booster and Jester. Other Spells: One for One and Where Arf Thou? (obviously), Instant Fusion 'cause Millennium-Eyes stops Ash and it can summon Independent, Foolish for Warbler, Kinka-Byo and Lamia, and Lightning Storm because going second. Extra: Worth mentioning are 2 Independent Nightingale because of Instant Fusion, Proxy to access it MP2, and Gravity Controller to turn Recital Starling into Carrier material. Also 1 arrogant Bird, buys you a turn if needed. Side Deck: DS to raise your ceiling when forced to go first and Harpie's Feather Storm for the same occasion.

deck_description: Oviraptor + Misc Step 1: Activate Misc’s effect in hand, sending it to the Graveyard. Step 2: Normal summon Oviraptor and activate its effect adding Babycerasaurus. Step 3: Activate the effect of Misc in the Graveyard to summon Archosaur from deck. Step 4: Activate the effect of Archosaur, destroying Babycera and adding Double Evolution Pill. Step 5: Activate the effect of the Babycera to summon another Babycera from deck. Step 6: Activate the second effect of Oviraptor, destroying the Babycera to bring the first Babycera back from the Graveyard, placing it underneath a Extra Monster Zone. This is the only zoning that matters, and it only matters in Barrier Statue combos. Step 7: Activate the effect of the Babycera you just destroyed to summon Giant Rex from your deck. Your field is now: Oviraptor, Giant Rex, Babycerasaurus, and Archosaur. Step 8: Perform the Starting Combo. Step 9: Link Archo into Linkuriboh. Link Linkuriboh and Giant Rex into Reprodocus, placing it above Babycerasaurus. Step 10: Activate Double Evolution Pill, Banishing Giant Rex and Linkuriboh to summon UCT. Summon the banished Giant Rex by its own effect. Step 12: Xyz Summon Evolzar Dolkka using Oviraptor and Rex. From here, this lets you protect your non-Dinosaur monsters from Nibiru. Step 13: Activate Reprodocus’ effect, declaring Winged-Beast. Link Reprodocus and Babycera into Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty. Step 14: Proceed to the End Phase, and activate Simorgh’s effect, summoning Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds from your hand or Deck.

deck_excerpt: A Combo Control deck that abuses Denglong to generate card advantage.
deck_description: That's right I'm back at it again with TYZ. It's been a while with a bunch of Banlist changes that greatly affected the deck for the better. Tenyi Yang Zing (TYZ) is a deck that's main focus is on card advantage. Card advantage is how TYZ is able to get a leg up on other decks and overwhelm them Non-effect monsters and synchros. The main play of the deck is to use one of the 3 one card starters (Souleating Oviraptor, Draconnet, Mathematican) to synchro summon Denglong and search Nine Pillars (Pro tip don't set backrow until you search Nine Pillars to ensure your opponent doesn't know where you set it). Then afterwords, use Denglong's effect to send a Tenyi from deck to GY (the best one to send, most of the time, is Ashuna) (BTW the level change isn't that important). Then on the opponent's turn negate something with Pillars and off of denlong being sent to GY summon Bi'an, then you revive Denlong with either Buddy Force or Back to the Front, use denlong to search Yang Zing Path (for card advantage), and when you see an opportunity use Bi'an to synchro with Denlong into Baxia and shuffle 2 cards on the opponent's field (Pro tip don't chain Bi'an to a card effect because if you do Baxia will miss timing, also Bi'an gives Baxia battle protection). That's the main bread and butter combo of the Deck that's a +2 in card advantage and gives you a way to recycle the Yang Zings (and draw 2) and puts a Tenyi in the GY. The new stuff include an unlimited copy of Vessel for the Dragon Cycle without having to add 5 extra cards to my deck to meet the trinity requirement. And because of that I cut the World Legacy package since Baxia is good enough removal and I needed space for Crystron Halqifibrax (which helps get denglong on the board even with super bricky hands). And Miscellaneousaurus is another target to send for soul just in case you already burned Carboneddon or hard drew it.
Zane Trusedale
A casual Crystal Beasts deck post Legendary Duelists

deck_excerpt: Dark Magicians? Banishing? Resurrection? Locking down the board? The DM deck you never knew you needed is HERE!
deck_description: This deck centers around using Dark Magician, Eternal Soul, and Dark Magic Circle, with the purpose of banishing your opponents cards as well as other independent supplements meant to make dueling you a living hell. It dominates in casual play and, with a couple card change-ups, is also very competitive in tournament play. Basic strategy: Eternal Soul and Dark Magical Circle are continuous traps and spells respectively. DMC allows you to look at the top 3 cards in your deck and select 1 that is Dark Magician related and add it to your hand immediately. Then you can choose the order of the other 2 cards. 2nd effect: When Dark Magician is summoned to the field, banish an opponent's card. This effect can be done multiple times per turn. Eternal Soul is your DM summoning engine. Once during either turn, you can Special Summon a DM from your hand or deck, thus activating DMC's effect. It doesn't matter if DM is destroyed, cause he'll just come back to banish. Plus ES guards your DM from any card effects. Banishment engine support Cards: Soul Servant, Metalfoes Fusion, Magician's Rod, Foolish Burial Goods, Dark Illusion, and Card Destruction. These are all meant to either help you draw those top 3 cards, or search them directly from your deck. More details below. Search engine: Use these cards to specifically search out DMC, ES, and/or DM directly from your deck. Magician's Rod allows you to add any spell or trap to your hand upon Normal Summon (use to search for DMC or ES). If in the graveyard, you can tribute your Dark Magician to the graveyard to place Rod back in your hand, setting you up for another spell/trap search and DM special summon/banish combo next turn. Soul Servant: Allows you to place any DM-related card at the top of your deck, ready for your next draw. Then, you can banish this to the GY and if you have DM on field or graveyard, draw that card. If you have both DM and DM Girl in field or graveyard, you can draw twice! Because it's a quick-play, you can basically activate this whenever you want. Use with DMC to guarantee a card you want (like ES!) Foolish Burial Goods: Sets you up for your draw engine by sending Soul Servant, Magician Navigation, or Metalfoes Fusion from your deck to the graveyard. See draw engine section below. Magician's Souls: Discard this from your hand to send DM directly from the deck to the GY, then special summon a DM to the field (why wait for that pesky draw?). Also use it to dump DM Girl to draw 2 cards after banishing Soul Servant. Illusion Magic: Tribute any spellcaster from your field to search 2 DMs and add them to your hand (combo by tributing DM to bring him back for a banish later or tribute Rod so that Rod can come back to your hand for another Summon/search combo on your next turn). Draw Engine: Another way to get your DMC, ES, and DM combo into your hand as fast as possible, if you don't have any search cards. Soul Servant: See above. Dump DM Girl and DM into the GY, before using this, to draw 2 cards (this is literally the only reason DM Girl is in your deck). Metalfoes: We don't care about Metalfoes fusion summoning, only its draw effect. Use Foolish Burial Goods to dump this into your GY, then you can shuffle it back into your deck and draw a card. Card Destruction: Currently limited to 1 in official gameplay rules, but if you're playing for fun, run 3. You know the feeling of drawing a crappy hand? Any deck suffers from this from time to time. Use Card Destruction to dump it and draw a new hand (with the added bonus of putting cards like DM, DM Girl, Soul Servant, and Metalfoes into the GY). If you're an official player, run 2 Spellbook of Secrets to search Spellbook of Knowledge to draw 2 cards. Magician's Souls: When this card is on your field, you can ditch 1 or 2 spell/trap cards from your hand or field to the GY and then draw that many cards. I don't use this affect that much, but it's there if you need it. Additional DM support: Other cards not focused on your revival/banishment engine, but their tricks add another layer of offensive and defensive flexibility. Includes Secret Village of Spellcasters, Magician of Dark Illusions, Apprentice Illusion Magician, Palladium Oracle Mahad, Eye of Timaeus, Secrets of Dark Magic, and Magician Navigation Secret of  Spellcasters: Lock down your opponent's board. As long as you have a spellcaster on the field, they can't use their spells. Magician of Dark Illusions: A supplement to your standard DM. This card is great because it's name becomes DM while on the field, allowing you more DMs to use with DMC. While you can't revive it with ES, it's great for summoning directly from your hand if you activate a spell/trap on your opponents turn. Say you have DMC on the field, but no ES yet. Just activate another spell/trap during your opponents turn to bring this out from your hand and get a quick banish on them, disrupting their strategy. I can't tell you how much more flexibility this card offers you. It's even a lvl 7, which will be important later on. Apprentice Illusion Magician and Palladium Oracle Mahad: These are the jacks of all trades! They're powerful beatsticks that are ridiculously easy to special summon from your hand and have killer effects. AIM pulls DM from deck to your hand when you summon her, and you can tribute her to give another magician an extra 2000 Atk/Def! Mahad can double his Atk points when fighting a Dark monster, and if he's destroyed, you can special summon DM from hand, deck, or grave. Eye of Timaeus and Secrets of Dark Magic: Activate these to bring out your Fusion monsters. Easily searchable with Soul Servant or Magician's Rod. Timaeus requires you to only have 1 DM on the field (easy!) and Secrets needs you to have both Fusion materials, but they can stay in your hand instead of exposed on the field. Magician Navigation: Great for summoning a DM straight from your hand and another from your deck (setting you up for multiple banishments or an XYZ or Fusion Summon). It's 2nd effect is arguably more useful though, allowing you to negate an opponent's spell/trap card's effect for that turn. Additional support: Same purpose as your DM support: lockdown your opponent from countering or effectively implementing their own strategies. These allow you to be more proactive in your offense and defense: Ash Blossom, Infinite Impermanence, Solemn Judgment, and Gozen Match. Alternatives include Skill Drain, Twin Twisters, or Solemn Strike/Solemn Warning Ash Blossom: Discard to negate a summon or search effect. Sometimes your opponent needs that one card to get their strategy going. Deny them that with this card Infinite Imperm: Your opponent's monster effect making things hard for you? Use this to negate that effect for a turn, as well as a spell/trap effect. Solemn Judgment: Sacrifice half your life points to activate this?!?! What?! Trust me, you'll need this. It's a counter trap, so only counter traps can counter it, so you're basically guaranteed to cancel out whatever it is your opponent is planning and destroy it. Disrupting them from summoning their trump monster or ace spell/trap is worth half your LP, cause if you don't, you'll lose a lot more than that. Gozen Match: My personal favorite. Each player can only control 1 attribute of monsters while this card is in play. This is perfect for you because most of your monsters are Dark anyways. And against decks where multiple attributes are used, it's a nightmare. *Note: You won't be able to use certain Extra Deck monsters and Mahad if this is active on your field. Fusion Monsters: DM the Dragon Knight: Your biggest challenge is going to be protecting DMC and ES while they're active, because your opponent will definitely target them. This giant beatstick boasts 3000 Atk AND protects your spells and traps from any card effects. Also, it's name becomes DM on the field or GY, so it benefits from your DMC and ES combo as well!!! Summon this, and ES protects it from any card effects and it protects all your spells/traps from effects as well. The only way for your opponent to attack your field is with a monster with +3000 Atk, and even then, you can always just bring it back with ES. Broken. The Dark Magicians: Also very useful effect, allowing you to draw 1 card for every effect activated. If it's a spell/trap, you can set it and/or activate it right then and there, depending on the type of spell or trap. And if it's destroyed, special summon DM and DM Girl from hand deck or graveyard to set off DMC's effect as revenge. When Dragun of Red-Eyes comes out, you will also want that in your Extra Deck for sure! If you need Fusions with just raw attack power, consider Amulet Dragon, Dark Paladin, and Dark Cavalry. Their effects are more limited, but they can shine in terms of brute strength. Xyz: Red Eyes Flare Metal Dragon, Number 11: Big Eye, and Ebon Illusion Magician. All of these are lvl 7 Xyz (and you conveniently have 6 lvl 7 monsters that can be easily put on the field at the same time. Ebon Illusion Magician is especially useful for this deck, allowing you to special summon spellcasters and have a banishing effect of its own! Your next most useful Xyz is Red-Eyes, oddly enough. It'll further lock down your opponent by inflicting 500 LP damage every time they activate a card or effect. Your opponent must choose: carry out their strategy at the expense of their LP, or save their LP at the expense of taking any action against you. Big Eye simply lets you take control of an opponents monster permanently. Ebon High Magician is also an option if you want, as well as Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack for link summoning (though this is a Wind-type) Links: I don't really know how to use Links that much, but you can definitely include some. I'd keep DM the Dragon Knight, The DMs, Dragun of Red Eyes (when it comes out), Ebon Illusion, Red Eyes, and Big Eye as essentials. They others can be switched out for Link monsters if you want.

deck_excerpt: An infinite negate combo from a single Crystron Halqifibrax.
deck_description: This deck uses a single card (anything that can summon Crystron Halqifibrax, except Jet Synchron) and a card to discard to set up the Mist Valley infinite negate (Apex Avian + Thunderbird) on the first turn. The combo: -Special Summon Crystron Halqifibrax (There are many ways to do this). Use its effect to Summon Mecha Phantom Beast O-Lion. -Summon Linkross with Halqifibrax, summoning 2 Link Tokens -Use O-Lion and 1 of the Tokens to Summon Martial Metal Marcher. Use O-Lion's effect to Summon a Mecha Phantom Beast Token, and use Marcher's effect to revive O-Lion. -Use O-Lion and the Mecha Phantom Beast Token to summon Accel Synchron. Use Accel Synchron's effect to send Jet Synchron to the GY and increase or decrease its level by 1. -Discard 1 card to summon Jet Synchron from the GY, then link into Linkuriboh. -Use Linkuriboh and Marcher to Summon Reprodocus. Use its effect to make Linkross a Winged Beast. -Link Summon Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty with Reprodocus and Linkross -Tribute the other Link Token to summon Linkuriboh, then use it and Accel Synchron to summon Union Carrier. -Use Union Carrier's effect to equip Mist Valley Thunderbird to Simorgh. -Set or activate a card to protect Mist Valley Thunderbird from destruction in battle, if you have one. -End your turn, and use Simorgh's effect to Summon Mist Valley Apex Avian. At this point, you will be able to negate anything once per chain, and if you have Raregold Armor or a similar card your Mist Valley Thunderbird will be protected from attacks. Full Deck Breakdown: Deep Sea Diva x3, Tour Guide from the Underworld x2, Sangan x3, Righty Driver x3, Draconnet x3: Used to summon Halqifibrax, start the combo. Crusadia Arboria x1, Lefty Driver x1, Guardragon Justicia x1: Needed for Snagan, Righty Driver, Draconnet Mecha Phantom Beast O-Lion x1, Jet Synchron x2, Mist Valley Thunderbird x1, Mist Valley Apex Avian x1: Needed for combo, Jet Synchron is at 2 because otherwise drawing it would destroy the combo. Raregold Armor x3, Armory Call x3, Vengeful Bog Spirit x3, Red Screen x3, Stumbling x3, Wall of Revealing Light x1: These cards are extremely helpful in protecting Mist Valley Thunderbird after it has been Summoned to the field. Prohibition x3: Useful for preventing Ash Blossom or Nibiru from wrecking the strategy. Called by the Grave x3: Used to counter Ash Blossom and Effect Veiler. Extra Deck: Akashic Magician, Salamangreat Almiraj x1: Used with Sangan or Tour Guide to enable link summons with Arboria. Crystron Halqifibrax x2, Linkross x2, Martial Metal Marcher x2, Accel Synchron x1, Linkuriboh x1: These cards are needed for the combo. Halqifibrax, Linkross, and Marcher are at 2 so you can restart the combo if you run into Ash Blossom or Nibiru. The extras can be replaced if necessary. I:P Masquerena x1, Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax x1: These cards are good to have for later game (turns 2+) summons. Avramax in particular is good for locking down attacks. Side deck: Nibiru the Primal Being x3: Good for stopping opposing combos, if forced to go second. Dark Ruler No More: This is one of the best cards for negating opponent's cards that would threaten the combo. Lightning Storm x3: To break boards with troublesome cards and/or bait cards like Savage Dragon or Dragoon. Infinite Impermanence x3: To negate opponent's monsters or bait their negation effects. Also good to stop Spells/Traps. Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring x3: Good for stopping combo decks before they start.

deck_excerpt: The Subterror Guru deck with several floodgates and mystic mine to definitively take the control of the game.
deck_description: This deck aims to explote the underrated quality of the subterror guru control decks: Their inmunity to the most played floodgates in the game.  By combining the Subterror Guru stringent strategy with the obvious stringency of floodgates, you can arise the highest level of control ever imagined in the game. Playing there can be only one at 3 and Gozen Match at 2, you can lock your oponent out of all the combos and strategies that imply monsters of the same type or different atributes. Furthermore the deck is designed to adapt the strategy to the oponent's deck by removing from the main deck the floodgate which isn't useful against an archetype (i.e: Playing against slamangreat you should remove gozen match as all the Salamangreat monsters are fire type, so the card is basically a "brick") and introducing in the main deck nteresting cards for a control deck such as Ash Blossom, Crackdown, Super Polymerization or Skill drain. You can even introduce 2 evenly matched in case of going second, which might be a weakness of the deck if you don't control the tempo porperly.  Furthermore you play 2 copies of mystic mine (+ terraforming + set rotation) that might slow the game enough to help you to take control of the game in situations in which you don't draw the Subterror Guru (which is one of the main problems that could arise when playing this archetype).  And last, but not least, I have incorporated a card I consider hardly underrated by the competitive comunity that is Witch's Strike, with a lot of potential in a format in which the negations are so extended. If activated and resolved, you have many chances to win the duel.

deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX turbo strategy: More consistency and more punch.
deck_description: This deck is a superconsistent and really competitive version of the powerfull Blue-Eyes Chaos Max strategy with the very boss monster, the Blue-Eyes Chaos Max dragon and his little brother the Blue-Eyes Chaos dragon that together look for really quick OTKs with different win conditions gathered in the definite Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX deck profile.  The main idea of the deck is summoning as quick as possible a Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX dragon and a Blue-Eyes Chaos dragon to attack and make OTKs without worrying about possible rival responses due to the inherent protection of these monsters which makes them something really hard to deal with and with almost no response in the meta strategies as the high attack and their extremely powerfull defense (obvously due to their effect, not the defense stat which is 0 in both ritual monsters) forces your rival to go for very specific plays to remove them from the field: They cannot be destroyed by card effects... and they cannot be targeted!!!  Even though it is difficult to go through their defense, it is possible that your rival manages to get a response to the presence of these monsters on the field... However, this deck profile presents 5 cards (2 x solemn strike and 3 x The Ultimate creature of destruction). The Ultimate Creature of destruction makes a Blue-Eyes monster you control totally immune to any card effect and destruction by battle and the Solemn Strike can be used to avoid special summons that might cause you problems or monster effects that might become an incovenient such as the Borreload Dragon effect or the Topologic Zeroboros.  Last but not least, this deck profile is not limited to the main deck monsters and effects, the 3 copies of Number 97: Draglubion give you acces to all the other Number dragon monsters in the extra deck with amazing effects and strategies to look for the OTK in case that the main strategy of the deck doesn't work.

deck_excerpt: A very consistent Plunder Patroll Deck
deck_description:
1. This Deck is very consistent with terraforming, upstart, salvage and 3 pot of desires, so it is nearly impossible to brick that hard
  2. the effects of your plunder patroll cards will resolve if u discard them
  3. Unlike other decks you don´t have to go first or second, it is possible to play either way, but going first is often the better option
  4. Make sure you already played everything "not plunder patroll monster" before you activate whitebeard and goldenhairs effect, because they force you to special summon plunder patrolls
  5. With Whitebeards effect in GY you always want to special Redbeard, unless you already have one on the board, so you can combo in your opponents turn
  6. Goldenhairs special summon effects, from hand or GY, are two seperatet effects, so for example if you got a goldenhair in your hand and one in your GY, you can special both of them for a blackbeard or moerk
  7. You mainly combo in your opponents turn with red,white and/or blackbeard and with Plunder Patroll Booty you can secure the attribute you need for moerk,brann or lys, also it is Monster reborn for your plunder patrolls, here revive the ship you need or red/whitebeard to extend your combo
  8. The Emblem is a very powerful card it can extend your combo by sending it to the GY or it protects your most important ship
  9. Ship shape ships shipping is a poly, but most of the time you want to dicard it to search a plunder patroll card, because light is a very common attribute and with Plunder Patroll Booty you can secure the light attribute for lys
  10. Nibiru and cosmos cyclone can be swapped; if you ar playing against a combo deck you want to have nibiru and against a controll heavy deck you will need the cyclone
  11. Called by the grave is a tool to secure your boats a little bit
For variatons you can swap a silent angler for antoher kaiju or you can swap a salvage,silent angler and the kaiju for 3 ash,ghost or dd crows or whatever you need, but this will reduce your consistency side deck choices are very individual but I recommend these aswell as Phantazmei,solemn judgement or sphere mode of Ra I also put necroquip prism in the side deck, it is a really interesting card for this deck which can extend your combo a lot, but its very specific and bricks often   This is the first deck I publish here, so sorry for false spelling and please give me feedback and tell me your experiences with my deck if you played it

deck_name: HERO! The return of Avian and Burstinatrix!
deck_excerpt: Avian and Burstinatrix are back, and they want to smack monsters!
deck_description: Just a simple HERO deck, this one focusing on fusion summoning Elemental HERO Grandmerge and Evil HERO Inferno Wing!  The main deck consist of the usual HERO goodstuff plus Avian and Burstinatrix. I use two Polys since the ideal stuff is to summon both Sunriser and Grandmerge. I also included a limited Plasma and Dark Law package for when you're required to go first, but make no mistake, this is a going-second beatdown strategy. There's only one of Adusted and Dark Calling each, but I feel that's enough given how easily searchable is.  It lacks in hand traps but makes up for it with plenty of S/T removal for floodgates and Called by the Grave for opposing hand traps since what you want is to get your combo through and not necessarily stop the opponent's.  The Extra Deck is where the real meat is. Our most important card is Xtra HERO Infernal Devicer, who will fetch our vanillas. Grandmerge and Inferno Wing will be our main beatsticks, usually paired with Sunriser. Once Grandmerge destroys a monster, you will tag out to Chaos (be wary of the level restriction!!). I chose Chaos as my prefered tag-out target given his useful negate, but you could make an argument fot not really needing it at that point. To be completely honest with you, I just like Chaos. You could also summon him with Poly or Miracle (yes, you can) given the right situation.  The rest is just more HERO goodstuff: Dark Law because Dark Law, Blast for S/T, Bane for an alternative Dark Calling summon, Absolute Zero/Acid combo for board wipe, Trinity for even more damage, and the rest of the Xtras for more combo and damage.  Lastly, the Side Deck is just "other things you can use" rather than an actually functional Side. Special attention to Nebula Neos who can also be summoned with Grandmerge and possibly give you some really sweet draw power.  If what you want is an actual Side Deck, just think of the usual: hand traps, Kaijus, etc.

deck_excerpt: For Destiny HERO lovers who want to use Dominance and D - Tactics in a somewhat viable deck
deck_description: I absolutely love Destiny HEROs and the cards that came out for them in Dark Neostorm but nobody plays the cards except for Fusion Destiny. The main focus of the deck is to turbo out Destiny HERO - Dominance with D - Tactics on the field in order to banish your opponents cards and bring all the D - Boys back. The main combo requires either Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio or Lonefire Blossom in your hand with another monster to discard (without having Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra in your hand since it turns off your combo). Normal summon either of the monsters, (Lonefire gets Scorpio from deck by tributing itself) use Scorpio's effect by discarding the monster in your hand (dont discard Destiny HERO - Plasma, Elemental HERO Honest Neos, or Vision HERO Faris unless you need to since their effect can be useful) to special summon Cobra from your deck. Activate Cobra's effect to add Fusion Destiny to your hand. Link summon Predaplant Verte Anaconda right after using Cobra and Scorpio. It is important to do this before activating Fusion Destiny since it locks you into dark HEROs for the rest of the turn. Hold off until using Anaconda's effect till the end of your turn. At this point, after summoning Anaconda, you can use Fusion Destiny to make Dominance. The material you use for Dominance depends on your hand but the best targets to use are Destiny HERO - Malicious, Destiny HERO - Dreadmaster, and Destiny HERO - Drawhand. Malicious is an excellent extender as all HERO players know and Dreadmaster is there for the D - Tactics combo. The reason I choose Drawhand instead of Destiny HERO - Disk Commander as the 3rd is because if your opponent destroys your Dominance right away you can't use it's floating effect to summon the D - Boys back from the grave if you have Disk Commander (and no extra D - HEROS) since he cant be summoned from the grave the turn he is sent there. You need 3 valid targets in your grave to trigger Dominance's floating effect. If you have Allure Of Darkness or Destiny Draw with a Destiny HERO in your hand, use Dominance's sorting effect on your deck before using them to try and get what you need on the top. The best targets, if you don't already have them in your hand, are D - Tactics, Mask Change, and Honest Neos. Other good cards are Plasma and Faris if you have the material to use them. If you have Mask Change you can either special summon Malicious and use it on him to make Masked HERO Dark Law or set it to use it on Drawhand on your opponent's turn. If you have Faris you can use their effect to place Vison HERO Increase in the spell/trap zone, tribute Faris, special summon itself to special summon Vision Hero Vyon from the deck. Use Vyon's effect to send Elemental HERO Shadow Mist to the grave (if you haven't already this turn) using Shadow Mist's effect to add Plasma, or whatever else you need. you can then special summon Malcious and tribute Malicious, Increase, and Vyon for Plasma. If you are finished with all your other plays you can then use Anaconda's effect to send a different copy of Fusion Destiny from your deck to the graveyard to special summon Destiny HERO - Dystopia. The materials you want to use now are Destiny HERO - Dynatag and Disk Commander. If you don't have D - Tactics set you can use Dynatag's effect to banish itself to give Dystopia 1000 atk damage, enabling it's quick effect pop effect. You want to target either Drawhand or Destiny HERO - Celestial in your graveyard for it's burn effect on summon to do 1600 effect damage. Your end board will most likely be Anaconda/Dominance/Dystopia with the possibility of having Plasma or Dark Law on top of that. Pretty much a board of a Drident/Skill Drain/Macro Cosmos + 1 hand rip if they search. During the standby phase use D - Tactics to boost your dude's attack points. The fun part is when your opponent destroys Dominance or it gets destroyed at the opponent's end phase by Fusion Destiny's effect. If your opponent destroys it before Dystopia dies then you want to summon Dreadmaster, Disk commander, and 1 other Destiny HERO (Normally Malicious if you used Dynatag/Drawhand's effects and banished them already) activating Disk Commander's effect to draw 2. If your opponent does not destroy Dominance or Dystopia dies first, then you want to summon Dystopia instead of the other Destiny HERO and use it's effect to burn your opponent again. When you summon Dreadmaster (or Dystopia) off of Dominance's floating effect on their turn while D - Tactics is on your field you can banish a card from either their hand (random), field, or graveyard. The cool thing about Dreadmaster is that the turn he is summoned, Destiny HEROs cannot be destroyed by battle or card effect AND you don't take battle damage from them, protecting your cards to set up for the next turn, guaranteeing you at least 3 monsters if your opponent has no other ways to get rid of them. What you can do from then on is summon Xtra HERO Cross Crusader using Disk Commander and Malicious/Dreadmaster/another hero in your hand as material to bring back Dystopia/Dominance from the graveyard, banishing ANOTHER opponent's card with D - Tactics. If you summon Dystopia again you could burn your opponent again up to 4800 damage over the two of your turns. The extra deck isn't super strict. 2 Dominance and Dystopia just in case. Masked HERO Anki and Vision HERO Trinity as OTK tech cards. 2 Dark law standard. Destiny HERO - Dangerous is there as a polymerization play as an extender or a third Fusion Destiny target if you run out of Destiny HEROs in the deck haha (this is actually a serious problem stop laughing). Xtra HERO Dread Decimator and Xtra HERO Wonder Driver are standard. 2 Cross Crusader pretty standard. Cross-Sheep is not necessary at all, just had extra space and its a nice card with Elemental HERO Stratos and Shadow Mist, activating their effects from the grave. Anaconda is really the only necessary expensive card in the deck. You need one copy in order to do the combo. I guess you could do without it and just use the Scorpio and Cobra for Cross-Sheep or material for Plasma (or Destiny HERO - Dogma if you are feeling extra spicy). The side deck is just additional draw power/Destiny End Dragoon in case you want to use him instead of one of the other 2 monsters going second. Overall this is a nice approach to the normally cookie cutter HERO standard strategy that everyone uses (myself included...). It is relatively budget; with the exception of the Vision HERO engine and Anaconda it is less than 50 dollars. Deck is about 135 dollars. Vision HEROS + Anaconda is about 91 dollars. 135 - 91 = 43 dollars. Pretty cheap huh? I was thinking about making a bigger deck since the deck runs out of resources but it hurts the chance of finding D - Tactics. Thank you for checking out my deck profile. I will probably make a similar/updated version of this deck in the near future.

deck_excerpt: My version of Plunder Patroll that I will be using at my locals until the next banlist will drop!
deck_description: Ever since the plunder payroll card where announced I was hyped and I fell in love with the pirates from the start and I became even more invested after the support from Eternity Code dropped. This decklist will probably need an update in a few weeks because I expect Konami to ban cards like Linkross or o-lion.   Ratios: I want to explain some of the ratios of my cards because they are a bit different from the profiles I have seen online. Plunder Patroll Monsters: like many I decided to max out all the plunder payroll monster cards because it is very important to have about 2 Plunder Patrolls in your starting hand 3x Danger! Mothman: I decided to play 3 Mothman and no other dangers because he is simply the best danger for the deck, he is a level 4 and if your opponents has to draw and discard it can actually be beneficial if he discards a monster with a dark, light or fire attribute so you can use Blackbeard, the Plunder Patroll Captain first turn. Only 2 Plunder Patroll Shipshape Ships Shipping and Plunder Patroll Booty: I decided to cut these 2 down because I ended up bricking a lot with them. I would only max out shipshape if I could play Magicians souls but sadly I only have 1 and I don't want to buy more :D 3x Salvage: I saw a lot of people playing 2 but I think this card is really important for the deck and I want to see it as much as possible because I always want to have plunder cards in my hand before I end my turn. no desires, 1 Pot of Avarice: I would play desires but I wanted to keep this deck at 40 cards and I feel like all the other cards are very important for my strategy and I think 1 avarice can really help you out if you top deck it. I will probably put it back in my next list but I decided to to this one without desires. Extra Deck Plunders: I saw a lot of people running 3 of every Plunder Patroll card in their extra deck. I get that you always need them to summon out your monsters on your opponents turn but I don't think you need to max out all of them. In fact I used to run only 1 of each but I decided to play 2 Moerk and Lys because they are the most important Extra deck plunders in my opinion. They both have really good effects and Moerk is also dark which is a pretty popular attribute. The reason why I don't want to play too many plunders in my extra deck because of 2 reasons: 1. The main combo of my strategy takes too much extra deck space and 2. there are plenty of options to recycle your ED monsters from the grave either with Booty, Avarice or Daigusto Emeral   Strategy/Main Combo: The Strategy of this deck focuses around 1 Main combo with Crystron Halqifibrax: Ideally you have a whitebeard, the Plunder Patroll Helm and another monster to make Halqifibrax. use Halq effect to summon Mecha Phantom Beast o-lion from your deck. Link halqifibrax into Linkross and summon 2 Tokens. Use 1 token and o-lion to synchro summon Martial Metal Marcher. Chain link 1 Material Metal, Chain link 2 o-lion. Then you can synchro summon Herald of the Arc light with Marcher and the lvl 1 token. be careful before you summon Herald because any monster you will send from hand or deck to the GY will be banished instead after he is on the field. Then you can synchro summon Cyberse Quantum Dragon with the lvl 3 token from o-lion and whitebeard. Now you can trigger Whitebeards effect to summon out another plunder patroll from your deck. After that you will be locked into plunder patrolls but you can still summon Blackbeard, the Plunder Patroll Captain using that plunder patroll monster and linkross as link material.

deck_excerpt: Inspired by Dito7's previous Red Archfiend deck, I just substituted some cards.
deck_description: Red Resonator is a really important card in this deck, normal summon Red Resonator to special summon a level 4 fiend monster from your hand. (Such as Red Sprinter, Red Familiar, Performage Hat Tricker, etc.) You will then be able to synchro summon Red Rising Dragon from your Extra Deck. By using Red Rising Dragon's effect you'll be able to special summon Red Resonator from the GY and use Red Resonator's special effect of targeting a monster on the field to gain LP equal to the monster's ATK.  You can then synchro summon for Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend.  Keep repeating this process and you'll have multiple synchro monsters on the field. Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss is a good card to synchro summon for, use something like Synkron Resonator or Chain Resonator to synchro summon it with Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend. Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss can use it's effect of negating your opponent's face up card once per turn. Using Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Bane's effect of tributing 1 monster to special summon 1 "Red Dragon Archfiend" monster from the GY is a must-do if you want many synchro monsters on the field.  Pretty fun deck, not too competitive.

deck_description: This deck is versatile, and doesn't really care if it goes first or second.  General plays:  Photon Vanisher + another level 4 monster -> Starleige Photon Blast. you want to use vanishers effect to special summon it and draw a Galaxy-eyes photon dragon, then summon Photon blast to special summon photon dragon. Photon blast also serves as protection for your other monsters and can special summon galaxy-eyes photon dragon from your gy or banished zone, and if you can attach Photon Orbital, Photon blast will protect itself.  Situations:  Opening play on an empty board.  Starleige Photon Blast Dragon: will protect your other monsters from card effects and can special summon galaxy eyes photon dragon.  Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord: will be able to negate a monster effect, and serves as a draw engine.  Galaxy-eyes solflare: you can use photon lord to add galaxy-eyes photon dragon and have fuel for solflare to pop a special summon, disrupting your opponent. (look for key targets like tuners, link monsters ect)  Opening turn and the opponent has played  Galaxy-eyes full armor photon dragon will be able to destroy any face up card by using its effect, also the 4000 attack is good enough to deal with most monsters.  Galaxy-Eyes cipher blade dragon will deal with pesky face downs that you don't want to trigger.  Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon dragon, if you just need to negate all monster effects on board. pretty useful and can OTK with a combo that we will get to later.  Neo Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon, basically if you need to just negate all effects on the board and you need something that's beefy, 4500 attack base and will indefinitely negate all effects on the board. if you get the option or are just able to, try summoning him first then your other monsters as to keep those effects.  Big damage Combos  Number 62: Galaxy-Eyes Prime Photon Dragon (has Galaxy-Eyes photon dragon and Galaxy-eyes afterglow as matierial) + other Xyz monsters. if you have this card and another Xyz monster, and you know its safe to attack, attack with number 62, activate its effect and remove afterglow as material, number 62 will gain attack equal to all the added up ranks of Xyz monsters on your field x200 (if you have 2 lvl 8 Xyz that will equal 8+8=16 x 200 = 3200) and then activate Afterglows effect, and since its activated during the damage step all number monsters have their attack doubled (in the case previously 4000+3200 = 7200 x 2 = 14400.)  Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon + Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon. This is pretty simple, at the start of your damage step, if you know its safe to attack, activate number 107's effect by removing afterglow as its material, you negate all monster effects on board and since its afterglow and you did this during the damage step number 107's attack will be 6000 and it will be able to attack twice.

deck_description:
So I've seen couple of YT videos around this and I have to say that almost every single one just sucks. They either have Uria in them (a monster completely useless in current format) or not enough "anti-meta" cards to slow down the opponents. (and then there's cemooo who didnt even put the field spell which protects them and gives you a +2 draw)
In this deck profile I tried to balance the Anti-meta aspect with turboing out Raviel and Hamon. Hamon for the defense protection and skyfire negate, Raviel just because we need 2 different sacred beast to negate opp. monster effects with Sacred Beast awakening.
In side deck I put the otk cards (Raviel Scrapper + Uria and Dimension Fusion Destruction) and Mystic Mine stoppers (Mystical Space Typhoon + Set Rotation), and boss monster killers (Kaiju + Swords of Concealing Light)
In the extra deck I only put 1 Armitlye because in the future there will be an archetype called Dragma that will require you to send card from extra deck to GY, so if we only have 1 extra deck monster your opponent cant really play. (and we don't really need more then 1 Armityle)

deck_excerpt: Will most likely not be legal in the TCG ever, but the combo was too cool not to share.
deck_description:
Not legal combo which puts Dragun of Red-Eyes alongside Apollousa with 2 negates before you use your HERO fusions. It's crazy bricky, but just seemed like too much fun, so I had to share it. There are a bunch of ways into the combo, it is still Isolde - Halqifibrax turbo. The combo is as follows
  1. Normal summon Armageddon Knight, send Malicious.
  2. Banish Malicious, special Malicious from the deck.
  3. Link into Isolde, add 1 HERO to your hand.
  4. Isolde effect sends Sword of Deep-Seated to the GY to special summon Grappler angler.
  5. Use Needlefibre/Linkross to summon 2 tokens and Red Rose Dragon
  6. Synchro your non-links into Garden Rose Maiden
  7. Red Rose effect specials White Rose Dragon from the deck.
  8. Link Rose Maiden and the link into Cross-Sheep.
  9. Banish Garden Rose Maiden, special summon Red Rose Dragon
  10. Link the Rose Dragons into Pisty and Elpy pointing at each other
  11. Special Summon Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon
  12. REDMD Effect, Special Summon White Rose Dragon
  13. Link Guardragons into Romulus, add Divine Lance
  14. Equip Divine Lance, special summon Phalanx
  15. Synchro Phalanx and White Rose Dragon into Muddy Mudragon.
  16. Muddy Muddragon Effect, Fusion Summon Dragun of Red-Eyes by fusing it (as Dark Magician) with a Dragon effect monster (this depowered Dragun is still a negate with good protection).
  17. Cross-Sheep Effect, ss Armaggeddon Knight
  18. Knight sends Shadow-Mist, adding Faris (Isolde guarantees Faris hits the field.)
  19. Make Apollousa before you Faris.
  20. Use fusion spells and Mask Change for fun and profit.

deck_excerpt: A modern version of Maykashi SABT Mill, which uses the newer Mayakashi support as combo extenders and as a backup plan.
deck_description: This decklist is based on a 2018 list, which I can't find now. I've edited the deck so that it uses Yuki-Musume and Yuki-Onna 4, and I made space by trimming Gozuki and some Link plays I didn't really find too useful. I also extended the second round of the Mayakashi ladder, so that it has better reach against abnormal deck counts, as well as giving it more fuel in case it has to fight conventionally. This comes at the cost of some toolbox space, but this deck is pretty committed to its game plan anyway.  Play lines all revolve around finding a way to get Dakki, 2 Level 1 material, and Bone Tower onto the field. Common lines almost always involve Hajun somehow, since he's a one-card trigger for the ladder. Yuki-Musume adds material and allows a send of Mezuki to the GY from Deck, and Uni-Zombie is of course very good for getting Bone Tower out of the deck. Hands without Bone Tower access can still attempt to play the game as a normal Mayakashi deck, and the final Extra Deck slot has a Borrelsword just in case.

The only downside to this combo is that you are not allowed to attack directly so never use it if the opponent does not have a monster.

deck_name: Orcust Deck 2020 July vs ALL META

deck_description: I've been testing with Infernoids for a bit, I really like this deck because it can surprisingly kill your opponent turn 2 if you wipe their board and link climb using cards that allow you to mill your deck like Monster Gate and Reasoning. A cool combo I came up with that I think is really good is with the Fire True King, you can use his effect to pop 2 fire monsters in your hand to special summon himself and banish an opponent's monster which is pretty sick. Sending Infernoids as cost from your hand to grave via Agnimazud isn't really a cost because you don't go neg since Infernoids can be special summoned from your graveyard anyway. Infernoid Imagination is also an insane going second card, allowing you to send basically all of your Infernoid monsters from deck to grave to special summon Infernoid Tierra and send all 3 copies of Elder Entity N'tss and using their effects to pop 3 cards on the field. You can also pop Nine-Tailed Fox using Agnimazud and it will generate 2 tokens. I know its not that consistent because its a two card combo that isn't searchable by any means, but its a cool tech I liked when testing. I've surprisingly beaten a lot of meta decks in testing with this deck. You just have to go second and bait out their negates with your lesser powerful interruption cards and then blow them out with Evenly Matched or Infernoid Imagination. I hope you guys enjoy and see you next time!

deck_excerpt: Somewhat Competitive Megalith build with Nekroz of Unicore
deck_description:
Your main goal with this deck is to get Megalith Phul on the field with materials to make Bethor on your opponent's turn to destroy their board. Your other objective is to get Unicore on field. You can get the Phul on board quite easily since you are running a ton of searchers. I can't stress it enough that getting Phul on the board is your #1 objective. Unicore is just the icing on the cake. But if you open a way to get Unicore + Kaleidoscope + Either Ophiel, Phul or one of the big Megaliths you can use Kaleidoscope to make Unicore, sending Herald of the Arclight, then using Herald Of the Arclight's effect to grab the missing combo piece. After turn one, you pretty much just keep setting up Phul to make Bethor, not allowing your opponent to get a hold on the game and slowly poke away at their lifepoints. PROS
  • It's Consistent. Like I said, you are running so many searchers that there are almost always multiple ways to get the cards you need.
  • A well placed summon of Bethor can just completely shut down a lot of decks.
  • It's extremely cheap. All of the Megalith cards are 15 cents or less, and the most expensive cards are Arclight ($3) and Chalislime ($3) and Manju ($4)
CONS
  • It is extremely fragile at the Phul resolution on your opponent's turn. It is easily stopped by an Imperm or ash, and at that point you just have a blue boy on field, and maybe a Unicore.
  • Nuking your opponent's board is cool, but there is a reason why Raigeki is not played in every deck today. Most meta decks can play through this, a lot like how they can play through Nibiru.

deck_excerpt: Jowgen Spellbook Control with new Dragma synergies with both be Light Spellcaster monsters. A loopable destruction protection for jowgen.
deck_description:
I found that most people would be countering the one card winda by siding Cyber Dragon Nova and Mechaba, when I realize that Jowgen the spiritualist just says no to all special summons, and that is the point of this deck. With the added protection from Spellbook of Fate and the new Dragma Punishment, it makes jowgen control more better and consistent. All the small dragma monsters are lv4 light spellcaster which is perfect for target for Downbeat to special jowgen straight from the deck! The spellbook portion is only to engine your card advantage and fuel fate. Deck space is tight so we run only 2 Spellbook Magician of Prophecy as this card is searchable easily by Spellbook of Secrets. Spellbook of Life is an additional extender and can be use to link climb as you can don't have to banish a monster that has a level, but the usual target is either jowgen or magicians' souls. Grand Spellbook Tower was way more useful than I thought as it would help you in the grind game AND if your opponent is going second, 8/10 times, they want to lightning storm your backrow as say you have dragma punishment facedown to protect your cards and forgetting the tower has a graveyard effect to special summon a monster from your deck. The Dragma portion allows the setup for protection and not usually to use up your normal summon. Adin is convenient that has 1000 atk to link into Almiraj which would back your other Dragma special summons live. Ecclesia in most decks searches Fleur but in this instance we want to to search Dragma punishment to set as a backrow. Fleur is of course a target for magicians' souls and a monster negate when needed. Now the second main reason why this deck came was Dragma Punishment. Dragma punish can send an extra monster to pop a monster on the field with atk less then or equal to the monster sent. There is 3 cards usually you want to send with this:
  1. Ashen Dragon, for the end search of Fleur or special ecclesia for another search if you haven't
  2. N'tss, pop another card on the field
  3. Omega, to put back dragma punishment into the deck to be searched again
The only other card I see worthy talking about is Dark ruler No More, it gives the deck a go second option to combat those n-negate boards.
Write your deck strategy here...  Focus on Dark magician girl and the traps that let you summon/tribute her and dark magician easily.

deck_excerpt: Just by ritual summoning BLS alone, you'll be able to have Titanic Galaxy + Conductor Tyranno. Also BLS, Chaos Ruler, and the Draitrons can return fro
deck_description: Draitron is Impcantation on crack and super compatible with Black Luster Soldier, being lv1 light it means you can have Overtex for Pill using Super Soldier Synthesis to fetch it from deck. Combo depends on what you draw, it means you need practice on how to maximize the Draitron advantage (key point is Synthesis can summon BLS from GY like Draitron ritual and Synthesis needs lv1 light fodder in hand). So, the deck has to be carefully tweaked for its ratio and after countless of testing, I found this ratio are the best (subjective, means you can still tweak it to find the objectively best ratio/combination). Tutorial: https://bit.ly/30sLjuO Diviner is combo piece searchable from Benten. Cupid Volley is there as it is a lv1 light for Synthesis and another light fairy target for Benten while can mill Draitron/BLS/Overtex/Meteornis. Effect Veiler is lv1 light for Synthesis and can be fetched from Chaos Ruler for extra interruption. Meteornis Draitron can be recurred from GY, summon ritual from GY. Gateway to Chaos for BLS and super easy to have counter for ritual spell searching. Fafnir mostly as extra Nova for Draitron, can search Meteornis too. Extra deck: N'tss and Arc Light as Diviner target. Michael as lv7 (Diviner + 1 Draitron) removal and mills card like Cupid Volley. Reprodocus as fodder if we draw Tyranno. I:P Masquerena as another disruption if we dont have enough Draitron (I:P + Tyranno). Pros: Themed, kinda consistent, multiple disruption, has followup play, big body, and great going first or second. Cons: Multiple cards combo because it's ritual. Fragile to interruption.
