deck_excerpt: Come August this will be legal... for a little while at least.
deck_description: The deck that will be legal for, at the very least, half of August or so. I'm expecting a Linkross ban, but with Coronavirus this might be legal for longer. I initially built this combo (or at least the shell of it) for HEROES, on the basis of using Cross-Sheep to res Stratos to search Faris after finding fodder with Isolde. The problem with the combo in that shell was threefold - the deck had no follow-ups, couldn't play through hand traps, and had too many bricks and not enough space. Eldlich seems like a much better fit for the combo, since it solves those problems - it even ends on additional monsters, since I didn't feel as bad about running the Seyfert/Black Dragon/White Dragon engine over REDM. That means either more negates for Apollousa, or a lingering effect in the form of Abyss Dweller. There are some problems - you can mill bricks with Tuning and kill your own combo, for example. And it does still take 8 bricks to do the combo, meaning nearly a 1/4 of the deck are bricks (though soft ones you don't mind in your hand). Also, Dragoon summoned this way can't break boards, significantly reducing its utility. Still, you get 2-4 negates, plus a potential lingering effect from Abyss Dweller, and an Omni-negate on a great beatstick before you start dropping backrow, and if you get interrupted you should still be able to get some Eldlich stuff going most of the time.

deck_excerpt: Remove 4 cards from the opponent's hand before their turn, one of which will be returned during End Phase, and then remove 1 more on their turn using
deck_description: The Level 7 "Mermail"s (Abyssteus and Abyssmegalo) allow us to     "Deep Sea Minstrel", a new addition to the deck allows us to outplay 1 hand-trap per turn, including "Nibiru, the Primal Being", "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring" and "Infinite Impermanence". Setup "True King of All Calamities", or take a spin and negate a spell or trap with "Adamancipator Risen - Dragite". He also has the ability to proc the Atlantean cards' effects to gain 'searches', 'pops', or summons by discarding or when Special Summoned (and getting lucky with mills). With "Deep Sea Diva" coming off of the ban-list entirely (previously limited to 1), this allows us to consistently set up "Crystron Halqifibrax" - the card that has become Meta by allowing players to make Synchro plays since it's release, and allowing us to loop hands easier. This deck is entirely about destruction of the opponent and should be used at its full extent to do so, destroy cards on the field using "Atlantean Heavy Infantry" with "Mermail Abyssalacia" on the opponent's turn, "Ghost Ogre" also allows us to destroy cards. "Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince" allows us to send "Atlantean Dragoons", to search for "Atlantean Dragoons", thus allowing us to get 2 searches for the price of one, or sending "Atlantean Heavy Infantry" to destroy an opponent's card (Infantry targets so be careful what you try to upset). "Moulinglacia, the Elemental Lord" is the key to destroying your opponent's hand before they even have a chance to play, Special Summon him when you have 5 WATER monsters in the Graveyard to remove 2 cards from their hand. "Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys" when Synchro Summoned allows us to draw a card to extend with, and also allows us to XYZ Summon "True King of all Calamities", or destroy a card on the field while sending cards such as: ♦ "Mermail Abyssgunde" to Monster Reborn a "Mermail" monster from the Graveyard; ♦ or any "Atlantean" to combo farther. "Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier" is our 4th hand destruction card, and allowing us to Banish other cards from the Hand, Graveyard and Field (1 each). "Bujinki Ahashima" allows us to setup the "Bahamut Shark" "Toadally Awesome" giving us another out to "Nibiru, the Primal Being", or to Negate a card in general. YouTube has many fine combo tutorials, and my deck is just the beginning. Please enjoy using this deck. If you have any questions at all: ♦ you can find me on Discord @ Bound#0478; ♦ or Dueling Nexus as "Bound", if you are lucky enough to bump into me. I am happy to help. Bound (Ocean Man), signing out.

deck_name: Orcust Mekk-Knight Deck 2020 - NO Scrap/Buster/Halqifibrax BS
deck_excerpt: This Orcust Mekk-Knight deck is for all the big PP epic gamers that dont want to play Scrap/Buster/Haliqifbrax/Linkross and other BS. Legit Meta Deck!
deck_description:
I personally like decks, which build a good board very consistently and reliably with few means.
The current format with stupid combo decks and 1-card starters which take you completely out of the game is not for my taste.
That's why I chose Orcust. I find that this deck currently has the best matchup against T1 or T0 decks.
  The main idea of this deck is to setup a decent turn 1 board with additional plays in your opponents turn. I dont play s*** like Scrap Recycler and Halqifibrax, bc i dont want my turn to take 20 min and loose to NIBIRU! In order to make a consistent turn 1 board I decided to play Iblee (and cynet mining) instead of Scrap b***s***.
The idea behind it is to protect myself as much as possible from opposing handtraps so that I can ensure that my plays work. Iblee protects you from handtraps like: Nibiru, Phantazmay, PSI Gamma, Impermanence, and other (off meta) handtraps. For Ash, veiler, etc. you play Called by the grave. This covers most of the time 100% of meta handtraps. And you are not reliant on your NS, bc I play the Mekk-Knights. Legit this version of the deck is actually insanely consistent.
Some stats - (Out of 100 starting hands): 1. Full combo with protection against (most) Meta handtraps: 3 card combo

Iblee (or cynet mining), any mekk-knight purple/blue, any Orcust monster

  • 26 out of 100 hands - NUTTY!!!
2. Full combo without protection against handtraps: 2 card combo

Girsu, any mekk-knight purple/blue

  • 40 out of 100 hands
3. Standard orcust combo: 1 or 2 card combo

Girsu (or armageddon), grepher + knightmare, orcustrated return + orcust cards,  or like multiple ways to get orcust stuff in grave with 1 NS or 1 SS

  • 24 out of 100 hands
4. Dead hands

Sadge. BUT STILL Imperm, Called by the grave, Ash -> enough against s*** T3/rogue decks

  • 10 out of 100 hands - Thats INSANE!
  I can explain the card choices in more detail aswell as some combos, but then this would be too long. Can update if necessary!

deck_excerpt: Horus the Black Flame Dragon Deck with Waking the Dragon and Injection Fairy Lily
deck_description: I haven’t played Yu-Gi-Oh! In almost 16 years but I decided to try updating my October 2004 deck for fun.  This deck includes a lot of old cards from my October 2004 deck as well as some newer cards I think sound interesting.  Before I quit in October 2004, I had plans to put the Horus LV cards in my deck if I decided to keep playing so I put them in this deck.  The deck relies on the Horus cards as a major strategy but it also relies on Waking the Dragon to get powerful monsters out of the extra deck easily.  Of course, Injection Fairy Lily is also a major factor in the deck as she was in my 2004 deck and I’ve included two copies in the main deck and one in the side deck (she was limited in 2004).  I’ve also included Lullaby of Obedience in the side deck to maybe use in the second duel of the match in order to disrupt the opponent’s strategy.

deck_excerpt: Trying (and probably failing) to make Meklords  work.
deck_description: This is the First Deck I've built so any constructive criticism is welcomed, now for the deck.   While Meklords finally got some love with their new cards, they're still not really viable in the meta, but did get a little better. Meklord Astro Dragon Triskelia will be the main boss monster of the deck, being able to hit hard and hurt your opponent by stealing a monster from their extra deck, wtih the added benefit of being able to attack up to 3 monsters if one of the monsters its equipped with is a Synchro. I'd say the deck benefits most from going first, as it gives you a chance to set up negates without having to worry about your opponents board. The main prbolem is hand traps, as they more or less shutdown your opening play outside of Meklord Nucleus Infinity Core and Meklord Assembly. Depending on your hand you have several options: Option 1- Meklord Army Arsenal of Obbligato and Meklord Emperor Wisel are needed in your hand. Summon Obbligato and uses it effect to destroy itself and summon two Meklord Army monsters from your deck, this will proc Wisel's effect so you can summon it. Link your two Meklord army monsters into Union Carrier, and uses its effect to equip Wisel with Dragon Buster Destruction Sword. Now you've locked your opponent out of their extra deck and have a 3500 attack point monster on the field. If you have any traps in your hand be sure to set them for extra negates or stall and Wisel can also negate one Spell card per turn for another layer of defence. Your Graveyard is also set to be able to summon Triskelia. A downside is that Wisel is the only monster that can attack due to its effect. Option 2- This can be done as long as you start with Meklord Assembly in your hand and any Meklord Emperor. Using Meklord Assembly you can search for Nucleus if it's not already in your hand, otherwise searh for any Mekord that you need. Summon Nucleus and use its effect to add Meklord Control to your hand. Use Meklord Assembly's other effect to destroy Nucleus by sending  Meklord Control to the Graveyard to summon one of your Emperors from the deck, this will also proc the effect of whatever Meklord Emperor is in your hand as well. Summon the Emperor from your hand and a different one from your deck using the effect of Nucleus. Wisel is good here as it adds that extra layer of defence with its effect. but Meklord Emperor Granel could also work giving you a 4000 attack point monster and then using the other Emperor you can link into Linkuriboh as well. Granels attack is based off your LP so it may not be great later into the match or if you use Solemn Judgement next turn. Having Meklord Control in your Graveyard also helps your Meklords survive an effect or attack as well, since you can banish it to negate their destruction. Of course their a more opening options but these two are the ones I like using the most, and can shut down some opening plays. Going second is a little bit harder as you'll have a tougher time getting out your Meklords. To help going second Dark Ruler No More and Lightning Storm are pretty self explanatory, and Infinite Impermanence can help shutdown your opponents combos. Try and get Triskelia out as soon as possible if you can. The easiest way is through the use of Obbligato since it sends itself to the Graveyard and you can Link summon to send the others to the Graveyard.   While some of the Spells and Traps seem obvious a choice like Pulse Mines helps keep your Meklords alive and kicking forcing your opponent to have all their monsters in defence position. Link monsters do get round this and can cause a problem but both Solemn traps can help prevent your opponent getting any on the field. I did try Guard Mines as well but found it got very little use as to many effects are mutlitarget. Meklord Astro Extermination is a nice way to summon 3 of your Meklords from your Graveyard ignoring their summoning conditions, which is a nice way to get Triskelia and Meklord Astro Mekanikle on the field. If your opponent dose have Synchro on the field too, it has the added benefit of being able to get rid of that as well. Meklord Control can be used to boost one Meklord up to some high attack, and by banishing it from your Graveyard gives your Meklords some defence. Just remember it uses the original attack of Meklords you control, so Emperor Granel will contribute nothing to the total as an example, as its original attack is 0.   As for the Extra Deck I used what most other Meklord decks use. Number 27: Dreadnought Dreadnoid is an alternative way to get a strong monster out on your field, such as Super Quantal Mech King Great Magnus as it's able to disrupt your opponents board by returning one card to their deck every turn as long as it has 2+ materials. Superdimensional Robot Galaxy Destroyer is another way to get rid of your opponents Spells and Traps will boasting 5000 attack points, its a nice anaswer to Spell and Trap heavy decks. deck_excerpt: YUGIOH! Red Dragon Archfiend Deck July 2020 [TCG/OCG] - Master rule 2020
deck_description: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9qG_z5sCyl8

Yes, this is possibly the worst way to play toons. The main point of this deck is to play off how the older toon monsters are worded, where they don't actually need Toon World/Kingdom on the field to attack directly (in this case, Blue-Eyes Toon Dragon and Toon Dark Magician Girl). You have the basic searchers, Bookmark and Tables, because if this deck is going to do anything, you will need all the searching you can get. Rollback, because why not, it's pretty much the only Toon spell you have access to without Toon World. Also Briefcase, which only requires a toon monster, for some reason.  So, even though you don't need Toon World to attack directly, you do need it for the summon right? Wrong! Because Red-Eyes Toon Dragon and Toon Dark Magician both ignore summoning conditions, so you need those as quickly as possible, hence Black Stone and Insight. Levianeer and BLS, because I needed to fill space, same with Chaos Space.  Does this deck work? Theoretically, yes, but since you have basically a clunky mess with no Extra Deck (you can do whatever you want with that, it's not like you'll ever get to it), and since you don't have Toon World, you don't have Comic Hand, Page Turn, Mimicat, or any other good toon support, you will probably lose by turn 4.  So why did I make this deck? Because I like finding weird loopholes in old cards. So if you play this deck good luck, you will need it.
Somewhat budget toon deck.

deck_excerpt: Uses store-bought sets (Duel Devastator and both Machina Structure Decks) along with a few other cards to create a Machina Gadget deck with Rank 4 and
deck_description: This deck is all about discarding cards and bringing them out en masse, either for their own power or to be used as Xyz Material. The two heavy hitters are Boot-Up Admiral and Machina Citadel. Boot-Up is the easier of the two to bring out, as the Gadgets can easily be brought out by each other, and even from the graveyard thanks to cards like Pinpoint Guard. Citadel, meanwhile, is best brought out using Air Raider's effect. Machina Fortress is there as a reliable 2500 beatstick that is ridiculously easy to summon, and if it gets taken out, there's always Megaform to fall back on. The Gadgets exist mainly to either provide discard fodder or to be used as Xyz Material themselves. Fortress and Citadel can be brought out from the graveyard so cards like Twin Twisters and Fortress itself can discard them easily. Most of the Xyz Monsters are Rank 4, but there are a couple of Rank 8, as well as 1 Rank 7 (brought out by Fortress) and a couple Rank 5 (which is where Jumbo Drill comes in).  This is not a strictly meta deck, but I did not have the budget to get a bunch of Infinitrack cards.

deck_excerpt: Post Structure Deck. Run less brick and less convoluted combo cus it's linear, with King Calamity stun and Areadbhair + Savage negation. Has Dux as fo
deck_description: Competitive Structure Deck at last, but it comes with price (literally and figuratively). Dragunity combo is so convoluted unlike regular Dragon Link which is only a Romulus turbo. This deck made the combo easier to navigate and only needs basic understanding. All we need is Gae Dearg + 1 extender (but for King Calamity we need Couse, Remus, Phalanx in GY, Halq summons 1, so we need 2 of them in GY). Combo: https://bit.ly/39efLg1 Our main pieces are Dux (best starter with tuner in GY), Couse (lets us Barcha), Remus (extender and Ravine searcher, only use its GY eff after Halq), Ravine (dumper/searcher). The secondary pieces or extenders are Arma Gram (follow up play), Mystletainn (behaves like Dux but slightly worse), Legatus (our second Dux, play 2 cus we dont wanna draw multiple as it can be sarched by Gae Dearg if we draw Baby Roc), Phalanx (combo pieces for Savage/King Calamity), Baby Roc (combo pieces as Gae Dearg target, we need 2 and it equals to Legatus if we hard draw it), Glow (great spell but bad starter, only as combo pieces), Divine Lance (hopt like Glow, but is a great starter, we dont wanna draw double both this and Glow, so just run 1 copy of both), Monster Reborn (revives our boss monster), and lastly World Legacy Guardragon (fixing Pisty zone). The rest of it is just staple or as Crossout target while being great handtrap. Only 2 Cards of Consonance because the target is only a few (like Orcust+Return ratio), so run Upstart instead. 3 Impermanence cus Zexal everywhere. Extra Deck: Combo pieces. Ascalon as removal and floats, Coral Dragon as removal and easy to make, Vajrayana for beater and synchro climb, Borreload as non-target/non-destruction removal. Pros: Consistent, big monsters, multiple negations, King Calamity stun, have follow up play, big staple slot. Cons: Multiple cards combo, prone to handtrap (still can make 1 negation at least).

deck_excerpt: Link up using the power of Ignister A.I  Land, and create battle and card effect locks!
deck_description: The general idea of the deck is to use the archtypes field spell Ignister A.I land, which allows you to special summon an ignister of each attribute for free so long as you dont have any monsters in the main monster zone. This allows you to link up, use the effect again, and so on to generate the link 6 arrival ignister from only 2 cards!  Additionally, the other cards will allow for strategies such as using Cyberse Quantum Dragon, Cyberse Magician and Crusadia Avramax to create a field that cannot be targeted with card effects or battle due to the looping restrictions. This means that your opponent has to use kaiju effects or non-targeting removal to tackle the board you create!  Heres the bread and butter combo to create Arrival Ignister and Quantum Dragon opening up with Pikari and Achichi. From step 17 onwards you have a lot of options available depending on the opponents board, or what additional cards you have in hand to generate more resources on the field:  1: NS Pikari to search for Ignister A.I Land (If already in hand, search for A.I Reborn to extend)  2: Link Summon into Lingruiboh  3: Activate Ignister A.I Land  4:Activate Lands effect to SS Achichi  5: Active Achichis effect to search for Doyon  6: Link up into Cyberse Wicckid  7: Lands effect to SS Doyon at one of Wicckids arrows  8: Doyons effect to add Pikari to hand from GY  8: Banish Achichi to add Bururu to hand via Wicckids effect  9: Link up into Transcode Talker  10: Lands effect to SS Pikari anywhere but below Talkers down arrow (Because he was NS only this turn, and lands effect only restricts SS from land!)  11: Transcode Talkers Effect to SS Wicckid  13: Link all 3 into Dark Templar  14: Lands effect to SS Bururu to one of Templars Arrows  15: Templars effect to SS Doyon and Pikari  16: Synchro Summon Quantum Dragon using Bururu and Doyon  17: SS Doyon via Bururus effect  18: Link Summon Splash Mage with Doyon and Pikari  19: SS Pikari via Splash Mage  20: Link Pikari, Splash Mage and Dark Templar into your Link 6, 3k boss monster!

deck_name: deck the wicked avatar Belial - Marquis of Darkness,numeron
deck_description: https://youtu.be/MEgQnEmjnY4

This build mainly focuses on control of the field with the Orcust engine. I decided to throw the Cyber Dragon engine in because it gives you a good negate and Infinity allows you to suck up a lot of problem monsters. Here's some notes.
  • Scrap Recycler  are used to send either Jet Synchron, Wonder Wand, any Orcust monster that isn't Girsu, or Cyber Dragon Herz & Core to the grave to start plays. It plays a lot more of a role than I would have thought.
  • Girsu the Orcust Mekk-Knight is a good foolish burial for any Orcust monster and a free token if you don't control any other monsters. (which you can go into a Linkuriboh and get a Galatea off of just that!)
  • This deck is very graveyard focused so you have to watch out for Called By The Grave. But it gives you plenty of options to bounce back!
  • Your turn one board should be either a Galatea with Crescendo, a Dingirsu, Apollousa & Infinity, or Savage Dragon. Or a combination of any of them! You have a lot of options but should keep in mind that once you start banishing Orcusts from the graveyard, you're locked into DARK monster special summoning for the rest of the turn. So get that Infinity or Apollousa out while you can. Oh yeah, and AccessCode Talker is here because we need a big beatstick and he happens to be the best suited I feel with his card destruction effect which isn't once per turn. Was Topological Zeroboros, but he's really unneeded unless you're using Gizmek Orochi for more power. (Also watch out for Nachster, because it locks you into only MACHINE types as well.)
I will be honest this deck can get a little brick heavy if you're going first because of the higher level monsters, but 9/10 I've found myself with at least one decent play to make in order to keep myself alive. It's very fun to play and isn't too complicated to try out!

deck_excerpt: A pure Rokket deck featuring Topologics and a few Dark Dragon helpers!
deck_description: Ah yes, Rokkets. The gun dragons (Dra-gun, if you will). These guys are pretty relevant to the meta game, and are surprisingly easy to pick up! Basically, your normal strategy is going to involve targeting your Rokket monsters with various Link monster effects (namely Striker Dragon, Booster Dragon, and the family of Borrels), activate the Rokket monster's effect, then at the end of the turn, special summon a different Rokket from the deck! These guys' biggest strengths include their ability to swarm the field and their quick effects, allowing various forms of destruction and removal (My personal favorite being Shelrokket Dragon). Another strength being their swole Link-4 Borrel dads and their crazy Topologic uncles. Want mass removal? Topologics. Want interruptions and the best way to trigger a Rokket? Borrels. Now for the interesting part. Namely, how their greatest strength is their greatest weakness: Graveyard effects. These guys can get really hurt if your opponent activates Called by the Grave or Silent Graveyard, so plan accordingly. Borreload Savage Dragon can ease that problem, so plan ahead with this sweet deck. Remember to have fun!

deck_excerpt: A combo that uses Crystron Halqifibrax to bring out and protect an infinite negate Mist Valley lockdown.
deck_description: This is a combo deck that uses Crystron Halqifibrax and a card to discard to achieve an ending field of Mist Valley Apex Avian, Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty equipped with Mist Valley Thunderbird, and I:P Masquerena and Union Carrier ready to be made into Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. It is similar to my other deck that ends with the same Mist Valley lock, but with a longer combo and the addition of I:P Masquerena/Avramax to the end. The combo: -Summon Crystron Halqifibrax (With one of the starters listed in the next section), and use its effect to summon Mecha Phantom Beast O-Lion from the Deck. -Summon Linkross using Halqifibrax as material, and use its effect to get 2 Link Tokens. -Summon Martial Metal Marcher using O-Lion and 1 of the Link Tokens. Use O-Lion's effect to get a Mecha Phantom Beast token, and use Marcher's effect to summon O-Lion back from the GY. -Summon Accel Synchron using O-Lion and the Mecha Phantom Beast Token. Use its effect to send Jet Synchron to the GY and decrease its level by 1. -Summon Herald of the Arc Light using Marcher and the remaining Link Token. -Summon Primathmech Alembertian using Herald and Accel Synchron (which is level 4 by its effect). Use its effect to add Mathmech Nabla to your hand, and chain Herald's effect to add Advanced Ritual Art. -Use Alembertian's effect to Tribute itself and Summon Nabla from your hand. -Use Nabla's effect to tribute Linkross and Summon Mathmech Division from your Deck. -Summon Gallant Granite using Nabla and Division. Use its effect to detach either Mathmech and add Block Dragon to your hand. -Discard 1 card (not Advanced Ritual Art or Block Dragon) to Summon Jet Synchron from the GY. -Summon Reprodocus using Gallant Granite and Jet Synchron. -Banish Primathmech Alembertian, Mathmech Division, and Gallant Granite to summon Block Dragon to the zone Reprodocus points to. -Use Reprodocus' effect to make Block Dragon a Winged Beast. -Summon Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty using Reprodocus and Block Dragon. Use Block Dragon's effect to add Gigantes and The Rock Spirit to your hand. -Banish Block Dragon to summon Gigantes, and banish Reprodocus to summon The Rock Spirit. -Summon Number 60: Dugares the Timeless using Gigantes and The Rock Spirit. -Detach both materials from Dugares to summon Herald of the Arc Light from the GY. -Summon I:P Masquerena using Dugares and Herald. Use Herald's effect to add Devotee of Nephthys to your hand. -Use Advanced Ritual Art to send Guardragon Justicia to the GY to summon Devotee. Use Devotee's effect to summon Disciple of Nephthys from your Deck. -Summon Union Carrier using Devotee and Disciple of Nephthys. Use its effect to equip Mist Valley Thunderbird to Simorgh. -End your turn, and use Simorgh's effect to summon Mist Valley Apex Avian from your deck. -During your opponent's turn, summon Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax using I:P Masquerena and Union Carrier (with I:P Masquerena's effect). At this point, you should be able to negate as many of your opponent's effects as you want (with Apex Avian's effect), while Avramax's effect makes sure your opponent does not attack Thunderbird after it has benn Summoned. Deck breakdown: Main Deck: Deep Sea Diva x3, Sangan x3, Righty Driver x3, Rescue Rabbit x3, Draconnet x3: These are the starters used to summon Halqifibrax. Crusadia Arboria x1, Lefty Driver x1, Guardragon Justicia x3: These cards are summoned with the effects of the starters. Justicia is also needed in the deck for Advanced Ritual Art. Mecha Phantom Beast O-Lion x1, Jet Synchron x2, Mathmech Nabla x1, Mathmech Division x2, Block Dragon x1, Gigantes/The Rock Spirit x2, Advanced Ritual Art x1, Devotee of Nephthys x1, Disciple of Nephthys x2, Mist Valley Thunderbird x2, Mist Valley Apex Avian x2: These cards are needed for the combo (see above). All non-Mist Valley cards that have 2 included cannot be used unless they are in the Deck. Gigantes and The Rock Spirit are completely interchangeable, this deck list uses 1 of each but 2 of 1 of them is fine. I have 2 of each Mist Valley monster because it is nice to be able to summon a second Apex Avian at the end of the opponent's turn, and despite the numerous negation effects Mist Valley Thunderbird can sometimes be removed by quick-play spells like Cosmic Cyclone and Twin Twisters. Called by the Grave x3, Prohibition x3, Dark Ruler No More x3: These cards are used to protect the combo, Called by the Grave is mostly used to stop Ash Blossom and Effect Veiler, and Prohibition is able to prevent Ash Blossom (or Nibiru, if you also have Called by the Grave). Dark Ruler No More is a great card for removing any monster-based threats when forced to go second, and it can be discarded for Jet Synchron if you draw it going first. I plan to add Crossout Designator and cards to banish with it once it releases, but for now it is not included because this is a TCG deck. Extra Deck: Salamangreat Almiraj x1: This card is used with Sangan to eventually summon Crystron Halqifibrax. Crystron Halqifibrax x2, Linkross x1, Martial Metal Marcher x1, Accel Synchron x1, Herald of the Arc Light x1, Primathmech Alembertian x1, Gallant Granite x1, Reprodocus x1, Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty x1, Number 60: Dugares the Timeless x1, I:P Masquerena x1, Union Carrier x1: These cards are all part of the combo. Halqifibrax is at 2 in case you run into an Ash Blossom with nothing to counter it. Side Deck: Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring x3, Nibiru the Primal Being x3, Infinite Impermanence x3, Lightning Storm x3, Effect Veiler x2, Red Reboot x1: These cards are all used to stop combo decks that get to go first games 2 or 3, except Red Reboot which is a counter to Impermanence or whatever other traps my opponent may have. The side deck cards are subject to change based on what seems to frequently threaten the combo.

deck_excerpt: Neo-Spacians have a lot of new support but they still suck
deck_description: This Deck does legit nothing going first so you are blinding second with this deck. If you are taking this deck to locals, the main deck as shown below is probably fine. You should really try to fit in Dark Ruler No More or other cards that just stop your opponent's board going second. You really want cards in your hand rather than field presence in this deck since a lot of this archetype's cards restrict you to only Fusions or make you just not be able to Special Summon for the rest of the turn like what Neos Fusion does. That is why we are playing no Link/Xyz monsters and some heavy draw power. For the draw power, Three Tactical Talents is actually good, but the situation will rarely be there where this is active since if you are bringing Neos-Spacians to locals or a tournament, you are expecting that they are also playing decks that are just as bad. Generation Next is in the side deck since you aren't always going to have it live despite how good it is. You could play A Hero Lives to shotgun Prisma off the top and have Generation Next live, but it is a limited card resulting in it not being always there in your starting hand. You do have Performapal Popperup to get Generation Next live, but you kind of want to set the other spells/traps that you need face-down before activating Popperup so that you aren't burn't for like 5k due to its effect and Generation Next is a Quick-play Spell (For some apparent reason) so you can't activate it the turn you set it. There is literally no starting combo you can do with this deck since such a thing doesn't exist. But if you do get a Fusion on the field, you can equip it with Favorite Hero to get a monster with like almost 8k ATK if its a triple fusion, Flare Neos, or Air Neos since those bois have a grand amount of ATK. Also, at the start of the BP, if you don't have a Field Spell for Favorite Hero's ATK boost, the card lest you activate any field spell from the deck like Neo Space for more ATK and no shuffle away eff or Mystic Mine since this deck sucks. Extra Deck has the triple fusions since they are decent and their shuffle effects can be devastating to your opponent (and yourself too????) but they are very hard to get on the field. Brave Neos searches almost every spell/trap in your deck. Air Neos gains ATK equal to the difference in LP you will have from the Performapal Popperup burn. Grand Neos is just trying his best here and Flare Neos is a possible big beefy boi. No Links because of the stupid fusion restrictions on most of the spells/traps in the main deck.

deck_description: This Deck goes second to use the effect of Armityle the Chaos Phantasm - Phantom of Fury which banishes your opponent's board to summon og Armityle from your Extra Deck. Dark Ruler No More helps you get to this point since there is no way that you can do this deck's normal plays trough any negate at all. Your general play is to get Raviel, Hamon, and Uria in your hand, onto the field, or in the graveyard so that you can fuse into the Armityle retrain using Dimension Fusion Destruction. Cards like Dark Beckoning Beast, Chaos Summoning Beast, and Dark Summoning Beast help get the Sacred Beasts into your hand or onto the field with the help of Opening of the Spirit Gates of course. If you plan to activate Dimension Fusion Destruction and plan to fuse a Sacred Beast that you currently control away, you can Link it off into Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos since you can fuse by banishing from the grave too. Soldier of Chaos gets it effect to be untargetable and indestructibility from card effects since you used a level 7 or higher monster and it can be an out to Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon in the battle phase since Raviel, Hamon, Uria, and og Armityle still lose out to its ability to gain attack of the monster it's battling if it has a level. Soldier of Chaos  can gain 1500 ATK if it destroys a monster by battle so you can use it to attack into Crystal Wing and it wont be able to gain ATK since BLS is a link monster. Exodius, the Ultimate Forbidden Lord is material for a Rank 10 monster and is also a target for Magicians' Souls. Capshell a free draw and a target for Spirit Gates and Dark Beckoning Beast's extra normal summon. Relinquished Amina allows you to equip one of your opponent's monsters to it. This allows you to free up one of your opponent's zones to give them the Armityle retrain. Verte Andaconda is for your fusion spell. Pentestag is for your monsters doing piercing. Gustav Max and Liebe for more damage and field presence. Mannequin Cat and Crumble Logos are there for you get Infinite Impermanenced.  Reasoning and Foolish Burial for grave set-up. Evil Mind is a free draw or a search for Dimension Fusion Destruction if you go against something like Adamancipator(?). One Fallen Paradise since it is a dead card i you don't have any Sacred Beasts on the field. Hyper Blaze and Sacred Beast Awakening in the side deck for going first.

deck_excerpt: Numeron Eldlich deck for July 2020  (Also, I wanted to throw any JoJo fans here a bone!)
deck_description: This is a Numeron Eldlich deck I made recently. I actually got the idea to make it months ago, but I've been too lazy to post a deck profile. Anyways, this deck is named after Gold Experience Requiem, the most powerful Stand in JoJo's Bizzare Adventure: Vento Auero. So, between this and Golden Wind(https://ygoprodeck.com/golden-wind/), that's TWO Eldlich decks inspired by JoJo.   Anyways, you'd prefer to go first with this deck, but 9 hand traps and some go-second cards in the Side Deck mean that it can still pack a whallop if you don't, especially given the battle-related effects of the Rank 1 "Numeron Gate" monsters. Nonetheless, you'd prefer to go first and try to summon Utopic ZEXAL so your opponent will never arrive at the truth.   And before you ask...YES, that WAS a JoJo reference!

deck_excerpt: New Synchro Eldlich starter: Deskbot 003   DRAW 6 CARDS FROM 1 !?!?!
deck_description:
Eldlich, but you draw 4 or 6 and dump Eldlich before starting. Jet way:
  1. Normal Jet, Linkuriboh, Halq, Halq effect: Deskbot 001, Linkross (2 tokens), summon back Linkuriboh, use Linkuriboh + Linkross to make Borg Blocker.
  2. 001 + Borg Blocker to make Auroradon, 3 tokens, summon back 001, Auroradon effect, tribute itself and 1 Mecha Phantom Beast(MPB) token to summon O-lion.
  3. O-lion + MPB token to make T.G. Librarian, O-lion effect, 001 + Linkross token to make Formula, Formula + MPB token to make Accel Synchron.
  4. Accel + MPB token to make Borreload Savage, equip Auroradon.    Combo off with whatever you have left and/or drawn.
Deskbot 003 way:
  1. Normal oo3, summon 001, make Halq, summon O-lion, Linkross (2 tokens), make Metal Marcher, summon back either tuner, DO NOT use O-lions effect.
  2. Linkross + 1 other monster to make Borg Blocker, Auroradon, 3 MPB tokens, summon back 001, Auroradon effect: itself + one MPB token, summon O-lion.
  3. O-lion + MPB token to make T.G. Librarian, O-lion effect, 001 + Linkross token to make Formula, Formula + MPB token to make Accel Synchron.
  4. Use Accel's effect to dump Jet and increase level, summon Crocodragon, summon back Jet (preferably dump Eldlich), summon Ascension Sky Dragon.
  5. Chain 1 Sky dragon's effect, chain 2 Librarian's effect.      Combo off with whatever you have left and/or drawn.
